\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Darrick Lang pulled at the oar and scanned the night-shrouded cliffs overlooking the Dyre River, hoping he remained out of sight of the pirates they hunted. Of course, he would only know they\'92d been discovered after the initial attack, and the pirates weren\'92t known for their generosity toward Westmarch navy sailors. Especially ones who were hunting them pursuant to the King of Westmarch\'92s standing orders. The possibility of getting caught wasn\'92t a pleasant thought.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 The longboat sculled against the gentle current, but the prow cut so clean that the water didn\'92t slap against the low hull. Sentries posted up on the surrounding cliffs would raise the alarm if the longboat were seen or heard, and there would be absolute hell to pay for it. If that happened, Darrick was certain none of them would make it back to\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 waiting out in the Gulf of Westmarch. Captain Tollifer, the vessel\'92s master, was one of the sharpest naval commanders in all of Westmarch under the king\'92s command, and he\'92d have no problem shipping out if Darrick and his band didn\'92t return before dawn.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Bending his back and leaning forward, Darrick eased the oar from the water and spoke in a soft voice. \'93Easy, boys. Steady on, and we\'92ll make a go of this. We\'92ll be in and out before those damned pirates know we\'92ve come and gone.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If our luck holds,\'94 Mat Hu-Ring whispered beside Darrick.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ll take luck,\'94 Darrick replied. \'93Never had anything against it, and it seems you\'92ve always had plenty to spare.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92ve never been one to go a-courtin\'92 luck,\'94 Mat said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint4}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint4}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Never,\'94 Darrick agreed, feeling a little cocky in spite of the danger they were facing. \'93But I don\'92t find myself forgetting friends who have it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Is that why you brought me along on this little venture of yours?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick replied. \'93And as I got it toted, I saved your life the last time. I\'92m figuring you owe me one there.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat grinned in the darkness, and the white of his teeth split his dark face. Like Darrick, he wore lampblack to shadow his features and make him more a part of the night. But where Darrick had reddish hair and bronze skin, Mat had black hair and was nut brown.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Oh, but you\'92re up and bound to be pushin\'92 luck this night, aren\'92t you, my friend?\'94 Mat asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The fog is holding.\'94 Darrick nodded at the billowing silver-gray gusts that stayed low over the river. The wind and the water worked together tonight, and the fog rolled out to the sea. With the fog in the way, the distance seemed even farther. \'93Mayhap we can rely on the weather more than we have to rely on your luck.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93An\'92 if ye keep runnin\'92 yer mouths the way ye are,\'94 old Maldrin snarled in his gruff voice, \'93mayhap them guards what ain\'92t sleepin\'92 up there will hear ye and let go with some of them ambushes these damned pirates has got set up. Ye know people talkin\'92 carries easier over the water than on land.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick agreed. \'93An\'92 I know the sound don\'92t carry up to them cliffs from here. They\'92re a good forty feet above us, they are.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Stupid Hillsfar outlander,\'94 Maldrin growled. \'93Ye\'92re still wet behind the ears and runnin\'92 at the nose for carryin\'92 out this here kind of work. If\'92n ye ask me, ol\'92 Cap\'92n Tollifer ain\'92t quite plump off the bob these days.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93An\'92 there you have it then, Ship\'92s Mate Maldrin,\'94 Darrick said. \'93No one bloody asked you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A couple of the other men aboard the longboat laughed at the old mate\'92s expense. Although Maldrin had a reputation as a fierce sailor and warrior, the younger men on the{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint5}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint5}crew considered him somewhat of a mother hen and a worrywart.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The first mate was a short man but possessed shoulders almost an ax handle\'92s length across. He kept his gray-streaked beard cropped close. A horseshoe-shaped bald spot left him smooth on top but with plenty of hair on the sides and in back that he tied in a queue. Moisture from the river and the fog glistened on the tarred breeches and soaked the dark shirt.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick and the other men in the longboat were clad in similar fashion. All of them had wrapped their blades in spare bits of sailcloth to keep the moonshine and water from them. The Dyre River was fresh water, not the corrosive salt of the Gulf of Westmarch, but a sailor\'92s practices in the King\'92s Royal Navy were hard to put aside.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Insolent pup,\'94 Maldrin muttered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Ah, and you love me for it even as you decry it, Maldrin,\'94 Darrick said. \'93If you think you\'92re miserable company now, just think about how you\'92d have been if I\'92d up and bloody left you on board\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star.\plain \f2\fs24 I\'92m telling you, man, I don\'92t see you up for a night of hand-wringing. Truly I don\'92t. And this is the thanks I get for sparing you that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93This isn\'92t going to be as easy as ye seem to want to believe,\'94 Maldrin said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And what\'92s to worry about, Maldrin? A few pirates?\'94 Darrick shipped his oar, watchful that the longboat crew still moved together, then eased it back into the water and drew again. The longboat surged through the river water, making good time. They\'92d spotted the small campfire of the first sentry a quarter-mile back. The port they were looking for wasn\'92t much farther ahead.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93These aren\'92t just any pirates,\'94 Maldrin replied.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Darrick said, \'93I have to agree with you. These here pirates, now these are the ones that Cap\'92n Tollifer sent us to fetch up some trouble with. After orders like them, I won\'92t have you thinking I\'92d just settle for any pirates.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Nor me,\'94 Mat put in. \'93I\'92ve proven myself right choosy when it comes to fighting the likes of pirates.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint6}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint6}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A few of the other men agreed, and they shared a slight laugh.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  No one, Darrick noted, mentioned anything of the boy the pirates had kidnapped. Since the boy\'92s body hadn\'92t been recovered at the site of the earlier attack, everyone believed he was being held for ransom. Despite the need to let off steam before their insertion into the pirates\'92 stronghold, thinking of the boy was sobering.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Maldrin only shook his head and turned his attention to his own oar. \'93Ach, an\'92 ye\'92re a proper pain in the arse, Darrick Lang. Before all that\'92s of the Light and holy, I\'92d swear to that. But if\'92n there\'92s a man aboard Cap\'92n Tollifer\'92s ship what can pull this off, I figure it\'92s gotta be you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92d doff my hat to you, Maldrin,\'94 Darrick said, touched. \'93If I were wearing one, that is.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Just keep wearin\'92 the head it would fit on if ye were,\'94 Maldrin growled.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Indeed,\'94 Darrick said. \'93I intend to.\'94 He took a fresh grip on his oar. \'93Pull, then, boys, while the river is steady and the fog stays with us.\'94 As he gazed up at the mountains, he knew that some savage part of him relished thoughts of the coming battle.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The pirates wouldn\'92t give the boy back for free. And Captain Tollifer, on behalf of Westmarch\'92s king, was demanding a blood price as well.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Damned fog,\'94 Raithen said, then swore with heartfelt emotion.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The pirate captain\'92s vehemence drew Buyard Cholik from his reverie. The old priest blinked past the fatigue that held him in thrall and glanced at the burly man who stood limned in the torchlight coming from the suite of rooms inside the building. \'93What is the matter, Captain Raithen?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen stood like a mountain at the stone balcony railing of the building that overlooked the alabaster and columned ruins of the small port city where they\'92d been encamped for months. He pulled at the goatee covering his{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint7}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint7}massive chin and absently touched the cruel scar on the right corner of his mouth that gave him a cold leer.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The fog. Makes it damned hard to see the river.\'94 The pale moonlight glinted against the black chainmail Raithen wore over a dark green shirt. The ship\'92s captain was always sartorially perfect, even this early in the morning. Or this late at night, Cholik amended, for he didn\'92t know which was the case for the pirate chieftain. Raithen\'92s black breeches were tucked with neat precision into his rolled-top boots. \'93And I still think maybe we didn\'92t get away so clean from the last bit of business we did.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
