\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Mayhap the pirates will do for you before you wind up abed in your dotage,\'94 Mat said. \'93I\'92m sure they\'92re not going to give up their prize when we come calling.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick felt a sour twist in his stomach. The \'93prize\'94 the pirates held was the biggest reason Captain Tollifer had sent Darrick and the other sailors upriver instead of bringing\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 up.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  As a general rule, the pirates who had been preying on the king\'92s ships out of Westmarch had left no one alive. This time, they had left a silk merchant from Lut Gholein clinging to a broken spar large enough to serve as a raft. He\'92d been instructed to tell the king that one of the royal nephews had been taken captive. A ransom demand, Darrick knew, was sure to follow.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  It would be the first contact the pirates had initiated{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint15}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint15}with Westmarch. After all these months of successful raids against the king\'92s merchanters, still no one knew how they got their information about the gold shipments. However, they had left only the Lut Gholein man alive, suggesting that they hadn\'92t wanted anyone from Westmarch to escape who might identify them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The anchor scraped across the stone riverbed, taking away the margin for success by steady inches. The water and the sound of the current muted the noise. Then the anchor stopped and the rope jerked taut in Tomas\'92s hands. Catching the rope in his callused palms, the sailor squeezed tight.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The longboat stopped but continued to bob on the river current.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick glanced at the riverbank a little more than six feet away. \'93Well, we\'92ll make do with what we have, boys.\'94 He glanced at Tomas. \'93How deep is the water?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Tomas checked the knots tied in the rope as the longboat strained at the anchor. \'93She\'92s drawing eight and a half feet.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick eyed the shore. \'93The river must drop considerably from the edges of the cliffs.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It\'92s a good thing we\'92re not in armor,\'94 Mat said. \'93Though I wish I had a good shirt of chainmail to tide me through the coming fracas.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92d sink like a lightning-blasted toad if you did,\'94 Darrick replied. \'93And it may not come to fighting. Mayhap we\'92ll nip aboard the pirate ship and rescue the youngster without rousing a ruckus.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Maldrin muttered, \'93an\'92 if ye did, it would be one of the few times I\'92ve seen ye do that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick grinned in spite of the worry that nibbled at the dark corners of his mind. \'93Why, Maldrin, I almost sense a challenge in your words.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Make what ye will of it,\'94 the first mate growled. \'93I offer advice in the best of interests, but I see that it\'92s seldom taken in the same spirit in which it was give. Fer all ye know, they\'92re in league with dead men and suchlike here.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The first mate\'92s words had a sobering effect on Darrick, reminding him that though he viewed the night\'92s activities{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint16}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint16}as an adventure, it wasn\'92t a complete lark. Some pirate captains wielded magic.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We\'92re here tracking pirates,\'94 Mat said. \'93Just pirates. Mortal men whose flesh cuts and bleeds.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick said, ignoring the dry spot at the back of his throat that Maldrin\'92s words had summoned. \'93Just men.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  But still, the crew had faced a ship of dead men only months ago while on patrol. The fighting then had been brutal and frightening, and it had cost lives of shipmates before the undead sailors and their ship had been sent to the bottom of the sea.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The young commander glanced at Tomas. \'93We\'92re locked in?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Tomas nodded, tugging on the anchor rope. \'93Aye. As near as I can tell.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick grinned. \'93I\'92d like to have a boat to come back to, Tomas. And Captain Tollifer can be right persnickety about crew losing his equipment. When we get to shore, make the longboat fast again, if you please.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye. It will be done.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Grabbing his cutlass from among the weapons wrapped in the bottom of the longboat, Darrick stood with care, making sure he balanced the craft out. He took a final glance up at the tops of the cliffs. The last sentry point they\'92d identified lay a hundred yards back. The campfire still burned through the layers of fog overhead. He glanced ahead at the lights glowing in the distance, the clangor of ships\'92 rigging slapping masts reaching his ears.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Looks like there\'92s naught to be done for it, boys,\'94 Darrick said. \'93We\'92ve got a cold swim ahead of us.\'94 He noticed that Mat already had his sword in hand and that Maldrin had his own war hammer.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93After you,\'94 Mat said, waving an open hand toward the river.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Without another word, Darrick slipped over the side of the boat and into the river. The cold water closed over him at once, taking his breath away, and he swam against the current toward the riverbank.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint17}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint17}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  TWO
