\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Twisting and squirming, hands flailing through the bands of invisible force that held him captive, Raithen fought against Cholik\'92s spell. Surprise and fear marked Raithen\'92s face, and Cholik knew the man realized he wasn\'92t facing the weak old priest he thought he\'92d been talking to with such disregard. The big pirate opened his mouth and struggled to speak. No words came out. At a gesture, Cholik caused Raithen to float out over the balcony\'92s edge and the hundred-foot drop that lay beyond. Only broken rock and the tumbled remains of the buildings that had made up Tauruk\'92s Port lay below.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 The pirate captain ceased his struggles as fear dawned on his purpling face.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Power has brought me to Tauruk\'92s Port,\'94 Cholik grated, maintaining the magic grip, feeling the obscene pleasure that came from using such a spell, \'93and to Ransim buried beneath. Power such as you\'92ve never wielded. And none of that power will do you any good. You do not know how to wield it. The vessel for this power must be consecrated, and I mean to be that vessel. It\'92s something that you\'92ll never be able to be.\'94 The priest opened his hand.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Choking and gasping, Raithen floated back in and dropped to the stone-tiled floor of the balcony overlooking the river and the abandoned city. He lay back, gasping for air and holding his bruised throat with his left hand. His right hand sought the hilt of the heavy sword at his side.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If you pull that sword,\'94 Cholik stated, \'93then I\'92ll promote your ship\'92s commander. Perhaps even your first mate. Or I could even reanimate your corpse, though I{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint18}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint18}doubt your crew would be happy about the matter. But, frankly, I wouldn\'92t care what they thought.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen\'92s hand halted. He stared up at the priest. \'93You need me,\'94 he croaked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Cholik agreed. \'93That\'92s why I\'92ve let you live so long while we have worked together. It wasn\'92t pleasant or done out of a weak-willed sense of fair play.\'94 He stepped closer to the bigger man sitting with his back against the railing.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Purple bruising already showed in a wide swath around Raithen\'92s neck.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92re a tool, Captain Raithen,\'94 Cholik said. \'93Nothing more.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The big man glared up at him but said nothing. Swallowing was obviously a hard and painful effort.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But you are an important tool in what I am doing.\'94 Cholik gestured again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Seeing the priest\'92s fluttering hand inscribing the mystic symbols, Raithen flinched. Then his eyes widened in surprise.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik knew it was because the man hadn\'92t expected to be relieved of his pain. The priest knew healing spells, but the ones that caused injury came more readily to him these days. \'93Please get up, Captain Raithen. If you have led someone here and the fog has obscured their presence, I want you to handle it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Showing restraint and caution, Raithen climbed to his feet.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Do we understand each other?\'94 As Cholik gazed into the other man\'92s eyes, he knew he\'92d made an enemy for life. It was a pity. He\'92d planned for the pirate captain to live longer than that.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Aribar Raithen was called Captain Scarlet Waters by most of the Westmarch Navy. Very few people had survived his capture of a ship, and most ended up at the bottom of the Great Sea or, especially of late, in the Gulf of Westmarch.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Raithen growled, but the sound wasn\'92t so menacing with all the hoarseness in it. \'93I\'92ll get right on it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint19}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint19}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Good.\'94 Cholik stood and looked out to the broken and gutted buildings that remained of Tauruk\'92s Port. He pretended not to notice as Raithen left, nor did he indicate that he heard the big pirate captain\'92s slight foot drag that told him Raithen had considered stabbing him in the back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Metal whispered coolly against leather. But this time, Cholik knew, the blade was being returned to the sheath.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik remained at the balcony and locked his knees so he wouldn\'92t tremble from the cold or from the exhaustion he suffered from spell use. If he\'92d had to expend any more energy, he thought he\'92d have passed out and been totally at Raithen\'92s mercy.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  By the Light, where has the time gone? Where has my strength gone?\plain \f2\fs24 Gazing up at the stars burning bright against the sable night, Cholik felt old and weak. His hands were palsied now. Most of the time he maintained control of them, but on occasion he could not. When one of those uncontrollable periods arrived, he kept his hands out of sight in the folds of his robes and stayed away from others. The times always passed, but they were getting longer and longer.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  In Westmarch, it wouldn\'92t be many more years before one of the younger priests noted his growing infirmity and brought it to the senior priest\'92s attention. When that happened, Cholik knew he\'92d be shipped out from the church and placed in a hospice to help with the old and the diseased, all of them dying deaths by inches and him helping only to ease them into the grave while easing into a bed of his own. Even the thought of ending his days like that was too much.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Tauruk\'92s Port, with Ransim buried beneath, the information gleaned from the sacred texts\'97those things Cholik viewed as his personal salvation. The dark forces he\'92d allied himself with the past few years willing, it would be.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He turned his gaze from the stars to the fogbound river. The white, cottony masses roiled across the broken land forming the coastal area. Farther north, barbarian tribes would have been a problem to their discovery, but here in{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint20}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint20}the deadlands far north of Westmarch and Tristram, they were safe.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  At least, Cholik mused, they were safe if Raithen\'92s latest excursion to take a shipload of the king\'92s gold fresh out of Westmarch had not brought someone back. He peered down at the layers of fog, but he could see only the tall masts of the pirate ships standing out against the highest wisps of silver-gray fog.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lanterns aboard those ships created pale yellow and orange nimbi and looked like fireflies in the distance. Men\'92s raucous voices, the voices of pirates and not the trained acolytes Cholik had handpicked over the years, called out to one another in casual disdain. They talked of women and spending the gold they\'92d fought for that day, unaware of the power that lay buried under the city.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Only Raithen was becoming more curious about what they sought. The other pirates were satisfied with the gold they continued to get.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik cursed his palsied hands and the cold wind that swept over the Hawk\'92s Beak Mountains to the east. If only he were young, if only he\'92d found the sacred Vizjerei text sooner . . .
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Master.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Startled from his musings but recovering in short order, Cholik turned. He tucked his shaking hands out of sight inside his robes. \'93What is it, Nullat?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Forgive me for interrupting your solitude, Master Cholik.\'94 Nullat bowed. He was in his early twenties, dark-haired and dark-eyed. Dirt and dust stained his robes, and scratches adorned his smooth face and one arm from an accident during the excavation only a few days ago that had claimed the lives of two other acolytes.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik nodded. \'93You know better than to interrupt unless it was something important.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes. Brother Altharin asked me to come get you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Inside his withered chest, Cholik\'92s heart beat faster. Still, he maintained the control he had over himself and his emotions. All of the acolytes he\'92d bent to his own ends{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint21}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint21}feared him, and feared his power, but they remained hungry for the gifts they believed he would bestow. He intended to keep it that way. He kept silent, refusing to ask the question that Nullat had left hanging in the air.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Altharin believes we have reached the final gate,\'94 Nullat said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And has Altharin halted his work?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Of course, master. Everything has gone as you have ordered. The seals were not broken.\'94 Nullat\'92s face creased with worry.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Is something wrong?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Hesitation held Nullat mute for a moment. The pirates\'92 voices and the clangor of ships\'92 lines and rigging against yardarms and masts continued unabated from below.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Altharin thinks he has heard voices on the other side of the gate,\'94 Nullat said. His eyes broke from Cholik\'92s.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Voices?\'94 Cholik repeated, feeling more excited. The sudden rush of adrenaline caused his hands to shake more. \'93What kind of voices?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Evil voices.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik stared at the young acolyte. \'93Did you expect any other kind?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I don\'92t know, master.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The Black Road is not a way found by those faint of heart.\'94 In fact, Cholik had inferred from the sacred Vizjerei texts that the tiles themselves had been shaped from the bones of men and women who had been raised in a village free of evil and strife. They\'92d never known need or want until the population had grown large enough to serve the demons\'92 needs. \'93What do these voices say?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Nullat shook his head. \'93I cannot say, master. I do not understand them.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Does Altharin?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If he does, master, he did not tell me. He commanded only that I come get you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And what does the final gate look like?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93As you told us it would, master. Immense and fearful.\'94 Nullat\'92s eyes widened. \'93I\'92ve never seen anything like it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint22}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint22}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Nor has anyone else in hundreds of years,\plain \f2\fs24 Cholik thought. \'93Get a fresh torch, Nullat. We\'92ll go have a look at what Brother Altharin has discovered.\'94\plain \f2\i\fs24 And pray that the sacred texts were right. Otherwise, the evil that we release from behind that gate will kill us all.
