\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Pressed into the side of the mist-covered cliff, holding himself on his boot toes and the fingers of one hand, Darrick Lang reached for the next handhold. He was conscious of the rope tied around his waist and loins. He\'92d tacked the rope to a ship\'92s spike he\'92d driven into the cliffside five feet below, leaving a trail of them behind him for the others to use. If he slipped and everything worked right, the rope would keep him from plunging to his death or into the river sixty feet below. If it worked wrong, he might yank the two men anchoring him to the side of the cliff down after him. The fog was so thick below that he could no longer see the longboat.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  I should have brought Caron along,\plain \f2\fs24 Darrick thought as he curled his fingers around the rocky outcrop that looked safe enough to hold his weight. Caron was only a boy, though, and not one to bring into a hostile situation. Aboard\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star,\plain \f2\fs24 Caron was ruling king of the rigging. Even when he wasn\'92t assigned aloft, the boy was often found there. Caron had a natural penchant for high places.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Resting for just a moment, feeling the trembling muscles in his back and neck, Darrick breathed out and inhaled the wet, musty smell of rock and hard-packed earth. It smelled, he couldn\'92t help thinking, like a newly opened grave. His clothing was wet from the immersion in the river, and he was cold, but his body still found enough heat to break out in perspiration. It surprised him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You aren\'92t planning on camping out up there, are you?\'94 Mat called up. He sounded good-natured about it, but someone who knew him well could have detected the small tension in his voice.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It\'92s the view, you know,\'94 Darrick called down. And it amused him that they acted as if they were there for a lark{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint23}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint23}instead of serious business. But it had always been that way between them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  They were twenty-three years old, Darrick being seven months the elder, and they\'92d spent most of those years as friends growing up in Hillsfar. They\'92d lived among the hill people, loaded freight in the river port, and learned to kill when barbarian tribes had come down from the north hoping to loot and pillage. When they\'92d turned fifteen, they\'92d journeyed to Westmarch and pledged loyalty in the king\'92s navy. Darrick had gone to escape his father, but Mat had left behind a good family and prospects at the family mill. If Darrick had not left, Mat might not ever have left, and some days Darrick felt guilty about that. Dispatches from home always made Mat talk of the family he missed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Focusing himself again, Darrick stared out across the broken land at the harbor less than two hundred yards away. Another pirate sentry was encamped on the cliff along the way. The man had built a small, yellow-tongued fire that couldn\'92t be seen from the river.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Beyond, three tall-masted cogs, round-bodied ships built for river travel as well as coastal waters rather than the deep sea, lay at anchor in a dish-shaped natural harbor fronting the ruins of a city. Captain Tollifer\'92s maps had listed the city as Tauruk\'92s Port, but not much was known about it except that it had been deserted years ago.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lanterns and torches moved along the ships, but a few also roved through the city, carried by pirates, Darrick felt certain. Though why they should be so industrious this early in the morning was beyond him. The swirling fog laced with condensation made seeing across the distance hard, but Darrick could make out that much.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The longboat held fifteen men, including Darrick. He figured that they were outnumbered at least eight to one by the pirates. Staying for a prolonged engagement was out of the question, but perhaps spiriting the king\'92s nephew away and costing the pirates a few ships were possible. Darrick had volunteered for such work before, and he\'92d come through it alive.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint24}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint24}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  So far, bucko,\plain \f2\fs24 Darrick told himself with grim realization.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Although he was afraid, part of him was excited at the challenge. He clung to the wall, lifted a boot, and shoved himself upward again. The top of the cliff ledge was less than ten feet away. From there, it looked as if he could gain safe ground and walk toward the city ruins and the hidden port. His fingers and toes ached from the climb, but he put the discomfort out of his mind and kept moving.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  When he reached the clifftop, he had to restrain a cry of triumph. He turned and looked back down at Mat, curling his hand into a fist.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Even at the distance, Darrick saw the look of horror that filled Mat\'92s face. \'93Look out!\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Whipping his head back up, some inner sense warning him of the movement, Darrick caught a glimpse of moonlight-silvered steel sweeping toward him. He pulled his head down and released his hold on the cliff as he grabbed for another along the cliff\'92s edge.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sword chopped into the stone cliff, striking sparks from the high iron ore content just as Darrick\'92s hands closed around the small ledge he\'92d pushed up from last. His body slammed hard against the mountainside.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I told you I saw somebody out here,\'94 a man said as he drew his sword back again and stepped with care along the cliff\'92s edge. His hobnailed boots scraped stone.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yeah,\'94 the second man agreed, joining the first in the pursuit of Darrick.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Scrambling, holding tight to the edge of the cliff, Darrick pressed his boots against the stone and tried in vain to find suitable purchase to allow him to push himself up. He gave thanks to the Light that the pirates were almost as challenged by the terrain as he was. His boot soles scraped and slid as he tried to pull himself up.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Cut his fingers off, Lon,\'94 the man in back urged. He was a short, weasel-faced man with an ale belly pressing against his frayed shirt. Maniacal lights gleamed in his eyes. \'93Cut his fingers off, and watch him fall on the others down there. Before they can make it up, we can nip on{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint25}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint25}down to the bonfire and warn Captain Raithen they\'92s coming.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick filed the name away. During his years as part of the Westmarch Navy, he\'92d heard of Raithen. In fact, Captain Tollifer had said that the Captain\'92s Table, the quarterly meeting of chosen ships\'92 captains in Westmarch, had suggested Raithen as a possible candidate for the guilty party in the matter of the pirate raids. It was good to know, but staying alive to relate the news might prove difficult.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Stand back, Orphik,\'94 Lon growled. \'93You keep abuzzing around me like a bee, and I\'92m gonna stick you myself.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Shove off, Lon. I\'92ll do for him.\'94 The little man\'92s voice tittered with naked excitement.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Damn you,\'94 Lon cursed. \'93Get out of the way.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Quick as a fox in a henhouse, Orphik ducked under his companion\'92s outstretched free arm and dashed at Darrick with long-bladed knives that were almost short swords in their own right. He laughed. \'93I\'92ve got him, Lon. I\'92ve got him. Just sit you back and watch. I bet he screams the whole way down.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Keeping his weight distributed as evenly as possible, going with the renewed strength that flowed through his body from the adrenaline surge, Darrick swung from hand to hand, dodging the chopping blows Orphik delivered. Still, one of the pirate\'92s attempts slashed across the knuckle of his left hand\'92s little finger. Pain shot up Darrick\'92s arm, but he was more afraid of how the blood flow would turn his grip slippery.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Damn you!\'94 Orphik swore, striking sparks from the stone again. \'93Just stay still, and this will be over with in a trice.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lon reeled back away from the smaller man. \'93Look out, Orphik! Someone down there has a bow!\'94 The bigger pirate held up a sleeve and displayed the arrow that had caught on its fletchings and still hung there.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Distracted by the presence of the arrow and aware that another could be joining it at any moment, Orphik stepped{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint26}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint26}back a little. He drew up a boot and lashed out at his intended victim\'92s head.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick swung to one side and grabbed for the little man\'92s leg with his bloody hand, not wanting to trade it for the certain grip of his right. He knotted his fingers in the pirate\'92s breeches. Even though the breeches were tucked into the hobnailed boots, there was plenty of slack to seize. Balancing his weight from one hand on the cliff, Darrick yanked hard with the other.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Damn him! Lon, give me your hand before this bilge rat yanks me off the cliff!\'94 Orphik reached for the other man, who caught his hand in his own. Another arrow fired from below clattered against the cliff wall behind them and caused them both to duck.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taking advantage of the confusion, knowing he\'92d never get a better chance, Darrick swung his weight to the side and up. He pushed his feet ahead of him, throwing his body behind, hoping to clear the cliff\'92s edge or he would fall. Maybe the rope tied around his loins would hold him, or maybe Mat and the other men below had forgotten it in the mad rush of events.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
