\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93That damned priest, Cholik, has been thinking of us as lackeys.\'94 Raithen peered into the mirror, surveying the wound on his neck, poking at the edges of it with his fingers. Thank the Light, it wasn\'92t bleeding any more than it had been, and it even appeared to be stopping.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The flesh between the bite marks was raised, swollen, and already turning purple. Bits of skin and even the meat beneath hung in tatters. It would scar, Raithen knew. The thought made him bitter because he was vain about his looks. By most accounts, he was a handsome man and had taken care to remain that way. And it would give him a more colorful and acceptable excuse about how all the bruising had taken place around his neck.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Pettit grunted. \'93Them priests, they get up under a man\'92s skin with them high-and-mighty ways of theirs. Always actin\'92 like they got a snootful of air what\'92s better\'92n the likes of ye and me. There\'92s been a night or two on watch when I\'92d think about goin\'92 after one of them and guttin\'92 him, leavin\'92 him out for the others to find. Might put them in a more appreciatin\'92 frame o\'92 mind about what we\'92re a-doin\'92 here.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Satisfied that his life wasn\'92t in danger unless the woman was carrying some kind of disease that hadn\'92t become apparent yet, Raithen took a kerchief from his pocket and tied it around his neck. \'93That\'92s not a bad idea, Pettit.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Thank ye, cap\'92n. I\'92m always thinkin\'92. And, why, this here deserted city with all them stories o\'92 demons and the like, it\'92d be a perfect place to pull something like that. Why, we\'92d find out who the true believers were among ol\'92 Cholik\'92s bunch fer damn sure.\'94 He grinned, revealing only a few straggling, stained teeth remaining in his mouth.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Some of the men might get worried, too.\'94 Raithen surveyed the kerchief around his neck in the mirror. Actually, it didn\'92t look bad on him. In time, when the wound scarred over properly, he\'92d invent stories about how he\'92d gotten it in the arms of a lover he\'92d slain or stolen from, or some{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint47}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint47}crazed and passionate princess out of Kurast he\'92d taken for ransom then returned deflowered to her father, the king, after getting his weight in gold.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Well, we could tell the men what was what, cap\'92n.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93A secret, Pettit, is kept by one man. Even sharing it between the two of us endangers it. Telling a whole crew?\'94 Raithen shook his head and tried not to wince when his neck pained him. \'93That would be stupid.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Pettit frowned. \'93Well, somethin\'92 has to be done. Them priests has discovered a door down there in them warrens. An\'92 if the past behavior of them priests is anythin\'92 to go by, they ain\'92t a-gonna let us look at what\'92s behind it none.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93A door?\'94 Raithen turned to his second-in-command. \'93What door?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The big pirate, Lon, attacked Darrick Lang without any pretense at skilled swordplay. He just fetched up that huge sword of his in both hands and brought it crashing down toward Darrick\'92s head, intending to split it like an overripe melon.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Thrusting his cutlass up, knowing there was a chance that the bigger sword might shear his own blade but having no other choice for defense, Darrick caught the descending blade. He didn\'92t try to stop the sword\'92s descent, but he did redirect it to the side, stepping to one side as he did because he expected the sudden reversal the pirate tried. He didn\'92t entirely block the blow, though, and the flat of the blade slammed against his skull, almost knocking him out and leaving him disoriented.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Working on sheer instinct and guided by skilled responses, Darrick managed to lock his opponent\'92s blade with his while he struggled to hold on to his senses. His vision and hearing faded out, as the world sometimes did between slow rollers when\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 followed wave troughs instead of cutting through them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Recovering a little, Lon shoved Darrick back but didn\'92t gain much ground.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Moving with skill and the dark savagery that filled him{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint48}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint48}any time he fought, Darrick took a step forward and head-butted the pirate in the face.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Moaning, Lon stumbled back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick showed no mercy, pushing himself forward again. Obviously employing all the skill he had just to keep himself alive, the pirate kept retreating, stumbling and tripping over the broken terrain as he tried to walk up the incline behind him. Only a moment later, he went too far.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  As though from a great distance, Darrick heard the man\'92s boots scrape in the loose dirt, then the man fell, flailing and yelling, in the end wrapping his arms about his head. Ruthless and quick, Darrick knocked the pirate\'92s blade from his hand, sending the big sword spinning through the air to land in the dense brush a dozen yards away.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lon held his hands up. \'93I surrender! I surrender! Give me mercy!\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  But, dazed as he was from the near miss of the sword, mercy was out of Darrick\'92s reach. He remembered the bodies he\'92d seen in the flotsam left by the plunderers who had taken the Westmarch ship. Even that was hard to hang on to, because his battered mind slipped even farther back into the past, recalling the beatings his father had given him while he was a child. The man had been a butcher, big and rough, with powerful, callused hands that could split skin over a cheekbone with a single slap.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  For a number of years, Darrick had never understood his father\'92s anger or rage at him; he\'92d always assumed he\'92d done something wrong, not been a good son. It wasn\'92t until he got older that he understood everything that was at play in their relationship.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Mercy,\'94 the pirate begged.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  But the main voice that Darrick listened to was his father\'92s, cursing and swearing at him, threatening to beat him to death or bleed him out like a fresh-butchered hog. Darrick drew back his cutlass and swung, aiming to take the pirate\'92s head off.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint49}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint49}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Without warning, a sword darted out and deflected Darrick\'92s blow, causing the blade to cut into the earth only inches from the pirate\'92s arm-wrapped head. \'93No,\'94 someone said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Still lost in the memory of beatings he\'92d gotten at his father\'92s hands, the present overlapping the past, Darrick spun and lifted his sword. Incredibly, someone caught his arm before he could swing and halted the blow.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Darrick, it\'92s me. It\'92s me, Darrick. Mat.\'94 Thick and hoarse with emotion, Mat\'92s voice was little more than a whisper. \'93It\'92s me, damn it, leave off. We need this man alive.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Head filled with pain, vision still spotty from the pirate\'92s blow, Darrick squinted his eyes and tried to focus. Forced out as he made his way to the present reality, memory of those past events left with reluctance.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He\'92s not your father, Darrick,\'94 Mat said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick focused on his friend, feeling the emotion drain from him, leaving him weak and shaking. \'93I know. I know that.\'94 But he knew he hadn\'92t, not really. The pirate\'92s blow had almost taken away his senses. He took in a deep breath and struggled to continue clearing his head.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We need him alive,\'94 Mat said. \'93There\'92s the matter of the king\'92s nephew. This man has information we can use.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I know.\'94 Darrick looked at Mat. \'93Let me go.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat\'92s eyes searched his, but the grip on his swordarm never wavered. \'93You\'92re sure?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Looking over his friend\'92s shoulder, Darrick saw the other sailors in his shore crew. Only old Maldrin didn\'92t seem surprised by the bloodthirsty behavior Darrick had exhibited. Not many of the crew knew of the dark fury that sometimes escaped Darrick\'92s control. It hadn\'92t gotten away from him for a long time until tonight.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92m sure,\'94 Darrick said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat released him. \'93Those times are past us. You don\'92t ever have to revisit them. Your father didn\'92t follow us from Hillsfar. We left him there those years ago. We left him there, and good riddance, I say.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint50}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint50}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Nodding, Darrick sheathed the cutlass and turned from them. He swept the horizon with his gaze, conscious of Mat\'92s eyes still on him. The fact that his friend didn\'92t trust him even after he\'92d said he was all right troubled and angered him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  And he seemed to hear his father\'92s mocking laughter ringing in his ears, pointing out his helplessness and lack of worth. Despite how far he\'92d pushed himself, even shoving himself up through the Westmarch Navy ranking, he\'92d never been able to leave that voice behind in Hillsfar.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick took a deep, shuddering breath. \'93All right, then, we\'92d best get at it, lads. Maldrin, take a couple men and fetch us up some water, if you please. I want this bonfire wetted so it can\'92t go up by design or by mistake.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye, sir,\'94 Maldrin responded, turning immediately and pointing out two men to accompany him. A quick search through the guards\'92 supplies netted them a couple of waterskins. After emptying the waterskins over the pitch blend torch, they set out for the cliff\'92s edge at once to get more water to finish the job.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Turning, Darrick surveyed the big pirate as Mat tied his hands behind his back with a kerchief. \'93How many of you were on guard here?\'94 Darrick asked.
