\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Standing near the dead woman\'92s body in the inn room in Tauruk\'92s Port, Raithen watched as Pettit reached into a pocket under his vest and took out a piece of paper.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \'93That\'92s what brung me up here to see ye, cap\'92n,\'94 the first mate said. \'93Valdir sent this along just now as quick as he could after them priests found the door buried down in them ruins.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen crossed the room and took the paper. Unfolding it, he leaned toward the fireplace and the lantern that sat on the mantel.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Valdir was the current spy the pirate captain had assigned to Cholik\'92s excavation team. Raithen kept them rotated out with each new arrival of slaves. The men assigned didn\'92t care for it, and the fact that they didn\'92t become sickly and emaciated as the others did would draw attention from the mercenaries who remained loyal to Cholik\'92s gold.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The paper held a drawing of a series of elliptical lines, centered one within the other, and a different line running through them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What is this?\'94 Raithen asked.
