\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Freezing halfway to his feet, Lhex looked at Raithen. The look was one of childhood innocence and daring, trying to ascertain if the pirate captain had meant what he\'92d said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen maintained his icy stare, knowing he\'92d carry out the action he\'92d threatened.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Evidently, Lhex decided he would, too. Grimacing, the boy sat, but he did so with stubbornness, keeping his knees drawn up and placing his back securely against the wall behind him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You must think you\'92re something,\'94 Lhex snarled. \'93Menacing a kid like that. What\'92d you do for breakfast? Kick a puppy?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Actually,\'94 Raithen said, \'93I had one beheaded and rendered out to serve you for breakfast chops. They tell me it fried up like chicken for your noonday meal.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Horror flirted with Lhex\'92s eyes. He remained silent, watching Raithen.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Where did you get such an attitude, boy?\'94 the pirate captain asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93My parents blame each other,\'94 Lhex said. \'93I think I get it from them both.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Do you think you\'92re going to get out of here alive?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Either way,\'94 the boy said, \'93I\'92m not getting out of here scared. I\'92ve done that till I\'92m sick of it. I threw up the first three days.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92re a most unusual boy,\'94 Raithen said. \'93I wish I\'92d gotten to know you sooner.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Looking for a friend?\'94 Lhex asked. \'93I only ask because I know most of these pirates are afraid of you. They\'92re not here because they like you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Fear is a far better tool for command than friendship,\'94 Raithen responded. \'93Fear is instant, and it is obeyed without question.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint78}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint78}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92d rather have people like me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen smiled. \'93I\'92d wager to say that Bull doesn\'92t like you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Some people I can live without.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Wise lad,\'94 Raithen said. He paused, feeling the cog shift slightly in the river current.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The boy shifted with the ship automatically, just like a sailor.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How long have you been at sea, Lhex?\'94 Raithen asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The boy shrugged. \'93Since Lut Gholein.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You were there?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The ship came from Lut Gholein,\'94 Lhex said, narrowing his eyes and watching Raithen with a thoughtful expression. \'93If you didn\'92t know that, how did you find the ship?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen ignored the question. The information had come from Buyard Cholik\'92s spies within Westmarch. \'93What were you doing in Lut Gholein?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lhex didn\'92t answer.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Don\'92t trifle with me,\'94 Raithen warned. \'93I\'92m in an ill mood as it is.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Studying,\'94 Lhex answered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  That, Raithen decided, sounded promising. \'93Studying what?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93My father wanted me to have a good education. As the king\'92s younger brother, he was sent abroad and learned from sages in Lut Gholein. He wanted the same for me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How long were you there?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Four years,\'94 the boy said. \'93Since I was eight.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And what did you study?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Everything. Poetry. Literature. Marketing. Forecasting profits, though the whole thing with chicken gizzards was quite disgusting and not any better than just guessing.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What about history?\'94 Raithen asked. \'93Did you study history?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Of course I did. What kind of education would you get if you didn\'92t study history?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen dug in his blouse for the paper Pettit had given him. \'93I want you to look at this paper. Tell me what it means.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint79}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint79}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Interest flickered in the boy\'92s eyes as he regarded the paper. \'93I can\'92t see it from here.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Hesitant, Raithen took the lantern from the wall. \'93If you try anything, boy, I\'92ll have you crippled. If your father persuades the king to ransom you back, you\'92ll have to hope the healers can make you whole again, or you\'92ll drag yourself around like a circus freak.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I won\'92t try anything,\'94 Lhex said. \'93Bring the paper here. I\'92ve stared at walls for days.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Until you worked the bed support loose and attacked Bull,\plain \f2\fs24 Raithen thought. He stepped forward, respecting the boy\'92s skills and focus. Most boys Lhex\'92s age would have been sniveling wrecks by now. Instead, the king\'92s nephew had busied himself with planning escape, conserving energy, and eating to keep himself healthy and strong.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lhex took the paper Raithen offered. His quick eyes darted over the paper. Hesitantly, he traced the design with his forefinger.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Where did you get this?\'94 Lhex asked in a quiet voice.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The cog shifted in the river, and water slapped against the hull, echoing throughout the ship. Raithen rode out the change in the ship without much thought. \'93It doesn\'92t matter. Do you know what it is?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 the boy said. \'93This is some kind of demon script. That symbol belongs to Kabraxis, the demon who supposedly constructed the Black Road.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen drew back and scoffed. \'93There are no such things as demons, boy.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93My teachers taught me to have an open mind. Maybe demons aren\'92t here now, but that doesn\'92t mean that they were never here.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen peered at the paper, trying to make sense of it. \'93Can you read it?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lhex made a rude noise. \'93Do you know anyone who can read demon script?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Raithen said. \'93But I\'92ve known some who sold parchments they said were treasure maps to demon{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint80}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint80}hoards.\'94 He\'92d bought and sold a few of those himself as his belief in such creatures had risen and fallen.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You don\'92t believe in demons?\'94 the boy asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Raithen said. \'93They\'92re only good for stories best told in taverns or over a slow campfire when there\'92s nothing else to do.\'94 Still, the boy\'92s words had intrigued him.\plain \f2\i\fs24 The priest is here hunting a demon?\plain \f2\fs24 He couldn\'92t believe it. \'93What else can you tell me about this design?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A trail scarred the mountainside, running parallel to the Dyre River. Darrick was certain Raithen\'92s pirate crew used it when changing the guard. He stayed off it, choosing the slower path through the brush.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat and Maldrin followed him, staying to the path he chose.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  As they neared the riverbank\'92s edge overlooking the three pirate vessels, wisps of silver fog threaded through the brush. Tobacco smoke itched Darrick\'92s nose. Though Captain Tollifer didn\'92t allow smoking on\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star,\plain \f2\fs24 Darrick had been around a number of men who smoked in ports they patrolled and traded with. He\'92d never acquired the habit himself and thought it was repugnant. And it reminded him of his father\'92s pipe.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The brush and treeline ended twenty yards short of the area the pirates had been using to shift their stolen goods. Shadows painted the stacks of crates and barrels, giving him more cover to take advantage of.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  One of the pirates walked away from the group of five who played dice. \'93That ale\'92s gettin\'92 the best of me. Hold my place. I\'92ll be back.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93As long as ye have money,\'94 one of the other pirates said, \'93we\'92ll stand ye to a place in this game. This is yer unlucky night and our lucky one.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Just be glad Cap\'92n Raithen\'92s been keepin\'92 us headed toward fat purses,\'94 the pirate said. He walked around to the side of the crates where Darrick hid in the brush.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick thought the man was going to relieve himself over the side of the riverbank and was surprised to see him{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint81}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint81}dig in the bag at his side frantically once he was out of sight of the others. Pale moonlight touched the dice that tumbled out into the man\'92s waiting palm.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The pirate grinned and closed his fist over the dice. Then he started to relieve himself.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Moving with catlike grace, Darrick crept up behind the pirate. Picking up a stone loose on the ground, Darrick fisted it and stepped behind the pirate, who was humming a shanty tune as he finished. Darrick recognized the tune as \'93Amergo and the Dolphin Girl,\'94 a bawdy favorite of a number of sailors.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick swung the stone, felt the thud of rock meeting flesh, and wrapped an arm around the unconscious pirate to guide him to the ground. Leaving the fallen pirate out of sight from the others, Darrick slid to the riverbank\'92s edge. He peered down, seeing that all three cogs did lie at anchorage beneath the overhang as he\'92d thought.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He drew back, put his shoulders to the crate behind him, slid his cutlass free, and waved to Maldrin and Mat. They crossed, staying low.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Hey, Timar,\'94 one of the pirates called, \'93ye comin\'92 back tonight?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Told ye he had too much to drink,\'94 another pirate said. \'93Probably start cheatin\'92 any minute now.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If\'92n I see them loaded dice of his one more time,\'94 another pirate said, \'93I swear I\'92m gonna cut his nose off.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick glanced up the slight rise of land toward the ruins of Tauruk\'92s Port. No one came down the trail that wound through the wreckage.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Four men left,\'94 Darrick whispered. \'93Once one of them makes a noise, there\'92ll be no more hiding here for us.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat nodded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Maldrin slitted his eyes and ran a thumb across the knife in his fist. \'93Better they not have a chance to make noise, then.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Agreed,\'94 Darrick whispered. \'93Maldrin, hold the steps. They\'92ll come from below as soon as we announce ourselves.{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint82}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint82}And we will be announcing ourselves. Mat, you and I are going to see about setting the ships on fire below.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat raised his eyebrows.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Barrels of whale oil,\'94 Darrick said. \'93Shouldn\'92t be that hard to get them over the edge of the riverbank. They\'92ll fall straight to the ships below. Get them on the decks of the one port of\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda,\plain \f2\fs24 and I\'92ll target the one starboard of her.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Smiling, Mat nodded. \'93They\'92ll be busy tryin\'92 to save their ships.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick said. \'93We\'92ll use the confusion to get aboard\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda\plain \f2\fs24 and see to the king\'92s nephew.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Be lucky if\'92n ye don\'92t get yerselves killed outright,\'94 Maldrin groused. \'93An\'92 me with ye.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick smiled, feeling cocky as he always did when he was in the thick of a potentially disastrous situation. \'93If we live, you owe me a beer back at Rik\'92s Tavern in Westmarch.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I owe ye?\'94 Maldrin looked as though he couldn\'92t believe it. \'93An\'92 how is it ye\'92re a-gonna buy me one?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Shrugging, Darrick said, \'93If I get us all killed, I\'92ll stand you to your first cool drink in the Burning Hells.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Maldrin protested. \'93That\'92s not fair.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Speak up first next time, and you can set the terms,\'94 Darrick said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Timar!\'94 one of the pirates bellowed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He\'92s probably fallen in,\'94 another pirate said. \'93I\'92ll go look for him.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick rose slowly, looking over the stack of crates as one of the pirates peeled off from the game. He held his cutlass in his hand, signaling Mat and Maldrin to stand down. If fortune was going to favor them with one more victim before they set to, so be it.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  When the man stepped around the crates, Darrick grabbed him, clapped a hand over the pirate\'92s mouth, and slit his throat with the cutlass. Darrick held the man as he bled out. A look of horror filled Mat\'92s face.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick looked away from the accusation he found in{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint83}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint83}his friend\'92s eyes. Mat could kill to save a friend or a shipmate in the heat of battle, but killing as Darrick had just done was beyond him. To Darrick, there was no remorse or guilt involved. Pirates deserved death, whether by his hands or by the hangman\'92s noose in Westmarch.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  As the pirate\'92s corpse shuddered a final time, Darrick released it and stepped away. Blood coated his left arm and warmed him against the chill wind. Knowing they were working on borrowed time, Darrick caught the edge of the crates in front of him and hauled himself around them. He lifted his knees and drove his feet hard against the ground, sprinting toward the three men still occupied with the dice game.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  One of the men glanced up, attracted by the flurry of motion coming toward them. He opened his mouth to yell a warning.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint84}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint84}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  SEVEN
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \'93Kabraxis is the demon who created the Black Road,\'94 Lhex said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \'93What is the Black Road?\'94 Raithen asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The boy shrugged, bathed in the golden light of the lantern the pirate captain held. \'93It\'92s all just legend. Old stories of demons. There\'92s talk that Kabraxis was just an elaborate lie.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But you said if a demon was involved,\'94 Raithen said, \'93it was all truth once.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I said it was based on something that was supposed to be the truth,\'94 Lhex replied. \'93But so many stories have been told since the Vizjerei started\plain \f2\i\fs24 supposedly\plain \f2\fs24 summoning demons from other worlds. Some of the stories are based on incidents that might have or might not have involved demons, but many are total fabrications. Or a story has been fractured, retold, and made more current. Old wives\'92 tales. Harsus, the toad-faced demon of Kurast\'97if he even existed\'97has become four different demons in the local histories. The man who taught me history told me there are sages at work now trying to piece together different stories, examining them for common links that bind them and make only one demon exist where two had stood before.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why would they bother with something like that?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because there were supposed to be other demons loose in the world according to all those simpleminded myths,\'94 Lhex said. \'93My teacher believed that men spent so much time trying to name the demons in mythology the better to hunt them down instead of waiting for them to act. To pursue their quarry, the demon hunters need to know how{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint85}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint85}many demons were in our world and where to find them. Sages research those things.\'94 The boy snorted. \'93Personally, I think demons were all named so that a\plain \f2\i\fs24 wise and wizened\plain \f2\fs24 sage could recommend employing demon hunters. Of course, that sage would get a cut of the gold paid to rid a place or a city or a kingdom of a demon. It was a racket. A well-thought-out scary story to tell superstitious people and separate them from their gold.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Kabraxis,\'94 Raithen reminded, growing impatient.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93In the beginning years,\'94 Lhex said, \'93when the Vizjerei first began experimenting with demon summoning, Kabraxis was supposed to be one of those demons summoned over and over again.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because Kabraxis operated the mystical bridges that stretched from the demon worlds to our world more easily than many did.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The Black Road is a bridge to the Burning Hells?\'94 Raithen asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Possibly. I told you this was all a story. Nothing more.\'94 Lhex tapped the drawing of the elliptical lines threaded through by the solitary one. \'93This drawing represents the power Kabraxis had to walk between the Burning Hells and this world.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If the Black Road isn\'92t the bridge between this world and the Burning Hells,\'94 Raithen asked, \'93what else could it be?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Some have said it was the path to enlightenment.\'94 Lhex rubbed his face as if bored, then smothered a yawn.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What enlightenment?\'94 Raithen asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Power,\'94 Lhex said. \'93Is there anything else that the legends would offer?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What kind of power?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lhex frowned at him, faking a yawn and leaning back comfortably against the wall behind them. \'93I\'92m tired, and I grow weary of telling you bedtime stories.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If you want,\'94 Raithen suggested, \'93I can have Bull come back and tuck you in.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint86}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint86}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Maybe I\'92ll get his other ear,\'94 Lhex suggested.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92re an evil child,\'94 Raithen said. \'93I can imagine why your father shipped you away to school.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92m willful,\'94 Lhex corrected. \'93There is a difference.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Not enough of one,\'94 Raithen warned. \'93I\'92ve got gold enough that I can do without your ransom, boy. Making the king pay is only retribution for past indignities I\'92ve suffered at his hands.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You know the king?\'94 Lhex\'92s eyebrows darted up.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What power can Kabraxis offer?\'94 the pirate captain demanded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The river current shifted\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda\plain \f2\fs24 again. She floated high, then slithered sideways a moment before settling in. The rigging slapped against the masts and yardarms above.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93They say Kabraxis offers immortality and influence,\'94 Lhex replied. \'93Plus, for those brave enough, and I can\'92t imagine there being many, there is access to the Burning Hells.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Influence over what?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93People,\'94 Lhex said. \'93When Kabraxis last walked this world\'97according to the myths I\'92ve read in the philosophy studies I did\'97he chose a prophet to represent him. A man named Kreghn, who was a sage of philosophy, wrote about the teachings of Kabraxis. And I tell you, that was a very ponderous tome. It bored my arse off.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The demon\'92s teachings? And it wasn\'92t a banned book?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Of course it was,\'94 Lhex answered. \'93But when Kabraxis first walked this world then, no one knew he was a demon. That\'92s the story we\'92ve all been told, of course, and there\'92s no proof of it. But Kabraxis was better thought of than some of the demons of legend.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because Kabraxis wasn\'92t as bloodthirsty as some of the other demons. He bided his time, getting more and more followers to embrace the tenets he handed down through Kreghn. He taught his followers about the Three Selves. Have you heard of that concept?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen shook his head. His mind buzzed steadily, gaining{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint87}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint87}speed as he tried to figure out what Buyard Cholik was doing seeking out remnants of such a creature.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The Three Selves,\'94 Lhex said, \'93consist of the Outer Self, the way a person portrays himself or herself to others; the Inner Self, the way a person portrays himself or herself to himself or herself; and the Shadow Self. The Shadow Self is the true nature of a man or woman, the part of himself or herself that he or she most fears\'97the dark part every person struggles hardest to hide. Kukulach teaches us that most people are too afraid of themselves to face that truth.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And people believed that?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The existence of the Three Selves is known,\'94 Lhex said. \'93Even after Kabraxis was supposedly banished from this world, other sages and scholars carried on the work Kreghn began.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What work?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The study of the Three Selves.\'94 Lhex grimaced as if displeased at Raithen\'92s listening skills. \'93The legend of Kabraxis first developed the theory, but other scholars\'97such as Kukulach\'97have made our understanding of it whole. It just sounds better couched in terms that led the superstitious to believe this was one of the bits of wisdom we needed to save from the demons. Fairy tales and mechanisms to define social order, that\'92s all they were.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Even so,\'94 Raithen said, \'93there\'92s no power in that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The followers of Kabraxis reveled in the exposure of their Shadow Selves,\'94 the boy said. \'93Four times a year, during the solstices and the equinoxes, Kabraxis\'92s worshippers came together and partied, reveling in the darkness that dwelt within them. Every sin known to man was allowed in Kabraxis\'92s name during the three days of celebration.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And afterward?\'94 Raithen asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93They were forgiven their sins and washed again in the symbolic blood of Kabraxis.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93That belief sounds stupid.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I told you that. That\'92s why it\'92s a myth.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint88}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint88}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How did Kabraxis get here?\'94 Raithen asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93During the Mage Clan Wars. There was some rumor that one of Kreghn\'92s disciples had managed to open a portal to Kabraxis again, but that was never confirmed.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Has Cholik confirmed it?\plain \f2\fs24 Raithen wondered.\plain \f2\i\fs24 And did that trail lead here, to the massive door that is located beneath the ruins of Tauruk\'92s Port?
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How was Kabraxis banished from this world?\'94 Raithen asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93According to legend, by Vizjerei warriors and wizards of the Spirit Clan,\'94 Lhex replied, \'93and by those who stood with them. They eradicated the temples to Kabraxis in Vizjun and other places. Only wreckage of buildings and broken altars remain where the demon\'92s temples once stood.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen considered that. \'93If a man could contact Kabraxis\'97\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And offer the demon a path back into this world?\'94 Lhex asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye. What could such a man expect?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Wouldn\'92t the promise of immortality be enough? I mean, if you believed in such nonsense.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen thought of Buyard Cholik\'92s body bent with old age and approaching infirmity. \'93Aye, maybe it would at that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Where did you find that?\'94 Lhex asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Before Raithen could respond, the door opened, and Bull stepped inside.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Cap\'92n Raithen,\'94 the big pirate said, holding a lantern high. Concern stretched his features tight. \'93We\'92re under attack.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Only a few steps short of the pirate about to scream out, Darrick leapt into the air. The other two pirates who had been playing dice reached for their weapons as Darrick\'92s feet slammed into the pirate\'92s head.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Caught by surprise and by all of Darrick\'92s weight, almost too drunk to stand, the pirate flew over the steep side of the riverbank. He didn\'92t even scream. The hard{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint89}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint89}thump told Darrick that the pirate had struck the wooden deck of the ship below instead of the river.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What the hell was that?\'94 a pirate called out from below.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick landed on the bare stone ground, bruising his hip. He clutched his cutlass and swiped at the nearest pirate\'92s legs, slashing both thighs. Blood stained the man\'92s light-colored breeches.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Help!\'94 the stricken pirate yelled. \'93Ahoy the ship! Damn it, but he\'92s cut me deep!\'94 He stumbled backward, trying to pull his sword free of its sash but forgetting to release the ale bottle he already held.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Pushing himself up and drawing the cutlass back again, Darrick drove the pirate backward, close to the riverbank\'92s edge. He whipped the cutlass around and chopped into the pirate\'92s neck, cleaving his throat in a bloody spray. The cutlass blade lodged against the man\'92s spine. Lifting his foot, Darrick shoved the dying man over the riverbank. He turned, listening to the splash as the pirate hit the water only a moment later, and saw Mat engaging the final pirate on guard at the supply station.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat\'92s cutlass sparked as he pressed his opponent\'92s guard. He penetrated the pirate\'92s guard easily, hesitating about drawing blood.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cursing beneath his breath, knowing that they had precious little time to rescue the boy and that they didn\'92t know for sure if he was aboard the ship waiting below, Darrick stepped forward and brought his cutlass down in a hand-and-a-half stroke that split the man\'92s skull. Acutlass wasn\'92t a fancy weapon; it was meant to hack and cleave because shipboard battles on vessels riding the waves tended to be messy things guided mostly by desperation and strength and luck.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Blood from the dead man splashed over Mat and onto Darrick.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat looked appalled as the pirate dropped. Darrick knew his friend didn\'92t approve of the blow dealt from behind or while the pirate had already been engaging one opponent. Mat believed in fighting fairly whenever possible.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint90}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint90}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Get the barrels,\'94 Darrick urged, yanking his sword from the dead man\'92s head.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He didn\'92t even see you comin\'92,\'94 Mat protested, looking down at the dead man.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The barrels,\'94 Darrick repeated.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He was too drunk to fight,\'94 Mat said. \'93He couldn\'92t have defended himself.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We\'92re not here to fight,\'94 Darrick said, grabbing Mat\'92s bloody shirtfront. \'93We\'92re here to save a twelve-year-old boy. Now,\plain \f2\i\fs24 move!\'94\plain \f2\fs24 He shoved Mat at the oil barrels. \'93There\'92s plenty of fair fights left down there if you\'92re wanting for them.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat stumbled toward the oil barrels.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Thrusting his cutlass into his waist sash, Darrick listened to the hue and cry taken up from the ships below. He glanced at the top of the stone steps carved into the side of the overhang.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Maldrin had taken up a position at the top of the steps. The first mate held a war hammer with a metal-shod haft in both hands. The hammer took both hands to wield, but the squared head promised crushed skulls, broken bones, or shattered weapons.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93 \'92Ware arrows, Maldrin,\'94 Darrick called.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A sour grin twisted the first mate\'92s mouth. \'93 \'92Ware yer own arse there, skipper. Ain\'92t me gonna be goin\'92 after that there boy.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick kicked a barrel over onto its side. The thick liquid inside glugged. Working with haste, he got behind the barrel and used his hands to roll it toward the riverbank\'92s edge. The downward slope favored the rolling barrel.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  After he got it started, he knew he couldn\'92t have easily stopped the barrel\'92s momentum. Giving the barrel a final shove, he watched it roll over the edge and disappear. He stopped at the edge, teetering for a moment, and gazed down, spotting the falling barrel just as it smashed against the ship\'92s deck below. Wisps of fog slid over the deck, but silvery patches showed through where the whale oil reflected the lantern lights of the pirate guards on watch.
