\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The gap left in the bridge was too far for Cholik to leap. The old priest realized he was trapped on the bridge.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Let that be your first lesson,\plain \f2\fs24 the demon said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 I will be your strength when you have no strength of your own.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Knowing he was doomed, Cholik turned and glanced back up the bone bridge. The silver star glowed brighter, revealing more of the path. The bridge of bones continued to lead up, but it zigzagged back and forth. What seemed to be trees occupied the elbows of the zigzags.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik hesitated, trying to muster more strength but knowing that his body had none left to give.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Come, Buyard Cholik,\plain \f2\fs24 the demon taunted.\plain \f2\i\fs24 You made your choice when you stepped through that doorway. You only had the illusion of being able to change your mind along the way.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik felt as though a great hand squeezed his chest, squeezing the breath from him. Was it his heart, then? Was it finally going to fail him? Or was this Zakarum\'92s vengeance for abandoning the church?
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Of course,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said,\plain \f2\i\fs24 you could throw yourself from the bridge.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik was tempted, but only for a moment. The temptation came not out of fear but out of rebellion. But that{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint107}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint107}was just a momentary spark. The fear in him of death was a raging bonfire. He lifted a foot and went on.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  As he neared the first of the trees, he saw that they bore fruit. When he was closer, he saw the fruits on the tree were tiny human heads. The small faces were filled with fear. Their lips moved in pleading that only then became audible to him. Although he couldn\'92t understand their words, Cholik understood their agony. The sound was an undercurrent, a rush of pain and despair that was somehow horribly melodic.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Tormented voices,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Isn\'92t it the sweetest sound you\'92ve ever heard?
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik kept walking, finding another bend and another tree and another chorus of hopelessness and hurt. His breath burned inside his chest and he felt as if iron bands constricted his chest.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He faltered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Come, Buyard Cholik. It\'92s only a little farther. Would you die there and become one of the fruits on the tree?
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Pain blurred the old priest\'92s vision, but he lifted his head after the next turn and saw that the bridge remained straight to a small island that floated in the middle of the darkness. The silver star hung behind the shoulder of a massive humanoid shape sitting on a stone throne.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Gasping, no longer able to do more than sip air, knowing he was only inches from death, Cholik made the final ascent and stopped in front of the massive figure on the throne. Unable to stand in front of the demon, the old priest dropped to his hands and knees on the abrasive black rock that made up the island. He coughed, weakly; the coppery taste of blood filled his mouth, and he saw the scarlet threads spray onto the black rock. He watched in stunned horror as the rock absorbed the blood, drinking it in till the rock was once more dry.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Look at me.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Wracked by pain, certain of his death, Cholik lifted his head. \'93You had best work quickly, Lord Kabraxis.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Even seated, the demon was taller than Cholik standing{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint108}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint108}up. The old priest guessed that Kabraxis was twice as tall as a man, perhaps even as much as fifteen feet tall. The demon\'92s massively broad body was black flesh, marbled with blue fire that burned and ran through him. His face was horrid, crafted of hard planes and rudimentary features: two inverted triangle eyes, no nose but black pits that were nostrils, and a lipless gash of a mouth filled with yellowed fangs. Writhing, poisonous vipers sprouted from his head, all of them beautiful, cool crystal colors of a rainbow.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Do you know of the Black Road?\plain \f2\fs24 the demon asked, leaning close. All the taunting had left his voice.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Cholik gasped.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Are you prepared to face what lies on the Black Road?
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Then do so.\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis reached forward, taking Cholik\'92s head between his huge three-fingered hands. The demon\'92s talons bit into the old priest\'92s head, driving into his skull.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik\'92s senses swam. His eyes teared as he stared into the demon\'92s monstrous visage and tasted Kabraxis\'92s foul breath. Before he knew he was doing it, Cholik screamed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The demon only laughed, then breathed fire over him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint109}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint109}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  NINE
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Glaring out into the harbor of Tauruk\'92s Port, Raithen knew two of the three cogs were lost. The flames ran up the masts, too well established in the rigging and the sails to be beaten back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 He strode\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda\'92\plain \f2\fs24 s deck with grim determination. \'93Get off that ship,\'94 he yelled to the pirates who had feared him more than they had feared the fire and had fought to save it. The effort to raise his voice hurt his wounded throat.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The pirates obeyed at once, showing no remorse at abandoning the vessel. If losing a few of the pirates would have meant saving the ship, Raithen would have done it, but losing the ship and more men was unacceptable.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen leapt onto the plank that led to the narrow shoreline below the overhanging cliff. Rocks and boulders littered the narrow strip of stone that provided a walkway to the steps cut into the cliffside. Dead pirates sprawled across the steps as well, victims of the Westmarch Navy rescue crew who had taken the boy from him. Other pirates had fallen into the river and been swept away. The old man with the war hammer had become death incarnate while holding the steps. Westmarch archers among the rescue group had wreaked havoc among the pirates for a long minute or two until the pirates had no longer tried to storm the steps to the clifftop.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen knew that the Westmarch sailors had gone, taking the boy with them. The pirate captain walked to the burning cog downstream from\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda,\plain \f2\fs24 stopped in front of the mooring rope that held the ship in place, and cut it{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint110}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint110}with one mighty blow from the ax he\'92d carried from\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  With the thick mooring rope severed, the burning cog slid out into the river, caught in the current, and floated away. It wasn\'92t a vessel anymore; it was a pyre.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93On board\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda,\'94\plain \f2\fs24 Raithen ordered his men. \'93Prepare poles, and let\'92s keep that damn burning tub from her.\'94 He crossed to the cog upstream from\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda,\plain \f2\fs24 waited until pirates lined the cog\'92s railing, then chopped through the hawser line.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The river carried the burning cog into\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda.\plain \f2\fs24 The pirates strove to keep the burning ship from the vessel Raithen hoped to salvage.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda\'92\plain \f2\fs24 s hull might be split or merely leaking, but he planned on saving her. Without the cog, it would be a long walk back to the rendezvous point where he kept the main ships of his pirate fleet.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen cursed his pirates, finally giving up, returning to\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda\plain \f2\fs24 himself, and taking up a pole. He felt the blaze\'92s heat against his face, but he yelled at his pirates. Slowly, propelled by the poles, the burning ship bumped and butted around\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The pirates started cheering.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Angry, Raithen grabbed the two men nearest him in quick succession and heaved them over\plain \f2\i\fs24 Barracuda\'92\plain \f2\fs24 s railing. The other pirates pulled back at once, knowing they\'92d all feel their captain\'92s wrath if they stayed near him. Bull was one of the first to step out of reach, knocking over three men in his haste.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen drew his sword, and it gleamed. He faced his men. \'93You damn stupid louts. We just lost two of our ships, our hidden port, and cargo we aren\'92t going to be able to freight out of here\'97and you stand there cheering like you done something?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Smoke stained the pirates\'92 faces, and no few of them bore burns and injuries from the brief battle with the Westmarch sailors.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I want a crew here to pump this vessel out and see to the repairs,\'94 Raithen yelled. \'93We\'92ll sail at dawn. Those{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint111}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint111}damned Westmarch sailors can\'92t get the river\'92s mouth closed by then. Bull, bring the rest of the men with me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Where to, cap\'92n?\'94 Bull asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We\'92re going to find that damned priest,\'94 Raithen said. \'93If he can persuade me to let him, I\'92ll suffer him to live and take him out of here, too. For a price.\'94 He touched his wounded throat. \'93If not, I\'92ll see him dead before I quit this port, and I\'92ll rob whatever treasures he\'92s scavenged from that buried city as well.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But, Cap\'92n Raithen,\'94 one of the pirates said, \'93that explosion what took out the cliffside and flattened the ruins came from the priests\'92 digs. I come from there when them buildings fell on us. Them priests were probably all killed.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then we\'92ll be robbing dead men if we can find them,\'94 Raithen said. \'93I\'92ve no problem with that.\'94 He turned and walked toward the cliffside. As he climbed the crooked stone steps, he shoved debris and dead men from his path. At the least, he intended to get his vengeance on Buyard Cholik\'97unless the old priest had been killed in the mysterious blast.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I won\'92t go! I won\'92t go, I tell you!\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick Lang watched the young boy struggle and fight against Mat and one of the other sailors who pulled him toward the Hawk\'92s Beak Mountains, escape, and\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 in the Gulf of Westmarch.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Please!\'94 the boy yelled. \'93Please! You\'92ve got to listen to me!\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Frustrated, Darrick waved Mat and the other sailor to halt. They were far enough up the mountainside that he had a clear view of the harbor and the city ruins. The second burning cog was passing beside them out on the river far below. A straggling line of pirates still extricated themselves from the ruins and made their way toward the cliffside harbor, but the line of lanterns and torches streaming up the stone steps announced that the pirates weren\'92t ready to abandon the port yet.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint112}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint112}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Listen to you about what?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The demon,\'94 the boy said. His breath came in ragged gasps because they had pushed him hard after getting him to the top of the cliff. He was too big to carry and run, so Darrick had grabbed the boy\'92s clothing and pushed and pulled him up the mountainside till he couldn\'92t run anymore.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What demon?\'94 Mat asked, dropping to one knee to face the boy squarely.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  After all those years with his younger brothers and sisters in the burgeoning Hu-Ring household, Darrick knew Mat had far more patience with children than he did.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We don\'92t need any talk of damn demons,\'94 Maldrin snarled. The old mate was covered in blood, but little of it was his own. Despite the battle he\'92d fought while holding the top of the stone steps until archers among the group could kill or chase away pirates eager to die, he still had stamina. Every hand aboard\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 believed that the crusty old mate could walk any sailor who shipped with him to death, then lace up his boots and walk another league or more. \'93We\'92ve been blessed with no bad luck thus far, an\'92 I wouldn\'92t have it any other way.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The pirate captain,\'94 Lhex said. \'93He showed me a sign of Kabraxis.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93An\'92 this Kabraxis,\'94 Mat said, \'93he\'92d be the demon you\'92re referrin\'92 to, would he?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Lhex said, turning and gazing back toward the ruins of Tauruk\'92s Port. \'93The door to Kabraxis\'92s Lair must be somewhere in that. I heard the pirates talking about the priests who were digging there.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What sign?\'94 Mat persisted.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Captain Raithen showed me Kabraxis\'92s sign,\'94 Lhex said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And how is it, then,\'94 Darrick asked in a sharp manner, \'93that you\'92d be knowing so much about demons?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lhex rolled his eyes at Darrick, showing obvious disapproval. \'93I was sent to Lut Gholein to be priest-trained. I\'92ve spent four years in school there. Some of our main philosophy books deal with the thematic struggle between man{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint113}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint113}and his demons. They aren\'92t supposed to be real. But what if they are? What if Kabraxis is somewhere lost in the ruins of this city?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The wind came down out of the peaks of Hawk\'92s Beak Mountains and chilled Darrick. Sweat from his exertions matted his hair, but it lifted as he gazed at the ruins of the city. Pirates boiled along the top of the cliff overhanging the Dyre River, their lanterns and torches cutting through the stirring fog and reflecting in the river below.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We\'92ve naught to do with demons, boy,\'94 Darrick said. \'93Our orders are to see you safe and home, and I mean to do that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We\'92re talking of a demon here, captain,\'94 Lhex insisted.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92m no captain,\'94 Darrick said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93These men follow you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye, but I\'92m no captain. My own captain has ordered me to bring you back, and I\'92m going to do that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And if the pirates find a demon?\'94 Lhex asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93They\'92re welcome to any foul demons they might find, says I,\'94 Maldrin offered. \'93Honest men don\'92t have nothin\'92 to do with demons.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 the boy said earnestly, \'93but demons steal the souls of honest men. And Kabraxis was one of the worst while he walked through these lands.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Ye ain\'92t gettin\'92 me to believe in demons,\'94 Tomas said, his face dark with suspicion. \'93Stories, that\'92s all them legends are. Just meant to give a man a laugh an\'92 maybe a sense of unease now an\'92 again.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Kabraxis,\'94 Lhex said, \'93was also called the Thief of Hope. People died wearing his chains, chains that they wove themselves because they believed he offered them redemption from sin, wealth, privilege, and everything else mortals have ever put stock in.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick nodded to the carnage left of the city. \'93If Kabraxis is responsible for that, I\'92d say the pirates and the priests aren\'92t going to find him any too thankful to be woke up.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Not woke up,\'94 Lhex said. \'93Returned to this world. The{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint114}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint114}Prime Evils helped work to seal him from this place because Kabraxis grew too powerful here.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He was no threat to them three, I\'92ll warrant,\'94 Maldrin declared. \'93Else I\'92d have heard tell of him, \'92cause that woulda been one damned bloody battle.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The wind ruffled the boy\'92s hair, and lightning seared the sky, painting his features the pale color of bone. \'93Diablo and his brothers feared Kabraxis. He\'92s a patient demon, one who works quietly and takes his time. If Kabraxis has a way into this world, we have to know. We have to be ready for him.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93My job is to get you back to Westmarch and to the king,\'94 Darrick said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92ll have to carry me,\'94 Lhex said. \'93I won\'92t go willingly.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Skipper,\'94 Maldrin said, \'93beggin\'92 yer pardon, but tryin\'92 to negotiate them cliffs while carryin\'92 a bellerin\'92 young \'92un ain\'92t gonna make for good or safe travelin\'92.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick already knew that. He took a deep breath, smelling the approaching storm on the wind, and hardened his voice. \'93Better I should leave you here and tell the king I didn\'92t get to you in time.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The boy\'92s dark eyes regarded Darrick for only a moment. \'93You won\'92t do that. You can\'92t.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick scowled fiercely, hoping to scare the boy.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And if you take me back without checking on the demon,\'94 Lhex threatened, \'93I\'92ll tell the king that you had the chance to find out more and you didn\'92t. After the troubles in Tristram, I don\'92t think my uncle will take kindly to a sailor derelict in his duty to find out as much as he could.\'94 The boy raised his eyebrows. \'93Do you?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick held his tongue for a moment, willing the boy to back down. But even if Lhex did, Darrick knew the truth of the boy\'92s words would weigh on him. The king\plain \f2\i\fs24 would\plain \f2\fs24 want to know. And despite the possibility of seeing a demon, which filled him with fear, Darrick was curious.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Darrick said. \'93I don\'92t think the king would take kindly to such a sailor at all.\'94 He raised his voice. \'93Maldrin.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint115}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint115}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye, skipper.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Can you and Mat and a couple others manage getting the waif back to the longboat on your own?\'94 Darrick stared at the boy. \'93If he agrees to be his most peaceable?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I can do that,\'94 Maldrin said grudgingly. \'93If it comes to it, I\'92ll tie him up an\'92 lower him by a rope down the mountainside.\'94 He glared at the boy for a moment, then turned his attention back to Darrick. \'93I don\'92t know that I agree that ye a-harin\'92 off right this minute is all that bright.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ve never been overly accused of brightness,\'94 Darrick said, but it was only bravado that he didn\'92t feel.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I ain\'92t gonna be left behind,\'94 Mat said, shaking his head. \'93No, if it\'92s to be demon huntin\'92 in the offin\'92, ye got to count me in, Darrick.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick looked at his oldest and best friend in the world. \'93Aye. I will, and glad to have you, but we\'92re not about to have a good time of it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat smiled. \'93It\'92ll be an adventure we can tell our grandkids about whilst we dandle \'92em on our knees in our dotage, me an\'92 ye.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I should go with you,\'94 Lhex interrupted.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick looked at the boy. \'93No. You\'92ve pushed this as far as needs be. You leave the matter with us now. The king wouldn\'92t be happy to hear that his nephew wasn\'92t amenable to being rescued by men who laid down their lives for him, either. Understand?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Reluctantly, the boy nodded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Now, you did yourself a good turn back on the pirate ship by getting yourself free,\'94 Darrick said. \'93I expect the same behavior while you\'92re with these men I\'92m asking to guard you with their lives. Have we got a bargain?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But I can identify the demon\'97\'94 the boy said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Boy,\'94 Darrick said, \'93I believe I\'92ll know a demon should I see one.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The coming storm continued to gather strength as Darrick led the group of sailors back into the ruins of the city. The moon disappeared often behind the dark, threatening{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint116}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint116}masses of storm clouds, leaving the world cluttered with black silk, then appeared again to draw harsh, long shadows against the silvered grounds. The alabaster columns and stones of the city blazed with an inner fire whenever moonlight touched them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sailors moved in silence, unencumbered by armor the way militiamen would be. The king\'92s army corps seldom went anywhere without the rattle and clangor of chainmail or plate. Those things were death to a man fighting on a ship if he somehow ended up in the water.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Finding the entrance to the underground cavern in the ruins turned out to be easy. Darrick held his group back, then followed the last of Raithen\'92s pirates down into the cleared path that led into the bowels of the earth beneath the remains of Tauruk\'92s Port.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  None of them spoke over the droning buzz that filled the cavern farther down. The dank earth blocked the wind, but it kept the wintry chill locked around Darrick. The cold made his body ache worse. The long climb up the cliff as well as the battles he\'92d fought had stripped him of energy, leaving him running on sheer adrenaline. He looked forward to his hammock aboard\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 and the few days\'92 journey it would take to reach Westmarch.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Fog or a dusty haze filled the cavern. The haze looked golden in the dim light of the lanterns Raithen\'92s pirates carried.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Gradually, the tunnel Darrick followed widened, and he saw the great door set into the stone wall on the other side of the immense cavern. The tunnel went no farther.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen and his pirates stopped before entering the main cavern area, and their position blocked Darrick\'92s view of what lay ahead. Several of the pirates seemed in favor of turning and fleeing, but Raithen held them firm with his harsh voice and the threat of his sword.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Hunkering down behind a slab of rock that had slid free during the excavation, Darrick stared into the cavern. Mat joined him, his breath rasping softly.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What\'92s wrong?\'94 Darrick whispered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint117}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint117}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It\'92s this damn dust,\'94 Mat whispered back. \'93Must not have settled from the explosion earlier. It\'92s tightenin\'92 me lungs up a mite.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taking the sleeve of his torn shirt in one hand, Darrick ripped it off and handed it to Mat. \'93Tie this around your face,\'94 he told his friend. \'93It\'92ll keep the dust out.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat accepted the garment remnant gratefully and tied it around his face.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick tore the other sleeve off and tied it around his own face. It was a pity because the shirt had been a favorite of his, though it was no comparison to the Kurastian silk shirts he had in his sea chest aboard\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star.\plain \f2\fs24 Still, growing up hard and without as he had, he treasured things and generally took good care of the ones he had.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Slowly and tentatively, Raithen led his pirates down into the cavern.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Darrick, look!\'94 Mat pointed, indicating the skeletons that lay in the cavern area. A few looked old, but most of them appeared to have been just stripped clean. Ragged clothing, torn but not aged, swaddled the skeletons.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I see them,\'94 Darrick said, and the hair at the back of his neck lifted. He wasn\'92t one for magic, and he knew he was looking at sure proof that magic had been recently worked.\plain \f2\i\fs24 We shouldn\'92t be here,\plain \f2\fs24 he told himself.\plain \f2\i\fs24 If I had any sense, I\'92d leave now before any of us are hurt.\plain \f2\fs24 In fact, he was just about to give the order when a man in black and scarlet robes stepped through the immense doorway in the far wall.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The man in scarlet and black looked as if he was in his early forties. His black hair held gray at the temples, and his face was lean and strong. A shimmering aura flowed around him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Captain Raithen,\'94 the man in scarlet and black greeted, but his words held little warmth.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The droning buzz increased in intensity.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Cholik,\'94 Raithen said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why aren\'92t you with the ships?\'94 Cholik asked. He{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint118}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint118}crossed the cavern floor, oblivious to the carnage of freshly dead men scattered around him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We were attacked,\'94 Raithen said. \'93Westmarch sailors set fire to my ships and stole the boy we held for ransom.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You were followed?\'94 Cholik\'92s anger cut through the droning noise that filled the cavern.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Who is that man?\'94 Mat whispered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick shook his head. \'93I don\'92t know. And I don\'92t see a demon around here, either. Let\'92s go. It\'92s not going to take that Cholik guy long to figure out what Raithen and his pirates are doing here.\'94 He turned and signaled to the other men, getting them ready to withdraw.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Maybe it wasn\'92t me who got followed,\'94 Raithen argued. \'93Maybe one of those men you buy information from in Westmarch got caught doing something and sold you out.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Cholik said. He stopped out of sword\'92s reach from the pirate captain. \'93The people who do business with me would be afraid to do something like that. If your ships were attacked, it was through your own gross ineptitude.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Maybe we should just skip all this faultfinding,\'94 Raithen suggested.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And then what should we do, captain?\'94 Cholik regarded the pirate captain with contempt and cold amusement. \'93Get to the part where you and your murderous crew kill me and try to take whatever it is that you\'92ve imagined I\'92ve found here?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen grinned without humor. \'93Not a very pretty way to put it, but that\'92s about it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik drew his robes in with imperious grace. \'93No. That won\'92t be done this night.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Striding forward, Raithen said, \'93I don\'92t know what kind of night you had planned for yourself, Cholik, but I aim to get what I came for. My men and I have spent blood for you, and the way we figure it, we haven\'92t gotten much in return.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Your greed is going to get you killed,\'94 Cholik threatened.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint119}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint119}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Raithen brandished his sword. \'93It\'92ll get you killed first.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A massive shape stepped through the door in the stone wall. Darrick stared at the demon, taking in the writhing snake hair, the barbaric features, the huge three-fingered hands, and the black skin slashed through with pale blue.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint120}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint120}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  TEN
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Raithen and his pirates drew back from the demon, filled with fear as the nightmare from the Burning Hells strode into the cavern. Men yelled in terror and retreated quickly.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \'93Okay,\'94 Mat whispered, fear shining in his eyes, \'93we can tell the boy an\'92 his uncle the king that the demon exists. Let\'92s be away from here.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Wait,\'94 Darrick said, mastering the thrumming fear that filled him at the sight of the demon. He peered over the stone slab they hid behind.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93For what?\'94 Mat gave him a disbelieving look. He made the sign of the Light in the air before him unconsciously, like the child he\'92d been when they\'92d attended church in Hillsfar.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Do you know how many men have seen a demon?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93An\'92 them livin\'92 to tell about it? Damned few. An\'92 ye want to know why, Darrick? \'92Cause they were killed by the demons they was gawkin\'92 at instead of runnin\'92 as any sane man should do.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Captain Raithen,\'94 the demon said, and his voice rolled like thunder inside the cavern. \'93I am Kabraxis, called the Enlightener. There is no need for disharmony between yourself and Buyard Cholik. You can continue to work together.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93For you?\'94 Raithen asked. His voice held fear and awe, but he stood before the demon with his sword in his fist.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 the demon replied. \'93Through me, you can find the true path to your future.\'94 He strode forward, stepping in front of the priest. \'93I can help you. I can bring you peace.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint121}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint121}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Peace I can find in the bottom of a cup of ale,\'94 Raithen said, \'93but I\'92ll not resort to serving demon scum.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick thought the reply would have sounded better if the pirate captain\'92s voice hadn\'92t been shaking, but he didn\'92t doubt that he would have had trouble controlling his own voice if he\'92d spoken to the demon.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then you can die,\'94 Kabraxis said, waving a hand in an intricate pattern before him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Archers!\'94 Raithen yelled. \'93Feather that hell-spawned beast!\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The pirates were stunned by the presence of the demon and slow to react. Only a few of them nocked and released arrows. The dozen or so arrows that hit the demon glanced off, leaving no sign that they had ever touched him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Darrick,\'94 Mat pleaded desperately, \'93the others have already gone.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Glancing over his shoulder, Darrick saw that it was true. The other sailors who had accompanied them were already beating a hasty retreat.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat pulled at Darrick\'92s shoulder. \'93C\'92mon. There\'92s naught we can do here. Gettin\'92 ourselves safe an\'92 to home, that\'92s our job now.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick nodded, getting up from behind the stone slab just as waves of shimmering force shot out from the demon\'92s hand.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
