\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Twice, as the current roiled and changed, Mat was nearly torn from Darrick\'92s grip. The water was cold enough to numb his hands, and the exhaustion he felt turned him weak.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Mat!\'94 he screamed in his friend\'92s ear, then went down again. He managed to call out to Mat twice more as they raced down the river but didn\'92t get any reaction. Mat remained dead weight in his arms.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lightning strobed the sky again, and this time Darrick thought he spotted blood on his elbow. It wasn\'92t his blood, and he knew it had to have come from Mat. But when the next wave hit him and he resurfaced, the blood wasn\'92t there, and he couldn\'92t be sure if it ever was.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Darrick!\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Maldrin\'92s voice came out of the night without warning.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick tried to turn his head, but the effort sent him plunging below the waterline again. He kicked the water fiercely, keeping Mat elevated. When he rose again, thunder boomed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93\'97rick!\'94 Maldrin squalled again in his huge voice that could reach the top of the rigging or empty a tavern of sailors that crewed aboard\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Here!\'94 Darrick yelled, spluttering, spitting water. \'93Here, Maldrin!\'94 He sank, then fought his way up again. Each time was getting harder. The skeleton remained clinging to Mat\'92s leg, and twice Darrick had to kick free of its embrace. \'93Hang on, Mat. Please hang on. It\'92s only a little longer now. Maldrin\'92s\'97\'94 The current took him down again, and this time he spotted light from a lantern on his port side.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93\'97see them!\'94 Maldrin roared. \'93Hold this damn boat, lads!\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint131}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint131}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick came up again, seeing a thick black shadow rising up from behind him, then lightning split the sky and reflected from the dark water, illuminating Maldrin\'92s homely features for a moment.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I got ye, skipper!\'94 Maldrin yelled above the storm. \'93I got ye. Just ye come back on ahead to ol\'92 Maldrin, an\'92 let me take some of that weight from ye.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  For a moment, Darrick feared that the mate was going to miss him. Then he felt Maldrin take hold of his hair\'97the easiest part of a drowning victim to grab hold of\'97and would have screamed with agony if he hadn\'92t been choking on water. Then, incredibly, Maldrin pulled him back toward the longboat they\'92d arrived in.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Give a hand!\'94 Maldrin yelled.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Tomas reached down and hooked his hands under Mat\'92s arms, then leaned back and started pulling him into the longboat. \'93I\'92ve got him, Darrick. Let him go.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Freed from Mat\'92s weight, Darrick\'92s arms slid away limply. If it hadn\'92t been for Maldrin holding him, he was sure he would have been swept away by the current. He fought to help Maldrin pull him on board, catching a glimpse of the boy, Lhex, wrapped in a blanket that was already soaked through from the rain.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We waited for ye, skipper,\'94 Maldrin said as he pulled. \'93Held steady to our course \'92cause we knew ye\'92d be here. Hadn\'92t ever been a time ye didn\'92t make it, no matter how bollixed up things looked like they was a-gettin\'92.\'94 He slapped Darrick on the shoulder. \'93An\'92 ye done us proud again. We\'92ll have stories to tell after this \'92un. I\'92ll swear to ye on that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Something\'92s holdin\'92 him,\'94 Tomas said, fighting to bring Mat onto the longboat.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Skeleton,\'94 Darrick said. \'93It\'92s holding on to his leg.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Without warning, the undead thing erupted from the water, lunging at Tomas with an open mouth like a hungry wolf. Galvanized by his fear, Tomas yanked back, pulling Mat into the longboat with him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Calmly, as if he were reaching for a dish at a tavern, Maldrin picked up his war hammer and smashed the{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint132}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint132}skeleton\'92s skull. Going limp, the undead creature released its hold and disappeared into the whitecapped water.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick\'92s chest heaved as he sucked in huge lungfuls of air. \'93River\'92s full of skeletons. They followed us in. They can\'92t swim, but they\'92re in the water. If they find the boat anchor\'97\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The longboat suddenly shuddered and swung sideways, no longer pointed into the current so that it could ride out the gorged river easier. It bucked like a mustang, throwing all the sailors aboard it around as if they were ragdolls.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Something\'92s got hold of the rope!\'94 one of the sailors yelled.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Shoving the other sailors aside, Maldrin raked a knife from his boot and sawed through the anchor rope as skeletal hands grabbed the longboat\'92s gunwales. The boat leapt into the river, cutting across the whitecaps like a thing possessed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Man those oars!\'94 Maldrin bawled, grabbing one from the middle of the longboat himself. \'93Get this damn boat squared away afore we all go down with it!\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Struggling against the exhaustion that filled him as well as the longboat being tossed like a child\'92s toy on the rushing river, Darrick pushed himself up and crawled over to Mat Hu-Ring. \'93Mat!\'94 he called.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lightning flashed, and thunder filled the river canyon through the Hawk\'92s Beak Mountains.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Mat.\'94 Tenderly, Darrick rolled Mat\'92s head over, sickened at once by how lax and loose it was on his neck.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat\'92s face kept rolling, coming around to face Darrick. The wide dark eyes stared sightlessly up, capturing the next reflection of the wicked lightning in them. The right side of Mat\'92s head was covered with blood, and white pieces of bone stuck out from the dark hair.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He\'92s dead,\'94 Tomas said as he pulled on his oar. \'93I\'92m sorry, Darrick. I know ye two was close.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  No!\plain \f2\fs24 Darrick couldn\'92t believe it\'97\plain \f2\i\fs24 wouldn\'92t\plain \f2\fs24 believe it. Mat couldn\'92t be dead. Not handsome and witty and funny Mat. Not Mat who could always be counted on to say the right{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint133}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint133}things to the girls in the dives in the port cities they visited on their rounds. Not Mat who had helped nurse him back to health those times Darrick\'92s punishment from his father laid him up for days in the loft above the butcher\'92s barn.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Darrick said. But his denial was weak even in his ears. He stared at the corpse of his friend.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Like as not he went sudden.\'94 Maldrin spoke quietly behind Darrick. \'93He musta hit his head on a rock. Or maybe that skeleton he was fightin\'92 with done for him.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick remembered the way Mat had struck the cliffside on the long fall from the canyon ridge.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I knew he was dead as soon as I touched him,\'94 Maldrin said. \'93There wasn\'92t nothin\'92 ye could do, Darrick. Every man that took this assignment from Cap\'92n Tollifer knew what our chances was goin\'92 in. Just bad luck. That\'92s all it was.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick sat in the middle of the longboat, feeling the rain beat down on him, hearing the thunder crash in the heavens above him. His eyes burned, but he didn\'92t let himself cry. He\'92d never let himself cry. His father had taught him that crying only made things hurt worse.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Did you see the demon?\'94 the boy asked, touching Darrick\'92s arm.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick didn\'92t answer. In that brief moment of learning of Mat\'92s death, he hadn\'92t even thought of Kabraxis.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Was the demon there?\'94 Lhex asked again. \'93I\'92m sorry for your friend, but I have to know.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick answered through his constricted throat. \'93Aye, the demon was there right enough. He caused this. Might as well have killed Mat himself. Him and that priest.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Several of the sailors touched their good luck charms at the mention of the demon. They pulled at their oars in response to Maldrin\'92s shouted orders, but it was primarily to direct the craft. The swollen river propelled the longboat swiftly.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Upriver, lantern lights burned aboard the single cog fighting the mooring tether as the river rushed against it.{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint134}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint134}Captain Raithen\'92s crew waited there, Darrick guessed. They didn\'92t know the captain wasn\'92t coming.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Giving in to the overwhelming emotion and exhaustion that filled him, Darrick stretched out over Mat\'92s body, as if he were going to protect him from the gale winds and the rain, the way Mat used to do for him when he was racked with fever while getting well from one of his father\'92s beatings. Darrick smelled the blood on Mat, and it reminded him of the blood that had been ever present in his father\'92s shop.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Before Darrick knew it, he fell into the waiting blackness, and he never wanted to return.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint135}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint135}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  ELEVEN
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Darrick lay in his hammock aboard\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star,\plain \f2\fs24 his hands folded behind his head, and tried not to think of the dreams that had plagued him the last two nights. In those dreams, Mat was still alive, but Darrick still lived with his parents in the butcher\'92s shop in Hillsfar. Since he had left, Darrick had never gone back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Over the years since his departure from the town, Mat had gone back to visit with his family on special occasions, arriving there by merchant ship and signing on as a cargo guard while on leave from the Westmarch Navy. Darrick had always suspected that Mat hadn\'92t visited his home or his family as much as he had wanted to. But Mat had believed there would be plenty of time. That was Mat\'92s nature: he never hurried about anything, took each thing in its time and place.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Now, Mat would never go home again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick seized the pain that filled him before it could escape his control. That control was rock-solid. He\'92d built it carefully, through beating after beating, through bald cruel things his father had said, till that control was just as strong and as sure as a blacksmith\'92s anvil.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He shifted his head, feeling the ache in his back, neck, and shoulders from all the climbing he\'92d done the night before last. Turning his head, he gazed out the porthole at the glittering blue-green water of the Gulf of Westmarch. Judging from the way the light hit the ocean, it was noon\'97almost time.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lying in the hammock, sipping his breaths, stilling himself and controlling the pain that threatened to overflow{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint136}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint136}even the boundaries he\'92d put up, he waited. He tried counting his heartbeats, feeling them echo in his head, but waiting was hard when he measured the time. It was better to go numb and let nothing touch him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Then the deck pipe played, blasting shrill and somehow sweet over the constant wave splash of the ocean, calling the ship\'92s crew together.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick closed his eyes and worked on imagining nothing, remembering nothing. But the sour scent of the moldy hay in the loft above the pens where his father kept the animals waiting to be slain and bled out filled his nose. Before Darrick knew it, a brief glimpse of Mat Hu-Ring, nine years old in clothing that was too big for him, flipped down from the rooftop and landed inside the loft. Mat had climbed the chimney of the smokehouse attached to the barn behind the butcher\'92s shop and made his way across the roof until he was able to enter the loft.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Hey,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat said, digging in the pockets of the loose shirt he wore and producing cheese and apples.\plain \f2\i\fs24 I didn\'92t see you around yesterday. I thought I\'92d find you up here.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  In his shame, his body covered with bruises, Darrick had tried to act mad at Mat and make him go away. But it was hard to be convincing when he had to be so quiet. Getting loud enough to attract his father\'92s attention\'97and let his father know someone else was aware of his punishment\'97was out of the question. After Mat had spread the apples and cheese out, adding a wilted flower to make it more of a feast and a joke, Darrick hadn\'92t been able to keep up the pretense, and even embarrassment hadn\'92t curbed his hunger.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  If his father had ever once found out about Mat\'92s visits during those times, Darrick knew he would never have seen Mat again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick opened his eyes and stared up at the unmarked ceiling. Just as he would never see him again now. Darrick reached for the cold numbness that he used to cover himself when things became too much. It slipped on like armor, each piece fitting the others perfectly. No weakness remained within him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint137}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint137}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The shrill pipe played again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Without warning, the door to the officers\'92 quarters opened.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick didn\'92t look. Whoever it was could go away, and would if he knew what was good for him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Mr. Lang,\'94 a strong, imperious voice spoke.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Hurriedly, reflexes overcoming even the pain of loss and the walls he\'92d erected, Darrick twisted in the hammock, fell out of it expertly even though the ship broke through oncoming waves at the moment, and landed on his feet at attention. \'93Aye, sir,\'94 Darrick answered quickly.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Captain Tollifer stood at the entranceway. He was a tall, solid man in his late forties. Gray touched the lamb-chop whiskers he wore surrounding a painfully clean-shaven face. The captain had his hair pulled back in a proper queue and wore his best Westmarch Navy uniform, green with gold piping. He carried a tricorn hat in his hand. His boots shone like fresh-polished ebony.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Mr. Lang,\'94 the captain said, \'93have you had occasion to have your hearing checked of late?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It\'92s been a while, sir,\'94 Darrick said, standing stiffly at attention.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then may I suggest that when we reach port in Westmarch the day after tomorrow, the Light willing, you report to a doctor of such things and find out.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Of course, sir,\'94 Darrick said. \'93I will, sir.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I only mention this, Mr. Lang,\'94 Captain Tollifer said, \'93because I clearly heard the pipe blow all hands on deck.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye, sir. As did I.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Tollifer raised an inquisitive eyebrow.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I thought I might be excused from this, sir,\'94 Darrick said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It\'92s a funeral for one of the men in my command,\'94 Tollifer said. \'93A man who died bravely in the performance of his duties. No one is excused from one of those.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Begging the captain\'92s pardon,\'94 Darrick said, \'93I thought I might be excused because Mat Hu-Ring was my friend.\'94\plain \f2\i\fs24 I was the one who got him killed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint138}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint138}\plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93A friend\'92s place is beside his friend.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick kept his voice cold and detached, glad that he felt the same way inside. \'93There\'92s nothing left that I can do for him. That body out there isn\'92t Mat Hu-Ring.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You can stand for him, Mr. Lang,\'94 the captain said, \'93in front of his peers and his friends. I think Mr. Hu-Ring would expect that of you. Just as he would expect me to have this talk with you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye, sir.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then I\'92ll expect you to clean yourself up properly,\'94 Captain Tollifer said, \'93and get yourself topside in relatively short order.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye, sir.\'94 Even with all his respect for the captain and fear of his position, Darrick barely restrained the scathing rebuttal that came to mind. His grief for Mat was his own, not property of the Westmarch Navy.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The captain turned to go, then stopped at the door and spoke, looking at Darrick earnestly. \'93I\'92ve lost friends before, Mr. Lang. It\'92s never easy. We perform the funerals so that we may begin letting go in a proper fashion. It isn\'92t to forget them but only to remind ourselves that some closure is given in death and to help us mark an eternal place for them in our hearts. A few good men are born into this world who should never be forgotten. Mr. Hu-Ring was one of those, and I feel privileged to have served with him and known him. I won\'92t be saying that in the address topside because you know I stand on policy and procedure aboard my ship, but I wanted you to know that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Thank you, sir,\'94 Darrick said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The captain placed his hat on his head. \'93I\'92ll give you a reasonable amount of time to get ready, Mr. Lang. Please be prompt.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye, sir.\'94 Darrick watched the captain go, feeling the pain boiling over inside him, turning to anger that drew to it like a lodestone all the old rage he\'92d kept bottled up for so long. He closed his eyes, trembling, then released his pent-up breath and sealed the emotions away.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  When he opened his eyes, he told himself he felt nothing.{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint139}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint139}He was an automaton. If he felt nothing, he couldn\'92t be hurt. His father had taught him that.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mechanically, ignoring even the aches and pains that filled him from that night, Darrick went to the foot of his hammock and opened his sea chest. Since the night at Tauruk\'92s Port, he hadn\'92t been returned to active duty. None of the crew had except Maldrin, who couldn\'92t be expected to lie abed on a ship when there was so much to do.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick chose a clean uniform, shaved quickly with the straight razor without nicking himself too badly, and dressed. There were three other junior officers aboard\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star;\plain \f2\fs24 he was senior among them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Striding out on deck, pulling on the white gloves that were demanded at ceremonial occasions, Darrick looked past the faces of the men as they stared at him. He was neutral, untouchable. They would see nothing on him today because there was nothing to see. He returned their crisp salutes proficiently.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The noonday sun hung high above\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star.\plain \f2\fs24 Light struck the sea, glittering in the blue-green troughs between the white rollers like a spray of gemstones. The rigging and canvas sheets above creaked and snapped in the wind as the ship plunged toward Westmarch, carrying the news of the pirate chieftain\'92s death as well as the unbelievable return of a demon to the world of man. The men aboard\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 had talked of little else since the rescue crew\'92s return to the ship, and Darrick knew all of Westmarch would soon be buzzing with the news as well. The impossible had happened.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick took his place beside the three other junior officers at the forefront of the sailors. All three of the officers were much younger than he, one of them still in his teens and already knowing command because his father had purchased a commission for him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A momentary flicker of resentment touched Darrick\'92s heart as they stood beside Mat\'92s flag-covered body on the plank balanced on the starboard railing. None of the other{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint140}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint140}officers deserved those positions; they had not been true sailing men like Mat. Darrick had chosen to follow his own career and become an officer when offered, but Mat never had. Captain Tollifer had never seen fit to extend a commission to Mat, though Darrick had never understood why. As a rule, such a promotion wasn\'92t done much, and hardly ever was it done aboard the same ship. But Captain Tollifer had done just such a thing.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The officers standing beside Darrick had never known a bosun\'92s lash for failing to carry out a captain\'92s orders or for failing to carry them out to their full extent. Darrick had, and he\'92d borne those injuries and insults with the same stoic resolve his father had trained him to have. Darrick hadn\'92t been afraid to take command in the field even when under orders. In the beginning, such behavior had earned him floggings under hard captains who refused to acknowledge his reinterpretation of their commands, but under Captain Tollifer, Darrick had come into his own.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Mat had never been interested in becoming an officer. He\'92d enjoyed the hard life of a sailor.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  During their years aboard the ships of the Westmarch Navy, Darrick had often thought that he had been taking care of Mat, looking out for his friend. But looking at the sheet-draped body in front of him, Darrick knew that Mat had never been that interested in the sea.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  What would you have done? Where would you have gone if I had not pulled you here?\plain \f2\fs24 The questions hung in Darrick\'92s mind like gulls riding a favorable wind. He pushed them away. He wouldn\'92t allow himself to be touched by pain or confusion.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Andregai played the pipes, standing at Captain Tollifer\'92s side on the stern castle. The wind whipped the captain\'92s great military cloak around him. The boy\'97Lhex, the king\'92s nephew\'97stood at the captain\'92s side. When the pipes finished playing and the last echoing sad note faded away, the captain delivered the ship\'92s eulogy, speaking with quiet dignity of Mat Hu-Ring\'92s service and devotion to the Westmarch Navy and that he gave his life while rescuing{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint141}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint141}the king\'92s nephew. Despite the scattering of facts, the address was formal, almost impersonal.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick listened to the drone of words, the call of gulls sailing after\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 and hoping for a trail of scraps to be left behind on the water.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Slain while rescuing the king\'92s nephew. That\'92s not how it was. Mat was killed while on a fool\'92s errand, and for worrying about me. I got him killed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick looked at the ship\'92s crew around him. Despite the action two nights ago, Mat had been the only one killed. Maybe some of the crew believed, as Maldrin said he did, that it was all just bad luck, but Darrick knew that some of them believed it was he who had killed Mat by staying too long in the cavern.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  When Captain Tollifer finished speaking, the pipes played again and the mournful sound filled the ship\'92s deck. Maldrin, clad in sailor\'92s dress whites that were worn only on inspection days or while at anchorage in Westmarch, stepped up on the other side of Mat\'92s flagcovered body on the plank. Five more sailors joined him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The pipes blew again, a going-away tune that always wished the listeners a safe trip. It was known in every maritime province Darrick had ever visited.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  When the pipes finished, Maldrin looked to Darrick, a question in his old gray eyes.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick steeled himself and gave an imperceptible nod.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93All right, then, lads,\'94 Maldrin whispered. \'93Easy as ye does it, an\'92 with all the respect ye can muster.\'94 The mate grabbed the plank and started it up, tilting it on its axis, and the other five men\'97two on one side with him and three on the other\'97lifted together. Maldrin kept a firm grip on the Westmarch flag. Maybe they covered the dead given to the sea, but the flags were not abandoned.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  As one, Darrick and the other officers turned to the starboard side, followed a half-second later by the sailors, all of them standing at rigid attention.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93For every man who dies for Westmarch,\'94 the captain spoke, \'93let him know that Westmarch lives for him.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The other officers and the crew repeated the rote saying.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint142}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint142}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick said nothing. He watched in stony silence and kept himself dwindled down to a small ember. Nothing touched him as Mat\'92s shroud-wrapped body slid from under the Westmarch flag and plummeted down the ship\'92s side to the rolling waves. The ballast rocks wrapped into the foot of the shroud to weight the body dragged it down into the blue-green sea. For a time, the white of the funeral shroud kept Mat\'92s body visible.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Then even that disappeared before the ship sailed on and left it behind.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The pipes blew the disassembly, and the men drifted away.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick walked to the railing, easily riding the rise and fall of the ship that had once made him so sick in the beginning. He peered out at the ocean, but he didn\'92t see it. The stink of the blood and the soured hay in his father\'92s barn filled his nose and took his mind away from the ship and the sea. His heart hurt with the roughened leather strokes his father had used to punish him until only the feel of his fists against Darrick\'92s body would satisfy him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He made himself feel nothing at all, not even the wind that pushed into his face and ruffled his hair. He had lived much of his life numb. It had been his mistake to retreat from that.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  That night, having not eaten at all during the day because it would have meant taking mess with the other men and dealing with all the unasked questions each had, Darrick went down to the galley. Cook usually left a pot of chowder hanging over a low fire during the dogwatches.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick helped himself to the chowder, catching the young kitchen apprentice half dozing at the long table where the crew supped in shifts. Darrick filled a tin plate with the thick chowder. The young kitchen apprentice fidgeted, then got to wiping the table as if he\'92d been doing that all along.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Without speaking, ignoring the young man\'92s embarrassment{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint143}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint143}and concern that his laxness at his duties might be reported, Darrick carved a thick hunk of black bread from one of the loaves Cook had prepared, then poured himself a mug of green tea. Tea in one hand, thick hunk of bread soaking in the chowder in the tin plate, Darrick headed back up to the deck.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He stood amidships, listening to the rustle and crackle of the canvas overhead. With the knowledge they carried and the fact that they were in clear waters, Captain Tollifer had kept the sails up, taking advantage of the favorable winds.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 sloshed through the moon-kissed rollers that covered the ocean\'92s surface. Occasional light flickers passed by in the water that weren\'92t just reflections of the ship\'92s lanterns posted as running lights.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Standing on the heaving deck on practiced legs, Darrick ate, managing the teacup and the tin plate in one hand\'97plate on the cup\'97and eating with his other hand. He let the black bread marinate in the chowder to soften it up, otherwise he\'92d have had to chew it for what seemed like forever to break it down. The chowder was made from shrimp and fish stock, mixed with spices from the eastern lands, and had thick chunks of potatoes. It was almost hot enough to burn the tongue even after being dipped on bread and cooled by the night winds.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick didn\'92t let himself think of the nights he and Mat had shared dogwatches together, with Mat telling wildly improbable stories he\'92d either heard somewhere or made up then and there and swore it was gospel. It had all been fun to Mat, something to keep them awake during the long, dead hours and to keep Darrick from ever thinking back to the things that had happened in Hillsfar.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92m sorry about your friend,\'94 a quiet voice said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Distanced as he was from his emotions, Darrick wasn\'92t even surprised to recognize Lhex\'92s voice behind him. He kept gazing out to sea, chewing on the latest lump of black bread and chowder he\'92d put into his mouth.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I said\'97\'94 the boy began again in a slightly louder voice.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I heard you,\'94 Darrick interrupted.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint144}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint144}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  An uncomfortable silence stretched between them. Darrick never once turned to face the boy.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I wanted to talk to you about the demon,\'94 Lhex said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Darrick replied.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I am the king\'92s nephew.\'94 The boy\'92s tone hardened somewhat.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And yet you are not the king, are you?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I understand how you\'92re feeling.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Good. Then you\'92ll understand if I trouble you for my own peace while I\'92m standing watch.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The boy was silent for a long enough time that Darrick had thought he\'92d gone away. Darrick thought there might have been some trouble with the captain in the morning over his rudeness, but he didn\'92t care.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What are those lighted patches in the water?\'94 Lhex asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Irritated and not even wanting to feel that because long years of experience had shown him that even the smallest emotion could snowball into the feelings of entrapment that put him out of control, Darrick turned to the boy. \'93What the hell are you still doing up, boy?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I couldn\'92t sleep.\'94 The boy stood on the deck in bare feet and a sleeping gown he must have borrowed from the captain.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then go find a new way of amusing yourself. I\'92ll not have it done at my expense.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lhex wrapped his arms around himself, obviously chilled in the cool night air. \'93I can\'92t. You\'92re the only one who saw the demon.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  The only one alive,\plain \f2\fs24 Darrick thought, but he stopped himself before he could think too far. \'93There were other men in that cavern.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93None of them stayed long enough to see the things you saw.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You don\'92t know things I saw.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I was there when you talked with the captain. Everything you know is important.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And what matter would it be of yours?\'94 Darrick demanded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint145}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint145}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ve been priest-trained for the Zakarum Church and guided my whole life by the Light. In two more years, I\'92ll test for becoming a full priest.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92re no more than a boy now,\'94 Darrick chided, \'93and you\'92ll be little more than a boy then. You should spend your time worrying about boy things.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Lhex said. \'93Fighting demons is to be my calling, Darrick Lang. Don\'92t you have a calling?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I work to keep a meal between my belly and my spine,\'94 Darrick said, \'93to stay alive, and to sleep in warm places.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yet you\'92re an officer, and you\'92ve come up through the ranks, which is both an admirable and a hard thing to do. A man without a calling, without passion, could not have done something like that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick grimaced. Evidently Lhex\'92s identity as the king\'92s nephew had drawn considerable depth in Captain Tollifer\'92s eyes.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92m going to be a good priest,\'94 the boy declared. \'93And to fight demons, I know I have to learn about demons.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93None of this has anything to do with me,\'94 Darrick said. \'93Once Captain Tollifer hands my report to the king, my part in this is finished.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lhex eyed him boldly. \'93Is it?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye, it is.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You didn\'92t strike me as the kind of man who\'92d let a friend\'92s death go unavenged.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And who, then, am I supposed to blame for Mat\'92s death?\'94 Darrick demanded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Your friend died by Kabraxis\'92s hand,\'94 Lhex said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But not till you made us go there after I told you all I wanted to do was leave,\'94 Darrick said in a harsh voice. \'93Not till I waited too long to get out of that cavern, then couldn\'92t outrun the skeletons that pursued us.\'94 He shook his head. \'93No. If anybody\'92s to blame for Mat\'92s death, it\'92s you and me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A serious look filled the boy\'92s face. \'93If you want to blame me, Darrick Lang, then feel free to blame me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint146}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint146}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Vulnerable, feeling his emotions shudder and almost slip from his control, Darrick looked at the boy, amazed at the way he could stand up to him in the dark night. \'93I do blame you,\'94 Darrick told him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lhex looked away.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If you choose to fight demons,\'94 Darrick went on, giving in to the cruelty that ran within him, \'93you\'92ll have a short life. At least you won\'92t need a lot of planning.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The demons must be fought,\'94 the boy whispered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Not by the likes of me,\'94 Darrick said. \'93A king with an army, or several kings with armies, that\'92s what it would take. Not a sailor.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You lived after seeing the demon,\'94 Lhex said. \'93There must be a reason for that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I was lucky,\'94 Darrick said. \'93Most men meeting demons don\'92t have such luck.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Warriors and priests fight demons,\'94 Lhex said. \'93The legends tell us that without those heroes, Diablo and his brothers would still be able to walk through this world.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You were there when I gave Captain Tollifer my report,\'94 Darrick said. The boy hadn\'92t shown any reluctance to throw his weight around with the captain, either, and Tollifer had reluctantly allowed him to sit in during the debriefing the morning before. \'93You know everything I know.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93There are seers who could examine you. Sometimes when great magic is worked around an individual, traces of it remain within that individual.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ll not be poked and prodded,\'94 Darrick argued. He pointed to the patches of light gliding through the sea. \'93You asked what those were.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lhex turned his attention to the ocean, but his expression revealed that he\'92d rather be following his own tack in the conversation.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Some of those,\'94 Darrick said, \'93are fire-tail sharks, named so because they glow in such a manner. The light attracts nocturnal feeders and brings them within striking distance of the sharks. Other light patches are Rose of{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint147}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint147}Moon jellyfish that can paralyze a man unlucky enough to swim into reach of their barbed tentacles. If you want to learn about the sea, there\'92s much I can teach you. But if you want to talk about demons, I\'92ll have no more of it. I\'92ve learned more than I ever care to know about them.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The wind changed directions slightly, causing the great canvas sheets overhead to luff a little, then to snap full again as the crew managed the change.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick tasted his chowder but found it had grown cold.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Kabraxis is responsible for your friend\'92s death,\'94 Lhex said quietly. \'93You\'92re not going to be able to forget that. You\'92re still part of this. I have seen the signs.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick pushed his breath out, feeling trapped and scared and angry at the same time. He felt exactly the way he had when he had been in his father\'92s shop when his father had chosen to be displeased with him again. Working hard to distance himself, he waited until he had control back, then whirled to face the boy, intending\'97even if he was the king\'92s nephew\'97to vent some of his anger.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  But when Darrick turned, the deck behind him was empty. In the moonlight, the deck looked silver white, striped by the shadows of the masts and rigging. Frustrated, Darrick turned back and flung his plate and teacup over the ship\'92s side.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A Rose of Moon jellyfish caught the tin plate in its tentacles. Lightning flickered against the metal as the barbs tried to bite into it.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Crossing to the starboard railing, Darrick leaned on it heavily. In his mind\'92s eye, he saw the skeleton dive at Mat, sweeping him from the cliff\'92s edge, then witnessed again the bone-breaking thump against the wall of stone. A cold sweat covered Darrick\'92s body as memory of those days in his father\'92s shop stole over him. He would not go back there\'97not physically, and not in his mind.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint148}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint148}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  TWELVE
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Darrick sat at a back table in Cross-Eyed Sal\'92s, a tavern only a couple of blocks back from Dock Street and the Mercantile Quarter. The tavern was a dive, one of the places surly sailors of meager means or ill luck ended up before they signed ship\'92s articles and went back to sea. It was a place where the lanterns were kept dim of an evening so the wenches there looked better if they weren\'92t seen as well, and the food couldn\'92t be inspected closely.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Money came into Westmarch through the piers, in the fat purses of merchants buying goods and selling goods, and in the modest coin pouches of sailors and longshoremen. The money spilled over to the shops scattered along the docks and piers first, and most of it stopped there. Little of it slopped over into the businesses crowded in back of the shops and tradesmen\'92s workplaces and the finer inns and even not-so-fine inns.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cross-Eyed Sal\'92s featured a sun-faded sign out front that showed a buxom red-haired woman served up on a steaming oyster shell with only her tresses maintaining her modesty. The tavern was located in part of the decaying layer that occupied the stretch of older buildings that had been built higher up on the hillside fronting the harbor. Over the years as Westmarch and the harbor had existed and grown, nearly all of the buildings nestled down by the sea had been torn down and rebuilt.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Only a few older buildings remained as landmarks that had been shored up by expert artisans. But behind those businesses that seined up most of the gold lay the insular layer of merchants and tavern owners who barely made{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint149}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint149}their monthly bills and the king\'92s taxes so they could stay open. The only thing that kept them going was the desperate times endured by out-of-work sailors and longshoremen.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cross-Eyed Sal\'92s had a rare crowd and was filled near to capacity. The sailors remained separate from the longshoremen because of the long-standing feud between the two groups. Sailors looked down on longshoremen for not having the guts to go to sea, and longshoremen looked down on sailors for not being a true part of the community. Both groups, however, stayed well away from the mercenaries who had shown up in the last few days.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 had returned to Westmarch nine days ago and still awaited new orders. Darrick drank alone at the table. During his leave from the ship, he\'92d remained solitary. Most of the men aboard\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 had hung around him because of Mat. Blessed with his good humor and countless stories, Mat had never lacked for company, friendship, or a full mug of ale at any gathering.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  None of the crew had made an attempt to spend much time with Darrick. Besides the captain\'92s frowning disapproval of an officer\'92s fraternization with crew, Darrick had never proven himself to be good company all the time. And with Mat dead now, Darrick wanted no company at all.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  During the past nine days, Darrick had slept aboard the ship rather than in the arms of any of the many willing women, and he\'92d marked time in one dive after another much like Cross-Eyed Sal\'92s. Normally, Mat would have dragged Darrick into any number of festive inns or gotten them invitations to events hosted by the lesser politicos in Westmarch. Somehow, Mat had managed to meet several wives and courtesans of those men while investigating Westmarch\'92s museums, art galleries, and churches\'97interests that Darrick had not shared. Darrick had even found the parties annoying.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick found the bottom of his mulled wine again and looked around for the tavern wench who had been serving{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint150}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint150}him. She stood three tables away, in the crook of a big mercenary\'92s arm. Her laughter seemed obscene to Darrick, and his anger rose before he could throttle it.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Girl,\'94 he called impatiently, thumping the tin tankard against the scarred tabletop.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The wench extricated herself from the mercenary\'92s grasp, giggling and pushing against him in a manner meant to free herself and be seductive at the same time. She made her way across the packed room and took Darrick\'92s tankard.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The group of mercenaries scowled at Darrick and talked among themselves in low voices.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick ignored them and leaned back against the wall behind him. He\'92d been in bars like this before countless times, and he\'92d seen hundreds of men like the mercenaries. Normally he was among ship\'92s crew, for it was Captain Tollifer\'92s standing order that no crewman drink alone. But since they\'92d been in port this time, Darrick had only drunk alone, making his way back to the ship each morning before daybreak any time he didn\'92t have an early watch.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The wench brought back Darrick\'92s filled tankard. He paid her, adding a modest tip that drew no favoring glance. Normally Mat would have parted generously with his money, endearing himself to the serving wenches. Tonight, Darrick didn\'92t care. All he wanted was a full tankard till he took his leave.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He returned his attention to the cold food on the wooden serving platter before him. The meal consisted of stringy meat and scorched potatoes, covered with flecks of thin gravy that looked no more appetizing than hound saliva. The tavern could get away with such weak fare because the city was burgeoning with mercenaries feeding at the king\'92s coffers. Darrick took a bit of meat and chewed it, watching as the big mercenary got up from his table, flanked by two of his friends.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Under the table, Darrick pulled his cutlass across his lap. He\'92d made a practice of eating with his left hand, leaving his right hand free.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint151}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint151}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Hey there, swabbie,\'94 the big mercenary growled, pulling out the chair across the table from Darrick and seating himself uninvited. The way he pronounced the term let Darrick know the man had meant the address as an insult.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Although the longshoremen rode the sailors about being visitors to the city and not truly of it, the mercenaries were even less so. Mercenaries touted themselves as brave warriors, men used to fighting, and when any sailor made the same claim, the mercenaries tried to downplay the bravery of the sailors.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick waited, knowing the encounter wasn\'92t going to end well and actually welcoming it all the same. He didn\'92t know if there was a single man in the room who would stand with him, and he didn\'92t care.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You shouldn\'92t go interrupting a young girl what\'92s going about her business the way that young wench was,\'94 the mercenary said. He was young and blond, broad-faced and gap-toothed, a man who had gotten by on sheer size a lot of the time. The scars on his face and arms spoke up for a past history of violence as well. He wore cheap leather armor and carried a short sword with a wire-wrapped hilt at his side.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The other two mercenaries were about the same age, though they showed less experience. Darrick guessed that they were following their companion. Both of them looked a little uneasy about the confrontation.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick sipped from the tankard. Awarm glow filled his belly, and he knew only part of it was from the wine. \'93This is my table,\'94 he said, \'93and I\'92m not inviting company.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You looked lonely,\'94 the big man said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Have your eyesight checked,\'94 Darrick suggested.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The big man scowled. \'93You\'92re not an overly friendly sort.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Darrick agreed. \'93Now, you\'92ve got the right of that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The big man leaned forward, thumping his massive elbows on the table and resting his square shelf of a chin over his interlaced fingers. \'93I don\'92t like you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint152}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint152}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick gripped his cutlass beneath the tabletop and leaned back, letting the wall behind him brace his shoulders. The flickering candle flame on a nearby table drew hollows on the big man\'92s face.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Syrnon,\'94 one of the other men said, pulling at his friend\'92s sleeve. \'93This man has officer\'92s braid on his collar.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Syrnon\'92s big blue eyes narrowed as he glanced at Darrick\'92s neckline. An oak leaf cluster was pinned to Darrick\'92s collar, two garnets denoting his rank. Putting it on had gotten to be such a habit he\'92d forgotten about it.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You an officer on one of the king\'92s ships?\'94 Syrnon asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick taunted. \'93You going to let fear of the king\'92s reprisal for attacking a ship\'92s officer in his navy cow you?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Syrnon,\'94 the other man said. \'93We\'92d be better off taking our leave of this man.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Maybe the man would have left then. He wasn\'92t too drunk to forget about listening to reason, and Westmarch dungeons weren\'92t rumored to be hospitable.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Go,\'94 Darrick said softly, giving in to the black mood that filled him, \'93and don\'92t forget to tuck your tail between your legs as you do.\'94 In the past, Mat had always sensed when Darrick\'92s black moods had settled on him, and Mat had always found a way to cajole him out of the mood or get them into areas where that self-destructive bent wouldn\'92t completely manifest itself.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  But Mat wasn\'92t there tonight, and hadn\'92t been around for nine long days.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Howling with rage, Syrnon stood and reached across the table, intending to grab Darrick\'92s shirt. Darrick leaned forward and head-butted the big mercenary in the face, breaking his nose. Blood gushed from Syrnon\'92s nostrils as he stumbled back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The other two mercenaries tried to stand.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick swung his cutlass, catching one of the men alongside the temple with the flat of the blade and knocking him out. Before the unconscious man had time to drop,{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint153}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint153}Darrick swung on the other man. The mercenary fumbled for the sword sheathed at his waist. Before his opponent could get his weapon clear, Darrick kicked him in the chest, driving the mercenary from his feet and back onto a nearby table. The mercenary took the whole table down with him, and four angry warriors rose to their feet, cursing the man who had landed upon the table, and they cursed Darrick as well.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Syrnon pulled his short sword and drew it back, causing nearby men to duck and dodge way. Curses and harsh oaths followed his movement.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Vaulting to the table, Darrick leapt over Syrnon\'92s sword blow, flipped forward\'97feeling his senses spin for a moment from all he\'92d had to drink\'97and landed on his feet behind the big mercenary. Syrnon spun, his face a mask of crimson from his broken nose, and spat blood as he cursed Darrick. The big mercenary swung his short sword at Darrick\'92s head.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick parried the man\'92s attack with the cutlass. Steel rang against steel inside the tavern. Holding the man\'92s blade trapped, Darrick balled his left fist and slammed it into Syrnon\'92s head. Flesh split along the mercenary\'92s cheek. Darrick hit his opponent twice more and felt immense satisfaction with his efforts. Syrnon was bigger than him, as much bigger as his father had been in the back of the butcher\'92s shop. Only Darrick was no longer a frightened boy too small and too unskilled to defend himself. He hit Syrnon one more time, driving the big man backward.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Syrnon\'92s face showed abuse. His right eye promising to swell shut, a split lip and a split ear joined the split over his cheekbone.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
