\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick felt the newest suture pull as the healer tied it.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The Light must be favorin\'92 ye is all that I can tell,\'94{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint161}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint161}Maldrin said, \'93for they ain\'92t nobody what\'92s been killed yet. An\'92 ye\'92re still alive to tell of it yer own self.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ve been careful,\'94 Darrick said, and regretted trying to make an excuse at once.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93A man bein\'92 careful, skipper,\'94 Maldrin said, \'93why, he\'92d never get in them fixes ye been into. Hell\'92s bells, most of the trouble ye\'92re in, a man what\'92s got a thought in his damned head would think maybe he should ought not be in them places.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick silently agreed. But the portent of trouble in those places had been exactly what had drawn him there. He wasn\'92t thinking when he was fighting, and he wasn\'92t in danger of thinking on things too long or too often when he was drinking and waiting for someone to pick a fight with.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The healer prepared another stitch.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What about the captain?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Skipper,\'94 Maldrin said in a quiet voice, \'93Cap\'92n Tollifer appreciates everythin\'92 ye done. An\'92 he ain\'92t about to forget it. But he\'92s a prideful man, too, an\'92 him havin\'92 to deal with one of his own always fightin\'92 while in port during these edgy times, why, it ain\'92t settin\'92 well with him at all. An\'92 ye damn sure don\'92t need me tellin\'92 ye this.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick agreed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The healer started in with the needle again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Ye need help, skipper,\'94 Maldrin said. \'93Cap\'92n knows it. I know it. Crew knows it. Ye\'92re the only one what seems convinced ye don\'92t.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taking a towel from his knee, the healer blotted blood from Darrick\'92s eye, poured fresh salt water over the wound, and started putting in the final stitch.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Ye ain\'92t the only man what\'92s lost a friend,\'94 Maldrin croaked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I didn\'92t say I was.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93An\'92 me,\'94 Maldrin went on as if he hadn\'92t heard Darrick, \'93I\'92m near to losin\'92 two. I don\'92t want to see you leave\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star,\plain \f2\fs24 skipper. Not if\'92n there\'92s a way I can help.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92m not worth losing any sleep over, Maldrin,\'94 Darrick said in a flat voice. The thing that scared him most was that{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint162}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint162}he felt that way, but he knew it was only his father\'92s words. They were never far from his mind. He\'92d found he could escape his father\'92s fists, but he\'92d never been able to escape the man\'92s harsh words. Only Mat had made him feel differently. None of the other friendships he\'92d made helped, nor did remembering any of the women he\'92d been with over the years. Not even Maldrin could reach him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  But he knew why. Everything Darrick touched would eventually turn to dung. His father had told him that, and it was turning out true. He\'92d lost Mat, and now he was losing\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 and his career in the Westmarch Navy.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Mayhap ye ain\'92t,\'94 Maldrin said. \'93Mayhap ye ain\'92t.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick ran, heart pounding so hard that the infection in his week-old eye wound thundered painfully. His breath came in short gasps as he held his cutlass at his side and dashed through the alleys around the Mercantile Quarter. Reaching Dock Street, he turned his stride toward Fleet Street, the thoroughfare that went through the Military District where the Westmarch Navy harbor was.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He saw the navy frigates in the distance, tall masts thrust up into the low-lying fog that hugged the gulf coastline. A few ships sailed out over the curve of the world, following a favorable breeze away from Westmarch.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  So far, Raithen\'92s pirates had presented no real threat to the city and may even have disbanded, but other pirates had gathered, preying on the busy shipping lanes as Westmarch brought in more and more goods to support the navy, army, and mercenaries. With almost two and a half months gone and no sighting of Kabraxis, the king was beginning to doubt the reports\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 had brought back. Even now, the main problems in Westmarch had become the restlessness of the mercenaries at not having a goal or any real action to occupy them and the dwindling food stores that the city had not yet been able to replace since the action against Tristram.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick cursed the fog that covered the city in steel gray.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint163}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint163}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He\'92d woken in an alley, not knowing if he\'92d gone to sleep there or if he\'92d been thrown there from one of the nearby taverns. He hadn\'92t awakened until after cock\'92s crow, and\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 was due to sail that morning.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He damned himself for a fool, knowing he should have stayed aboard ship. But he hadn\'92t been able to. No one aboard, including the captain and Maldrin, talked with him anymore. He had become an embarrassment, something his father had always told him he was.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Out of breath, he made the final turn toward Spinnaker Bridge, one of the last checkpoints where nonnaval personnel were turned back from entering the Military District. He fumbled inside his stained blouse for his papers.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Four guards stepped up to block his way. They were hard-faced men with weapons that showed obvious care. One of them held up a hand.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick stopped, breathing hard, his injured eye throbbing painfully. \'93Ship\'92s Officer Second Grade Lang,\'94 he gasped.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The leader of the guards looked at Darrick doubtfully but took the papers Darrick offered. He scanned them, noting the captain\'92s seal embossed upon the pages.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Says here you sail with\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star,\'94\plain \f2\fs24 the guard said, offering the papers back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick said, raking the sea with his good eye. He didn\'92t recognize any of the ships sailing out into the gulf as his. Maybe he was in luck.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 sailed hours ago,\'94 the guardsman said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick\'92s heart plummeted through his knees. \'93No,\'94 he whispered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93By rights with you missing your ship like you have,\'94 the guardsman said, \'93I ought to run you in and let the commodore deal with you. But from the looks of you, I\'92d say getting beaten up and robbed will stand as a good excuse. I\'92ll make an entry of it in my log. Should stand you in good stead if you\'92re called before a naval inquest.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  You\'92d be doing me no favors,\plain \f2\fs24 Darrick thought. Any man caught missing from his ship for no good reason was hung{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint164}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint164}for dereliction of duty. He turned and gazed out to sea, watching the gulls hunting through the water for scraps carried out by the tide. The cries of the birds sounded mournful and hollow, filtering over the crash of the surf against the shore.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  If Captain Tollifer had sailed without him, Darrick knew there no longer remained a berth for him aboard\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star.\plain \f2\fs24 His career in the Westmarch Navy was over, and he had no idea what lay ahead of him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He wanted nothing more than to die, but he couldn\'92t do that\'97he wouldn\'92t do that\'97because it would mean that his father would win even after all these years. He walled himself off from his pain and loss, and he turned away from the sea, following the street back into Westmarch. He had no money. The possibility of missing meals didn\'92t bother him, but he knew he\'92d want to drink again that night. By the Light, he wanted to drink right now.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint165}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint165}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  THIRTEEN
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \'93Master.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Buyard Cholik looked up from the comfortable sofa that took up one long wall of the coach he traveled in. Drawn by six horses on three axles, the coach had all the amenities of home. Built-in shelves held his priestly supplies, clothing, and personal belongings. Lamps screwed into the walls and fluted for smoke discharge through the sides of the coach provided light to read by. Since leaving the ruins of Tauruk\'92s Port and Ransim almost three months ago, almost all of his time had been spent reading the arcane texts Kabraxis had provided him and practicing the sorcery the demon had been teaching him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What is it?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The man speaking stood outside on the platform attached to the bottom of the coach. Cholik made no move to open one of the shuttered windows so that he might see the man. Since Kabraxis had changed him, altering his mind and his body\'97in addition to removing decades from his age\'97Cholik felt close to none of the men who had survived the demon\'92s arrival and the attack of Raithen\'92s pirates. Several of them were new, gathered from the small towns the caravan had passed through on its way to its eventual destination.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We are approaching Bramwell, master,\'94 the man said. \'93I thought you might want to know.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Cholik replied. He could tell by the level ride of the coach that the long, winding, uphill trek they\'92d been making for hours had passed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik marked his place in the book he\'92d been reading with a thin braid of human tongues that had turned leathery{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint166}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint166}over the years. Sometimes, with the proper spell in place, the tongues read aloud from profane passages. The book was writ in blood upon paper made from human skin and bound in children\'92s teeth. Most of the other books Kabraxis had provided over the past months were crafted in things that Cholik in his past life as a priest of the Zakarum Church would have believed to be even more horrendous.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The bookmarker made of tongues whispered a sibilant protest at being put away, inciting a small amount of guilt in Cholik as he felt certain Kabraxis had spelled them to do. Nearly all of his days were spent reading, yet it never seemed enough.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Moving with the grace of a man barely entering his middle years, Cholik opened the coach\'92s door, stepped out onto the platform, then climbed the small hand-carved ladder that led up to the coach\'92s peaked, thatched roof. A small ledge was rather like a widow\'92s walk on some of the more affluent houses in Westmarch where merchanter captains\'92 wives walked to see if their husbands arrived safely back from sea.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The coach had been one of the first things Cholik had purchased with the gold and jewels he and his converted priests had carted out of the caverns with Kabraxis\'92s blessing. In its past life, the coach had belonged to a merchant prince who specialized in overland trading. Only two days before Cholik had bought the coach, the merchant prince had suffered debilitating losses and a mysterious illness that had killed him in a matter of hours. Faced with certain bankruptcy, the executor of the prince\'92s goods had sold the coach to Cholik\'92s emissaries.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Standing on the small widow\'92s walk, aware of the immense forest around him, Cholik looked over the half-dozen wagons that preceded the coach. Another half-dozen wagons, all loaded down with the things that Kabraxis had ordered salvaged from Tauruk\'92s Port, trailed behind Cholik\'92s coach.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A winding road cut through the heart of the forest. Cholik couldn\'92t remember the forest\'92s name at the{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint167}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint167}moment, but he had never seen it before. His travels from Westmarch had always been by ship, and he\'92d never been to Bramwell as young as he now was.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  At the end of the winding road lay the city of Bramwell, a suburb north-northwest of Westmarch. Centuries ago, situated among the highlands as it was, the city had occupied a position of prominence that competed with Westmarch. Bramwell had been far enough away from Westmarch that its economy was its own. Farmers and fishermen lived in the tiny city, descendants of families that had lived there for generations, sailing the same ships and plowing the same lands as their ancestors had. In the old days, Bramwell\'92s sailors had hunted whales and sold the oil. Now, the whaling fleets had become a handful of diehard families who stubbornly got by in a hardscrabble existence more with pride and a deep reluctance to change than out of necessity.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Almost ancient, Bramwell was constructed of buildings two and three stories tall from stones cut and carried down from the mountains. Peaked roofs crafted with thatching dyed a dozen different shades of green mimicked the forest surrounding the city on three sides. The fourth side fronted the Gulf of Westmarch, where a breakwater had been built of rock dug from the mountains to protect the harbor from the harsh seasons of the sea.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  From atop the coach and atop the mountains, Cholik surveyed the city that would be his home during the first of Kabraxis\'92s conquests. An empire, Cholik told himself as he gazed out onto the unsuspecting city, would begin there. He rode on the platform, rocking back and forth as the heavy-duty springs of the coach compensated for the road\'92s failings, watching as the city drew closer.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Hours later, Cholik stood beside the Sweetwater River that fed Bramwell. The river ran deep and true between broad, stone-covered banks. The waterway also provided more harbor space for smaller craft that plied the city\'92s trade farther inland and graced the lands with a plenitude{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint168}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint168}of wells and irrigation for the farms that made checkerboards outside the city proper.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  At the eastern end of the city where the loggers and craftsmen gathered and where shops and markets had sprung up years ago, Cholik halted the caravan in the campgrounds that were open to all who hoped to trade with the Bramwell population.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Children had gathered around the coach and the wagons immediately, hoping for a traveling minstrel show. Cholik didn\'92t disappoint them, offering the troupe of entertainers he\'92d hired as the caravan had journeyed north from Tauruk\'92s Port. They\'92d taken the overland route, a long and arduous event compared with travel by sea, but they had avoided the Westmarch Navy as well. Cholik doubted that anyone who had once known him would recognize him since his youth had been returned, but he hadn\'92t wanted to take the chance, and Kabraxis had been patient.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The entertainers gamboled and clowned, performing physical feats that seemed astounding and combining witty poems and snippets of exchanges that had the gathering audience roaring with laughter. The juggling and acrobatics, while pipes and drums played in the background, drew amazed comments from the families.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik stood inside the coach and watched through a covered window. The festive atmosphere didn\'92t fit with how he\'92d been trained to think of religious practices. New converts to the Zakarum Church weren\'92t entertained and wooed in such a manner, although some of the smaller churches did.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Still disapproving, are you?\'94 a deep voice asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Recognizing Kabraxis\'92s voice, Cholik stood and turned. He knew the demon hadn\'92t entered the coach in the conventional means, but he didn\'92t know from where Kabraxis had traveled before stepping into the coach.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Old habits are hard to break,\'94 Cholik said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Like changing your religious beliefs?\'94 Kabraxis asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Kabraxis stood before Cholik wearing a dead man\'92s{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint169}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint169}body. Upon his decision to go among the humans and look for a city to establish as a beachhead to begin their campaign, Kabraxis had killed a merchant, sacrificing the man\'92s soul to unforgiving darkness. Once the mortal remains of the man were nothing more than an empty shell, Kabraxis had labored for three days and nights with the blackest arcane spells available, finally managing to fit himself into the corpse.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Although Cholik had never witnessed something like that, Kabraxis had assured him that it was sometimes done, though not without danger. When the host body was taken over a month ago, it had been that of a young man who had not yet seen thirty. Now the man looked much older than Cholik, like a man in his twilight years. The flesh was baggy and loose, wrinkled and crisscrossed by hair-fine scars that marred his features. His black hair had gone colorless gray, his eyes from brown to pale ash.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Are you all right?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The old man smiled, but it was with an expression Cholik recognized as Kabraxis\'92s. \'93I\'92ve put many harsh demands on this body. But its use is almost at an end.\'94 He stepped past Cholik and peered out the window.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What are you doing here?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I came to watch you observe the festivities of the people coming to see you,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93I knew that this many people around you, and so many of them happy and needing diversion, would prove unnerving for you. Life goes much easier for you if you can maintain a somber vigilance over it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93These people will know us as entertainers,\'94 Cholik said, \'93not as conduits to a new religion that will help them with their lives.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Oh,\'94 Kabraxis said, \'93I\'92ll help them with their lives. In fact, I wanted to have a word with you about how this evening\'92s meeting will go.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Excitement flared within Cholik. After two months of being on the road, of planning to found a church and build a power base that would eventually seek to draw its constituency{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint170}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint170}from the Zakarum Church, it felt good to know that they were about to start.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Bramwell is the place, then?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93There is old power located within this town. Power that I can tap into that will shape your destiny and my conquest. Tonight, you will lay the first stone in the church we have discussed for the past month. But it won\'92t be of stone and mortar as you think. Rather, it will be of believers.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The comment left Cholik cold. He wanted an edifice, a building that would dwarf the Zakarum Church in Westmarch. \'93We will need a church.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We will have a church,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93But having a church anchors you in one spot. Although I\'92ve tried to teach you this, you\'92ve still not learned. But a belief\'97Buyard Cholik, First Chosen of the Black Road\'97a belief transcends all physical boundaries and leaves its mark on the ages. That\'92s what we want.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik said nothing, but visions of a grand church continued to dance in his head.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ve given you an extended life,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93Few humans will ever achieve the years that you\'92ve lived so far without the effects of my gift. Would you want to spend all the coming years in one place, looking only over the triumphs you\'92ve already wrought?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You are the one who has spoken of the need for patience.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I still speak of patience,\'94 Kabraxis insisted, \'93but you will not be the tree of my religion, Buyard Cholik. I don\'92t need a tree. I need a bee. A bee that flits from one place to another to collect our believers.\'94 He smiled and patted Cholik on the shoulder. \'93But come. We start here in Bramwell with these people.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What do you want me to do?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Tonight,\'94 Kabraxis said, \'93we will show these people the power of the Black Road. We will show them that anything they may dream possible can happen.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\qc\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f0\fs20 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\qc\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 ***
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint171}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint171}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik walked out of the coach and toward the gathering area. He wore his best robe, but it was of a modest style that wouldn\'92t turn away those who were poor.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  At least three hundred people ringed the clearing where the caravan had stopped. Other wagons, some of them loaded with straw, apples, and livestock, formed another ring outside Cholik\'92s. Still more wagons, empty of any goods, made seating areas beneath the spreading trees.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Ah,\'94 one man whispered, \'93here comes the speechmaker. The fun and games are over now, I\'92ll warrant.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If he starts lecturing me on how to live my life and how much I should tithe to whatever religion he\'92s shilling for,\'94 another man whispered, \'93I\'92m leaving. I\'92ve spent two hours watching performers that I didn\'92t have time to lose and will never get back.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ve got a field that needs tending.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And the cows are going to be expecting an early morning milking.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Aware that he was losing part of the audience the performers had brought in for him, knowing not to make any attempt to speak to them of anything smacking of responsibility or donations, Cholik walked to the center of the clearing and brought out the metal bucket containing black ash that Kabraxis had made and presented to him. Speaking a single word of power that the audience couldn\'92t hear, he threw out the ashes.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The ashes roiled from the bucket in a dense black cloud that paused in midair. The long stream of ash twisted like a snake on a hot road as it floated on the mild breeze wafting through the clearing. Abruptly, the ash thinned and shot forward, creating whorls and loops that dropped over the ground. In places, the lines of ash crossed over other lines, but the lines didn\'92t touch. Instead, the loops and whorls stayed ten feet away, creating enough distance that a man might walk under.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sight of the thin line of ash hanging in the air caught the attention of the audience. Perhaps a mage might be{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint172}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint172}able to do something like that, but not a typical priest. Enough curiosity was created that most people wanted to see what Cholik would do next.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  When the line of ash ended its run, it glowed with deep violet fire, competing just for a moment with the deepening twilight darkening the eastern sky and the embers of the sunset west over the Gulf of Westmarch.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik faced the audience, his eyes meeting theirs. \'93I bring you power,\'94 he said. \'93A path that will carry you to the dreams you\'92ve always had but were denied by misfortune and outdated dogma.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  An undercurrent of conversation started around the clearing. Several voices rose in anger. The populace of Bramwell clung to their belief in Zakarum.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93There is another way to the Light,\'94 Cholik said. \'93That path lies along the Way of Dreams. Dien-Ap-Sten, Prophet of the Light, created this path for his children, so that they might have their needs met and their secret wishes answered.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ve never heard of yer prophet,\'94 a crusty old fisherman in the front shouted back. \'93An\'92 ain\'92t none of us come here to hear the way of the Light maligned.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I will not malign the way of the Light,\'94 Cholik responded. \'93I came here to show you a clearer way into the beneficence of the Light.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The Zakarum Church already does that,\'94 a grizzled old man in a patched priest\'92s robe stated. \'93We don\'92t need a pretender here digging into our vaults.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I didn\'92t come here looking for your gold,\'94 Cholik said. \'93I didn\'92t come here to take.\'94 He was conscious of Kabraxis watching him from inside the coach. \'93In fact, I will not allow the gathering of a single copper coin this night or any other that we may camp in your city.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The Duke of Bramwell will have something to say to you if you try staying,\'94 an elderly farmer said. \'93The duke don\'92t put up with much in the way of grifters and thieves.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik pushed aside his stung pride. That chore was made even harder by the knowledge that he could have{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint173}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint173}blasted the life from the man with one of the spells he\'92d learned from Kabraxis. After he\'92d become one of Zakarum\'92s priests and even while he was wearing the robe of a novice, no one had dared challenge him in such a manner.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Crossing the clearing, Cholik stopped in front of a large family with a young boy so crippled and wasted by disease that he looked like a stumbling corpse.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The father stepped up in front of Cholik protectively. The man gripped the knife sheathed at his waist.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Good sir,\'94 Cholik said, \'93I see that your son is afflicted.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The farmer gazed around self-consciously. \'93By the fever that come through Bramwell eight years ago. My boy ain\'92t the only one that was hurt by it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He hasn\'92t been right since the fever.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Nervously, the farmer shook his head. \'93None of them has. Most died within a week of getting it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What would you give to have one more healthy son to help you work your farm?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I ain\'92t going to have my boy hurt or made fun of,\'94 the farmer warned.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I will do neither,\'94 Cholik promised. \'93Please trust me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Confusion filled the man\'92s face. He looked at the short, stocky woman who had to be the mother of the nine children who sat in their wagon.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Boy,\'94 Cholik said, addressing the young boy, \'93would you stay a burden to your family?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Hey,\'94 the farmer protested. \'93He ain\'92t no burden, and I\'92ll fight the man that says he is.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik waited. As an ordained priest of the Zakarum Church, he\'92d have had the father penalized at once for daring to speak to him in such a manner.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Wait,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis whispered in Cholik\'92s mind.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik waited, knowing the audience\'92s full attention was upon him. It would be decided here, he told himself, whether the audience stayed or went.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Something lit the boy\'92s eyes. His head, looking bulbous on his thin shoulders and narrow chest, swiveled toward his father. Reaching up with an arthritic hand with fingers{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint174}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint174}that had to have been painful to him all the time and could barely be expected to enable him to feed himself, the boy tugged on his father\'92s arm.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Father,\'94 the boy said, \'93let me go with the priest.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The farmer started to shake his head. \'93Effirn, I don\'92t know if this is right for you. I don\'92t want you to get your hopes up. The healers at the Zakarum Church haven\'92t been able to cure you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I know,\'94 the boy said. \'93But I believe in this man. Let me try.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The farmer glanced at his wife. She nodded, tears flashing diamondlike in her eyes. Looking up at Cholik, the farmer said, \'93I hold you accountable for what happens to my son, priest.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You may,\'94 Cholik said politely, \'93but I assure you the healing that young Effirn will shortly enjoy shall be the blessing of Dien-Ap-Sten. I am not skilled enough to answer this boy\'92s wish to be healed and whole.\'94 He glanced at the boy and offered his hand.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The boy tried to stand, but his withered legs wouldn\'92t hold him. He folded his hand with its twisted and crooked fingers inside Cholik\'92s hand.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik marveled at the weakness of the boy. It was hard to remember when he\'92d been so weak himself, but it had been only scant months ago. He helped the boy to his feet. Around the clearing almost every voice was stilled.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Come, boy,\'94 Cholik said. \'93Place your faith in me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I do,\'94 Effirn replied.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Together, they walked across the clearing. Not quite to the nearest end of the long rope of black ash that still sparked with violent fire, the boy\'92s legs gave out. Cholik caught Effirn before he could fall, overcoming his own discomfort at handling the disease-ridden child.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik knew that every eye in the clearing was upon him and the child. Doubt touched Cholik as he gazed up at the tall trees around the clearing. If the boy died along the path of the Black Road, perhaps he could hold the townspeople off long enough to get away. If he didn\'92t get away,{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint175}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint175}he was certain he\'92d be swinging by a noose from one of those branches overhead. He\'92d heard about the justice meted out by the people of Bramwell to bandits and murderers among their community.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  And Cholik intended to help them suckle a serpent to their breasts.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  At the beginning of the black ash trail, Cholik helped the boy stand on his own two feet.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What do I do?\'94 Effirn whispered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Walk,\'94 Cholik told him. \'93Follow the trail, and think about nothing but being healed.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The boy took a deep, shuddering breath, obviously rethinking his decision to follow a path so obviously filled with magic. Then, tentatively, the boy released his grip on Cholik\'92s hands. His first steps were trembling, tottering things that had Cholik\'92s breath catching at the back of his throat.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  With agonizing slowness, the boy walked. Then his steps came a little smoother, although the swaying gait he managed threatened to tear him from the path.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  No sound was made in the clearing as the audience watched the crippled boy make his way around the black ash trail. His feet kicked violet sparks from the black ash with every step he took, but it didn\'92t take long for the steps to start coming more sure, then faster. The boy\'92s shoulders straightened, and his carriage became more erect. His thin legs, then his arms, then his body swelled with increased muscle mass. No longer did his head look bulbous atop his skeletal frame.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  And when the black ash trail rose up in the air to pass over a past section, the boy stepped up into the air after it. Before, even omitting the impossibility of following such a thin line of ash into the air, the boy would not have been able to meet the challenge of the climb.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Conversations buzzed around Cholik, and he gloried in the amazement the audience had for what was taking place. While serving at the Zakarum Church, he would never have been allowed to take credit for such a spell. He turned to face the audience, moving so that he faced them all.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint176}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint176}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93This is the power of the Way of Dreams,\'94 Cholik crowed, \'93and of the generous and giving prophet I choose to serve. May Dien-Ap-Sten\'92s name and works be praised. Join me in praising his name, brothers and sisters.\'94 He raised his arms. \'93Glory to Dien-Ap-Sten!\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Only a few followed his example at first, but others joined. Within a moment, the tumultuous shout rose above the clearing, drowning out the commonplace noise that droned from the city downriver.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Buyard Cholik!
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The voiceless address exploded in Cholik\'92s mind with such harshness that he momentarily went blind with the pain and was nauseated.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Beware,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 The spell is becoming unraveled.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Gathering himself, Cholik glanced back at the maze created by the line he\'92d cast, watching as the starting point of the line suddenly burst into violet sparks and burned rapidly. The small fire raced along the length of the line of ash. As the fire moved, it consumed the ash, leaving nothing behind.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The fire raced for the boy.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  If the fire reaches the boy,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis warned,\plain \f2\i\fs24 he will be destroyed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik walked to the other end of the line of ash, watching as the fire swept toward the boy. He thought furiously, knowing he couldn\'92t show any fear to the cheering audience.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  If we lose these people now,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said,\plain \f2\i\fs24 we might not get them back. If a miracle occurs, we will win believers, but if a disaster happens, we could be lost. It will be years before we can come back here, and maybe even longer before these people will forget what happened tonight to let us attempt to win them over again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Effirn,\'94 Cholik called.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The boy looked up at him, taking his eyes from the path for a moment. His steps never faltered. \'93Look at me!\'94 he cried gleefully. \'93Look at me. I\'92m walking.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes, Effirn,\'94 Cholik said, \'93and everyone here is proud of you and grateful to Dien-Ap-Sten, as is proper.{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint177}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint177}However, there is something I need to know.\'94 Glancing back at the relentless purple fire pursuing the boy, he saw that it was only two curves back from Effirn. The end of the ash trail was still thirty feet from the boy.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What?\'94 Effirn asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Can you run?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The boy\'92s face worked in confusion. \'93I don\'92t know. I\'92ve never tried.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The violet fire gained another ten feet on him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Try now,\'94 Cholik suggested. He held his arms out. \'93Run to me, Effirn. Quickly, boy. Fast as you can.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Tentatively, Effirn started running, trying out his new muscles and abilities. He ran, and the violet fire burning up the ash trail chased him, still gaining, but by inches now rather than feet.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Come on, Effirn,\'94 Cholik cheered. \'93Show your da how fast you\'92ve become now that Dien-Ap-Sten has shown you grace.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Effirn ran, laughing the whole way. The conversation of the audience picked up intensity. The boy reached the trail\'92s end, sweeping down the final curve to the ground, and was in Cholik\'92s arms just as the violet blaze hit the end of the trail and vanished in a puff of bruised embers.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Feeling as though he\'92d just escaped death again, Cholik held the boy to him for a moment, surprised at how big Effirn had gotten. He felt the boy\'92s arms and legs tight against him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Thank you, thank you, thank you,\'94 Effirn gasped, hugging Cholik with strong arms and legs.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Embarrassed and flushed with excitement at the same time, Cholik hugged the boy back. Effirn\'92s health meant nothing but success for him in Bramwell, but Cholik didn\'92t understand how the demon had worked the magic.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Healing is simple enough,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said in Cholik\'92s mind.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Causing hurt and pain are separate issues, and much harder if it\'92s going to be lasting. In order to learn how to injure someone, the magic is designed so that first a person learns to heal.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik had never been taught that.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  There are a number of things you haven\'92t been taught,{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint178}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint178}\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 But you have time left to you. I will teach you. Turn, Buyard Cholik, and greet your new parishioners.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Easing the boy\'92s grip from him, Cholik turned to face the parents. No one thought to challenge him about why the ash trail had burned away.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Released, wanting to show off his newfound strength, the boy raced across the clearing. His brothers and sisters cheered him on, and his father caught him up and pulled him into a fierce hug before handing him off to his mother. She held her son to her, tears washing unashamedly down her face.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik watched the mother and son, amazed at the way the scene touched him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  You\'92re surprised by how good you feel at having had a hand in healing the boy?\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Cholik whispered, knowing no one around him could hear him but that the demon could.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  It shouldn\'92t. To know the Darkness, a being must also know the Light. You lived your life cloistered in Westmarch. The only people you met were those who wanted your position.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Or those whose positions I coveted,\plain \f2\fs24 Cholik realized.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  And the Zakarum Church never allowed you to be so personal in the healing properties they doled out,\plain \f2\fs24 the demon said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  The Light is afraid to give many people powers like I have given you,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 People who have powers like this get noticed by regular people. In short order, they become heroes or talked-about people. In only a little more time, the tales that are told about them allow them to take on lofty mantles. The stewards of the Light are jealous of that.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But demons aren\'92t?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Kabraxis laughed, and the grating, thunderous noise echoing inside Cholik\'92s head was almost painful.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Demons aren\'92t as jealous as the stewards of Light would have you believe. Nor are they as controlling as the stewards of Light. I ask you, who always has the most rules? The most limitations?
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik didn\'92t answer.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Why do you think the stewards of Light offer so many rules?{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint179}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint179}\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis asked.\plain \f2\i\fs24 To keep the balance in their favor, of course. But demons, we believe in letting all who support the Darkness have power. Some have more power than others. But they earn it. Just as you have earned that which I\'92m giving you the day you faced your own fear of dying and sought out the buried gateway to me.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I had no choice,\'94 Cholik said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Humans always have choices. That\'92s how the stewards of Light seek to confuse you. You have choices, but you can\'92t choose most of them because the stewards of Light have decreed them as wrong. As an enlightened student of the Light, you\'92re supposed to know that those choices are wrong. So where does that really leave you? How many choices do you really have?
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik silently agreed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Go to these people, Buyard Cholik. You\'92ll find converts among them now. Once they have discovered that you have the power to make changes that will let them attain their goals and desires, they will flock to you. Next, we must begin the church, and we must find disciples among these people who will help you spread word of me. For now, give the gift of health to those who are sick among these before you. They will talk. By morning, there won\'92t be anyone in this city who hasn\'92t heard of you.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Glorying in the newfound respect and prestige he\'92d gained by healing the boy, Cholik went forward. His body sang with the buzzing thrill of the power Kabraxis channeled through him. The power drew him to the weak and infirm in the crowd.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Laying hands on the people in the crowd as he came to them, Cholik healed fevers and infections, took away warts and arthritis, straightened a leg that had grown crooked after being set and healing, brought senses back to an elderly grandmother who had been addled for years according to the son who cared for her.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I would like to settle in Bramwell,\'94 Cholik said as the Gulf of Westmarch drank down the sun and twilight turned to night around them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The crowd cheered in response to his announcement.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But I will need a church built,\'94 Cholik continued. \'93Once a permanent church is built, the miracles wrought{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint180}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint180}by Dien-Ap-Sten will continue to grow. Come to me that I may introduce you to the prophet I choose to serve.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  For a night, Buyard Cholik was closer to lasting renown than he\'92d ever been in his life. It was a heady feeling, one that he promised himself he would get to know more intimately.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Nothing would stop him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint181}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint181}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  FOURTEEN
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \'93Are you a sailor?\'94 the pretty serving wench asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Darrick looked up at her from the bowl of thick potatoes and meat stew and didn\'92t let the brief pang of loss her words brought touch him. \'93No,\'94 he replied, because he hadn\'92t been a sailor for months.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The serving girl was a raven-haired beauty scarcely more than twenty years old if she was that. Her black skirt was short and high, revealing a lot of her long, beautiful legs. She wore her hair pulled back, tied at the neck.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why do you ask?\'94 Darrick held her eyes for a moment, then she looked away.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Only because your rolling gait as you entered the door reminded me of a sailor\'92s,\'94 the wench said. \'93My father was a sailor. Born to the sea and lost to the sea, as is the usual course for many sailors.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What is your name?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Dahni,\'94 she said, and smiled.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It\'92s been nice meeting you, Dahni.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  For a moment, the wench gazed around the table, trying to find something to do. But she\'92d already refilled his tankard, and his bowl remained more than half full. \'93If you need anything,\'94 she offered, \'93let me know.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I will.\'94 Darrick kept his smile in place. He\'92d learned in the months since losing his berth aboard\plain \f2\i\fs24 Lonesome Star\plain \f2\fs24 that smiling politely and answering questions but asking none ended conversations more quickly. If people thought he was willing to be friendly, they didn\'92t find his lack of conversation as threatening or challenging. They just thought he was inept or shy and generally left him alone. The ruse{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint182}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint182}had kept him from a number of fights lately, and the lack of fighting had kept him from the jails and fines that often left him destitute and on the street again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Tilting his head, he glanced briefly at the four men playing dice at the table next to his. Three of them were fishermen, he knew that from their clothing, but the fourth man was dressed a little better, like someone who was putting on his best and hoping to impress. It came off as someone down on his luck and getting desperate. That appearance, Darrick knew, was an illusion.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He ate hungrily, trying not to act as if he hadn\'92t eaten since yesterday. Or perhaps it was the day before. He was no longer certain of time passing. However few meals he\'92d had, he\'92d always managed to make enough money to drink. Drinking was the only way to keep distanced from the fears and nightmares that plagued him. Almost every night, he dreamed of the cliffside in Tauruk\'92s Port, dreamed that he almost saved Mat from the skeleton\'92s clutches, from the awful thump against the cliffside that had broken Mat\'92s skull.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The tavern was a dive, another in a long string of them. They all looked alike to him. When he finished with his work, wherever he was, he ate a meal, drank until he could hardly walk, then hired a room or bedded down in a stable if the money hadn\'92t been enough to provide drink and a proper bed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The clientele was mostly fishermen, hard-faced men with callused hands and scars from nets, hooks, fish, the weather, and years of disappointment that ran bone-deep. They talked of tomorrows that sounded much better than the morning would bring, and what they would do if someday they escaped the need to climb aboard a boat every day and pray the Light was generous.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Merchants sat among the fishermen and other townspeople, discussing shipments and fortunes and the lack of protection in the northern part of the Great Ocean since Westmarch was keeping its navy so close to home these days still. There still had been no sign of the demon whom{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint183}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint183}the Westmarch sailors had seen at Tauruk\'92s Port, and many of the merchants and sailors north of Westmarch believed that the pirates had made up the story to lure the king into pulling his navy back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Dissent grew among the northern ports and cities because they depended on Westmarch to help defend them. With the Westmarch Navy out of the way, men turned to piracy when they couldn\'92t make the sea pay any other way. Although most pirates weren\'92t acting together, their combined raiding had hurt the economies of several independent ports and even cities farther inland. Westmarch diplomacy, once a feared and treasured and expansive thing, had become weak and ineffective. Northern cities no longer curried favor with Westmarch as much.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick sopped a biscuit through the stew and popped it into his mouth. The stew was thick and oily, seasoned with grease and spices that made it cloying and hot, a meal that finished off a hardworking man\'92s day. Over the last months, he\'92d lost weight, but his fighting ability had stayed sharp. For the most part, he stayed away from the docks for fear that someone might recognize him. Although the Westmarch Navy and guardsmen hadn\'92t made a strong effort to find him, or other sailors who had intentionally jumped ship, he remained leery of possible apprehension. Some days death seemed preferable to living, but he couldn\'92t make that step. He hadn\'92t died as he\'92d grown up under his father\'92s fierce hands, and he didn\'92t intend to die willingly now.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  But it was hard to live willingly.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He glanced across the room, watching Dahni as she talked and flirted with a young man. Part of him longed for the companionship of a woman, but it was only a small part. Women talked, and they dug at the things that bothered a man, most of them wanting only to help, but Darrick didn\'92t want to deal with that.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The big man sitting at the end of the bar crossed the floor to Darrick. The man was tall and broad, with a nose flattened and misshapen from fights. Scars, some freshly pink and{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint184}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint184}webbed with tiny scabs, covered his knuckles and the heels of his palms. An old knife scar showed at his throat.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Uninvited, he sat across from Darrick, his truncheon lying across his knees. \'93You\'92re working,\'94 the man said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick kept his right hand in his lap where his cutlass was. He gazed at the man. \'93I\'92m here with a friend.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  To his right, the gambler who had hired Darrick for an evening\'92s protection after they had come in on the trade caravan together praised the Light for yet another good turn. He was an older man, thin and white-haired. During an attack by bandits only yesterday, Darrick had learned that the man could handle himself and carried a number of small knives secreted on his person.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Your friend\'92s awfully lucky tonight,\'94 the big man said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He\'92s due,\'94 Darrick said in a level voice.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The big man eyed Darrick levelly. \'93It\'92s my job to keep the peace in the tavern.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick nodded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If I catch your friend cheating, I\'92m throwing you both out.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
