\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Shaking her head, Meridor said, \'93No. I only talked to him.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But you got a good look at him?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes. He had a burned face. He was scared to come in here. He said Dien-Ap-Sten might know him, but he came anyway.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I don\'92t know.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Another guard rushed up to the burly one. \'93Master Sayes lives,\'94 the guard reported.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Thank Dien-Ap-Sten,\'94 the burly guard said. \'93I would not have wanted to go where the Way of Dreams would have taken me if Master Sayes had died.\'94 He gave a description of the assassin, adding that a man with a burned face should be easy enough to find. Then he turned his attention back to Meridor, keeping a painful grip on her arm. \'93Come along, girl. You\'92re coming with me. We\'92re going to talk to Master Sayes.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Meridor tried to escape. The last thing she wanted to do was talk to Master Sayes. But she couldn\'92t escape the grip the guard had on her arm as he dragged her through the crowd.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint209}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint209}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  SIXTEEN
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \'93I\'92m tellin\'92 ye, I\'92ve seen it with me own two eyes, I have,\'94 old Sahyir said, looking mightily offended. He was sixty if he was a day, lean and whipcord tough, with a cottony white beard and his hair pulled back into a ponytail. Shell earrings hung from both ears. Scars showed on his face and hands and arms. He wore tarred breeches and a shirt to stand against the spray that carried across the still-primitive harbor.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Darrick sat on a crate that was part of the cargo he\'92d been hired to help transport from the caravel out in the bay to the warehouse on the shoreline of Seeker\'92s Point. It was the first good paying work he\'92d had in three days, and he\'92d begun to think he was going to have to crew out on a ship to keep meals coming and a roof over his head. Shipping out wasn\'92t something he looked forward to. The sea held too many memories. He reached into the worn leather bag he carried and took out a piece of cheddar cheese and two apples.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I have trouble believing the part about the stone snake gulping people down, I do,\'94 Darrick admitted. He used his small belt knife to cut wedges from the half-circle of cheese and to cut the apples into quarters, expertly slicing the cores away. He gave Sahyir one of the cheese wedges and one of the sliced apples. Tossing the apple cores over the side of the barge attracted the small perch that lived along the harbor and fed on refuse from the ships, warehouses, and street sewers. They kissed the top of the water with hungry mouths.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I seen it, Darrick,\'94 the old man insisted. \'93Seen a man that couldn\'92t use his legs pull himself into that snake\'92s gullet,{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint210}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint210}an\'92 then come up an\'92 walk outta there on his own two legs again. Healthy as a horse, he was. It was right something to see.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick chewed a piece of cheese as he shook his head. \'93Healers can do that. Potions can do that. I\'92ve even seen enchanted weapons that could help a man heal faster. There is nothing special about healing. The Zakarum Church does it from time to time.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But those all come for a price,\'94 Sahyir argued. \'93Healers an\'92 potions an\'92 enchanted weapons, why, they\'92re all well an\'92 good for a man what\'92s got the gold or the strength to get \'92em. And churches? Don\'92t get me started. Churches dote on them that put big donations in the coffers, or them what\'92s got the king\'92s favor. Churches keep an eye on the hands what feed \'92em, I says. But I ask ye, what about the common, ordinary folk like ye and me? Who\'92s gonna take care of us?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Gazing across the sea, feeling the wind rush through his hair and against his face, the chill of it biting into his flesh in spite of his own tarred clothing, Darrick looked at the small village that clung tenaciously to the rocky land of the cove. \'93We take care of ourselves,\'94 he said. \'93Just like we always have.\'94 He and the old man had been friends for months, sharing an easy companionship.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Seeker\'92s Point was a small town just south of the barbarian tribes\'92 territories. In the past, the village had been a supply fort for traders, whalers, and seal hunters who had trekked through the frozen north. Little more than a hundred years ago, a merchant house had posted an army there meant to chase off the marauding barbarian pirates who hunted the area without fear of the Westmarch Navy. A bounty had been placed on the heads of the barbarians, and for a time the mercenary army had collected from the trading house.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Then some of the barbarian tribes had united and laid siege to the village. The trading house hadn\'92t been able to resupply or ship the mercenaries out. During the course of one winter, the mercenaries and all those who had lived{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint211}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint211}with them had been killed to the last person. It had taken more than forty years for a few fur traders to reestablish themselves in the area, and only then because they traded favorably with the barbarians and brought them goods they couldn\'92t get on their own with any dependability.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Houses and buildings dotted the steep mountains that surrounded the cove. Pockets of unimproved land and forest stood tall and proud between some of the houses and buildings. The village slowly eroded those patches, though, taking the timber for buildings and for heat, but baring several of those places only revealed the jagged, gap-toothed, rocky soil beneath. Nothing could be built in those places.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why didn\'92t you stay in Bramwell?\'94 Darrick asked. He bit into the apple, finding it sweet and tart.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Sahyir waved the thought away. \'93Why, even before they up an\'92 had all this religious business success, Bramwell wasn\'92t for the likes of me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Snorting, Sahyir said, \'93Why, it\'92s too busy there is why. A man gets to wanderin\'92 around them streets\'97all in a tizzy and a bother\'97an\'92 he\'92s like to meet hisself comin\'92 and goin\'92.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Despite the melancholy mood that usually stayed with him, Darrick smiled. Bramwell was a lot larger than Seeker\'92s Point, but it paled in comparison with Westmarch. \'93You\'92ve never been to Westmarch, have you?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Once,\'94 Sahyir answered. \'93Only once. I made a mistake of signing on with a cargo freighter needin\'92 a hand. I was a young strappin\'92 pup like yerself, thought I wasn\'92t afeard of nothin\'92. So I signed on. Got to Westmarch harbor and looked out over that hell-spawned place. We was at anchorage for six days, we was. An\'92 never once durin\'92 that time did I leave that ship.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You didn\'92t? Why?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because I figured I\'92d never find my way back to the ship I was on.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick laughed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint212}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint212}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Sahyir scowled at him and looked put out. \'93\'92Tweren\'92t funny, ye bilge rat. There\'92s men what went ashore there that didn\'92t come back.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I meant no offense,\'94 Darrick said. \'93It\'92s just that after making that trip down to Westmarch and through the bad weather that usually marks the gulf, I can\'92t imagine anyone not leaving the ship when they had a chance.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Only far enough to buy a wineskin from the local tavern and get a change of victuals from time to time,\'94 Sahyir said. \'93But the only reason I brought up Bramwell today was because I was talkin\'92 to a man I met last night, an\'92 I thought ye might be interested in what he had to say.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick watched the other barges plying the harbor. Today was a busy day for Seeker\'92s Point. Longshoremen usually had two jobs in the village because there wasn\'92t enough work handling cargo to provide for a family. Even men who didn\'92t take on crafts and artisan work hunted or fished or trapped when finances ran low. Sometimes they migrated for a time to other cities farther south along the coast like Bramwell.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Interested in what?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Them symbols I see ye a-drawin\'92 and a-sketchin\'92 now an\'92 again.\'94 Sahyir brought up a water flask and handed it to Darrick.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick drank, tasting the metallic flavor of the water. There were a few mines in the area as well, but none of them was profitable enough to cause a merchant to invest in developing and risk losing everything to the barbarians.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I know ye don\'92t like talkin\'92 about them symbols,\'94 Sahyir said, \'93an\'92 I apologize for talkin\'92 about \'92em when it ain\'92t no business of me own. But I see ye a-frettin\'92 an\'92 aworryin\'92 about \'92em, an\'92 I know it troubles ye some.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  During the time he had known the old man, Darrick had never mentioned where he\'92d learned about the elliptical design with the line that threaded through it. He\'92d tried to put all that in the past. A year ago, when the gambler had died while under his protection, Darrick had lost himself to work and drink, barely getting by. Guilt ate at him over{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint213}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint213}losing Mat and the gambler. And the phantasm of his father back in the barn in Hillsfar had lived with him every day.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick didn\'92t even remember arriving in Seeker\'92s Point, had been so drunk that the ship\'92s captain had thrown him off the ship and refused to let him back on. Sahyir had found Darrick at the water\'92s edge, sick and feverish. The old man had gotten help from a couple of friends and taken Darrick back to his shanty up in the hills overlooking the village. He\'92d cared for Darrick, nursing him back to health during the course of a month. It had been a time, the old man had said, when he\'92d been certain on more than one occasion he was going to lose Darrick to the sickness or to the guilt that haunted him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Even now, Darrick didn\'92t know how much of his story he\'92d told Sahyir, but the old man had told him that he\'92d drawn the symbol constantly. Darrick couldn\'92t remember doing that, but Sahyir had produced scraps of paper with the design on it that Darrick had been forced to assume were in his own hand.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Sahyir appeared uncomfortable.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It\'92s all right, then,\'94 Darrick said. \'93Those symbols aren\'92t anything.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Scratching his beard with his callused fingers, Sahyir said, \'93That\'92s not what the man said that I talked to last night.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What did he say?\'94 Darrick asked. The barge had nearly reached the shore now, and the men pulling the oars rested more, letting the incoming tide carry them along as they jockeyed around the other barges and ships in the choked harbor.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He was mighty interested in that there symbol,\'94 the old man said. \'93That\'92s why I was a-tellin\'92 ye about the Church of the Prophet of the Light this mornin\'92.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick thought about it for a moment. \'93I don\'92t understand.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I was worried some about tellin\'92 ye that I\'92d done a bit of nosin\'92 about in yer business,\'94 Sahyir said. \'93We been{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint214}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint214}friends for a time now, but I know ye ain\'92t up an\'92 told me everythin\'92 there is to know about that there symbol or yer own ties to it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Guilt flickered through Darrick. \'93That was something I tried to put behind me, Sahyir. It wasn\'92t because I was trying to hide anything from you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The old man\'92s eyes fixed him. \'93We all hide somethin\'92, young pup. It\'92s just the way men are an\'92 women are, an\'92 folks in general is. We all got weak spots we don\'92t want nobody pokin\'92 around in.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  I got my best friend killed,\plain \f2\fs24 Darrick thought,\plain \f2\i\fs24 and if I told you that, would you still be my friend?\plain \f2\fs24 He didn\'92t believe that Sahyir could, and that hurt him. The old man was salt of the earth; he stood by his friends and even stood by a stranger who couldn\'92t take care of himself.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Whatever it is about this symbol that draws ye,\'94 Sahyir said, \'93is yer business. I just wanted to tell ye about this man \'92cause he\'92s only gonna be in town a few days.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He doesn\'92t live here?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If he had,\'94 Sahyir said with a grin, \'93I\'92d probably have talked to him before, now, wouldn\'92t I?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick smiled. It seemed there wasn\'92t anyone in Seeker\'92s Point who didn\'92t know Sahyir. \'93Probably,\'94 Darrick said. \'93Who is this man?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93A sage,\'94 Sahyir replied, \'93to hear him tell it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Do you believe him?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye, I do. If\'92n I didn\'92t, an\'92 didn\'92t think maybe he could do ye some good, why, we\'92d never be having this talk, now, would we?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick nodded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Accordin\'92 to what I got from him last night,\'94 Sahyir said, \'93he\'92s gonna be at the Blue Lantern tonight.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What does he know about me?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Nothin\'92.\'94 Sahyir shrugged. \'93Me, young pup? Why, I done forgot more secrets than I ever been told.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93This man knows what this symbol represents?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He knows somewhat of it. He seemed more concerned learnin\'92 what I knew of it. \'92Course, I couldn\'92t tell him{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint215}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint215}nothin\'92 \'92cause I don\'92t know nothin\'92. But I figured maybe ye could learn from each other.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick thought about the possibility as the barge closed on the shoreline. \'93Why were you telling me about the Church of the Prophet of the Light?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because this symbol ye\'92re thinkin\'92 about so much? That sage thinks maybe it\'92s tied into all that what\'92s going on down in Bramwell. And the Church of the Prophet of the Light. He thinks maybe it\'92s evil.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The old man\'92s words filled Darrick\'92s stomach with cold dread. He had no doubt that the symbol denoted evil, but he no longer knew if he wanted any part of it. Still, he didn\'92t want to let Mat\'92s death go unavenged.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If this sage is so interested in what\'92s going on down in Bramwell, what is he doing here?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because of Shonna\'92s Logs. He came here to read Shonna\'92s Logs.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Buyard Cholik lay supine on a bed in the back room of the Church of the Prophet of the Light and knew that he was dying. His breath rattled and heaved in his chest, and his lungs filled with his own blood. Try as he might, he could not see the face of the man\'97or woman\'97who had so gravely wounded him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  In the beginning, the pain from the arrow embedded in his chest had felt as if a red-hot poker had been shoved into him. When the pain had begun to subside, he\'92d mistakenly believed it was because he hadn\'92t been as badly hurt as he\'92d at first feared. Then he\'92d realized that he wasn\'92t getting better; the pain was going away because he was dying. Death closing in on him robbed him of his senses.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He silently damned the Zakarum Church and the Light he\'92d grown to love and fear as a child. Wherever they were, he was certain that they were laughing at him now. Here he was, his youth returned to him, stricken down by an unknown assassin. He damned the Light for abandoning him to old age when it could have killed him young{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint216}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint216}before fear of getting infirm and senile had settled in, and he damned it for letting him be weak enough to allow his fear to force him to seek a bargain with Kabraxis. The Light had driven him into the demon\'92s arms, and he\'92d been betrayed again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  You haven\'92t been betrayed, Buyard Cholik\plain \f2\fs24 , Kabraxis\'92s calm voice told him.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Do you think I would let you die?
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik had believed the demon would let him die. After all, there were plenty of other priests and even acolytes who could step into the brief void that Cholik felt he would leave in his passing.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  You will not die,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 We still have business to do together, you and I. Clear the room that I may enter. I don\'92t have enough power to maintain an illusion to mask myself and heal you at the same time.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik drew a wheezing breath. Fear rushed through him, winding hard and coarse as a dry-mouthed lizard\'92s tongue. He had less room to breathe now than he had during his last breath. His lungs were filling up with his blood, but there was hardly any pain.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Hurry. If you would live, Buyard Cholik, hurry.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Coughing, gasping, Cholik forced open his heavy eyelids. The tall ceiling of his private rooms remained blurred and indistinct. Blackness ate at the edges of his vision, steadily creeping inward, and he knew if it continued it would consume him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Do it now!
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Priests attended Cholik, putting compresses on the wound in his chest. The crossbow quarrel jutted out, the shaft and feathers speckled with his blood. Acolytes stood in the background while mercenaries guarded the doorway. The room was decorated with the finest silks and hand-carved furniture. An embroidered rug from the Kurast markets covered the center of the stone floor.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik opened his mouth to speak and only made a hoarse croaking noise. His breath sprayed fine crimson droplets.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What is it, Master Sayes?\'94 the priest beside Cholik\'92s bed asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint217}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint217}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Out,\'94 Cholik gasped. \'93Get out! Now!\'94 The effort to speak nearly drained him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But, master,\'94 the priest protested. \'93Your wounds\'97\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Out, I said.\'94 Cholik tried to rise and was surprised that he somehow found the strength.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  I am with you,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said, and Cholik felt a little stronger.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The priests and acolytes drew back as if watching the dead return to life. Perplexity and maybe a little relief showed on the faces of the mercenaries. A dead employer meant possibly some blame in the matter, and definitely no more gold.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Go,\'94 Cholik wheezed. \'93\plain \f2\i\fs24 Now. Now\plain \f2\fs24 , damn you all, or I\'92ll see to it that you\'92re lost in one of the hell pits that surround the Black Road.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The priests turned and ordered the acolytes and the mercenaries from the room. They closed the massive oaken double doors, shutting him off from the hallway.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Standing beside the bed where he\'92d lain hovering between life and death, Cholik gripped a small stand that held a delicate glass vase that had been blown in the hands of a master. Flowers and butterflies hung trapped in death inside the glass walls of the vase, preserved by some small magic that had not allowed them to burn while the molten glass had been formed and cooled.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The secret door hidden at the back of the chamber opened, turning on hinges so that the section of wall twisted to reveal the large tunnel behind it. The church was honeycombed with such tunnels to make it easier for the demon to get around inside the buildings. Even as tall as the ceiling was, the demon\'92s horns almost scraped it.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Hurry,\'94 Cholik gasped. The room blurred further still, then abruptly seemed to spin around him. Only a moment of dizziness touched him, but he saw the rug on the floor coming up at him and knew he was falling although there was no sensation of doing so.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Before Cholik hit the floor, Kabraxis caught him in his huge, three-fingered hands.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint218}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint218}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You will not die,\'94 the demon said, but his words took on more the aspect of a command. \'93We are not done yet, you and I.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Even though the demon was in his face, Cholik barely heard the words. His hearing was failing him now. His heart had slowed within his chest, no longer able to struggle against his blood-filled lungs. He tried to take a breath, but there was no room. Panic set in, but it was only a distant drumbeat at his temples, no longer able to touch him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Kabraxis stated, gripping Cholik by the shoulders.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A bolt of fire coursed through Cholik\'92s body. It ignited at the base of his spine, then raced up to the bottom of his skull and exploded behind his eyes. He went blind for a moment, but it was white light instead of darkness that filled his vision. He felt the pain of the quarrel as it was ripped from his chest. The agony almost pushed him over the edge of consciousness.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Breathe,\'94 Kabraxis said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik couldn\'92t. He thought perhaps he didn\'92t remember how or that he lacked the strength. Either way, no air entered his lungs. The world outside his body no longer mattered; everything felt cottony and distant.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Then renewed pain forked through his chest, following the path the quarrel had made and spiking into his lungs. Gripped by the pain, Cholik instinctively took a breath. Air filled his lungs\'97now empty of blood\'97and with each heaving breath he took, the incredible iron bands of pain released their hold on him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Kabraxis guided him to the edge of the bed. Cholik only then realized that his blood smeared the bed coverings. He gasped, drinking down air as the room steadied around him. Anger settled into him then, and he glanced up at the demon.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Did you know about the assassin?\'94 Cholik demanded. He imagined that Kabraxis had let the assassin shoot him only to remind Cholik how much he was needed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94 Kabraxis crossed his arms over his huge chest. Muscles rippled in his forearms and shoulders.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint219}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint219}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How could you not know? We built this place. You have wards everywhere around the grounds.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I was also making your miracle happen at the time of your attack,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93I made two whole boys from the conjoined twins, and that was no easy feat. People will be talking about that for years. While I was still working on that, your assassin struck.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You couldn\'92t save me from that arrow?\'94 Assessing the demon\'92s abilities and powers had been out of Cholik\'92s reach. Did the Black Road consume Kabraxis so much that it left him weak? That knowledge might be important. But it was also frightening to realize that the demon was limited and fallible after Cholik had tied his destiny to Kabraxis.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I trusted the mercenaries hired with the gold that I have made available to you to save you from something like this,\'94 Kabraxis answered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Don\'92t make that mistake again,\'94 Cholik snapped.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Deliberately, Kabraxis twisted the bloody quarrel in his hands. Lines in his harsh face deepened. \'93Never make the mistake of assuming you are my equal, Buyard Cholik. Familiarity breeds contempt, but it also pushes you toward sudden death.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Watching the demon, Cholik realized that Kabraxis could just as easily thrust the bolt through his chest again. Only this time the demon could pierce his heart. He swallowed, hardly able to get around the thick lump in his throat. \'93Of course. Forgive me. I forgot myself in the heat of the moment.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Kabraxis nodded, dipping his horns, almost scratching the ceiling.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Did the guards catch the assassin?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93They failed even in that? They could not protect me, and they could not get vengeance on the person who nearly killed me?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Disinterested, the demon dropped the quarrel to the floor. \'93Punish the guards as you see fit, but realize that something else has come of this.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint220}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint220}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Kabraxis faced Cholik. \'93Hundreds of people saw you killed today. They were certain of it. There was much weeping and wailing among them.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The thought that the crowd had lamented his apparent death filled Cholik with smugness. He liked the way the people of Bramwell curried favor with him when he passed through the city\'92s streets, and he liked the desperate envy he saw in their eyes regarding his place in the worship of their new prophet. They acknowledged the power that he wielded, each in his or her own way.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Those people thought the Way of Dreams was going to be denied to them as a result of your murder,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93Now, however, they\'92re going to believe that you\'92re something much more than human, made whole again by Dien-Ap-Sten. Talk will go out past Bramwell even more, and the miracles that were seen here will grow in the telling.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik thought about that. Although he would not have chosen the action, he knew that what the demon said was true. His fame, and that of Dien-Ap-Sten, would grow because of the murder attempt. Ships and caravans would carry the stories of the conjoined twins and his near assassination across the sea and the land. The stories, as they always did, would become larger than life as each person told another.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93More people will come, Buyard Cholik,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93And they will want to be made to believe. We must be prepared for them.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Striding to the window, Cholik looked out at Bramwell. The city was already bursting at the seams as a result of the church\'92s success. Ships filled the harbor, and tent camps had sprung up in the forests around Bramwell.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93An army of believers lies outside the walls of this church waiting to get in,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93This church is too small to deal with them all.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The city,\'94 Cholik said, understanding. \'93The city will be too small to hold them all after this.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint221}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint221}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Soon,\'94 Kabraxis agreed, \'93that will be true.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Turning to face the demon, Cholik said, \'93You didn\'92t think it would happen this quickly.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Kabraxis gazed at him. \'93I knew. I prepared. Now, you must prepare.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You must bring another to me whom I may remake as I have remade you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Jealousy flamed through Cholik. Sharing his power and his prestige wasn\'92t acceptable.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You won\'92t be sharing,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93Instead, you will take on greater power by acquiring this person and bending him to our power.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What person?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Lord Darkulan.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik considered that. Lord Darkulan ruled Bramwell and had a close relationship with the King of Westmarch. During the problem with Tristram, Lord Darkulan had been one of the king\'92s most trusted advisors.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Lord Darkulan has let people know he\'92s suspicious of the church,\'94 Cholik countered. \'93In fact, there was talk for a time of outlawing the church. He would have done it if the people hadn\'92t stood so firmly against that, and if the opportunity for taxing the caravans and ships bringing the people from other lands hadn\'92t come up.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Lord Darkulan\'92s concern has been understandable. He\'92s been afraid that we would win the allegiance of his people.\'94 Kabraxis smiled. \'93We have. After today, that is a foregone conclusion.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why are you so sure?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because Lord Darkulan was in the audience today.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint222}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint222}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  SEVENTEEN
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 A chill stole over Cholik at Kabraxis\'92s announcement about Lord Darkulan\'92s presence in the church. The man had never come there before.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \'93Lord Darkulan entered the church disguised,\'94 Kabraxis went on. \'93No one knew he was here except for his bodyguards and me. And now you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He may have hired the assassin,\'94 Cholik said, feeling his anger rise. He gazed down at his chest, seeing the crimson-stained robe and the hole where the quarrel had penetrated. Only unblemished flesh showed beneath now.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why are you so certain?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because the assassin strove alone to murder you,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93If Lord Darkulan had organized the murder, he would have ordered three or four crossbowmen into the church. You would have been dead before you hit the floor.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik\'92s mouth went dry. A thought occurred to him, one that he didn\'92t want to investigate, but he was drawn to it as surely as a moth was drawn to the candle flame. \'93If they had killed me, would you have been able to return me to life?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If I\'92d had to do that, Buyard Cholik, you would not have recognized the true chill of death. But neither would you have known again the fiery passion of life.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  An undead thing\plain \f2\fs24 , Cholik realized. The thought almost made him sick. Images of lurching zombies and skeletons with ivory grins came to him. As a priest for the Zakarum Church, he\'92d been called on to clear graveyards and buildings of undead things that had once been humans and animals.{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint223}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint223}And he had nearly been damned with coming back as one of them. His stomach twisted in rebellion, and sour bile painted the back of his mouth.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You would not have been merely animated as those things were,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93I would have gifted you with true unlife. Your thoughts would have remained your own.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And my desires?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Your desires and mine are closely aligned at this time. There would have been little you would have missed.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik didn\'92t believe it. Demons lived their lives differently from men, with different dreams and passions. Still, he couldn\'92t help wondering if he would have been less\'97or more?
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Perhaps,\'94 Kabraxis said, \'93when you are more ready, you\'92ll be given the chance to find out. For now, you\'92ve learned to hang on to your life as it is.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then why was Lord Darkulan here?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The demon smiled, baring his fangs. \'93Lord Darkulan has a favored mistress dying of a slow-acting poison that was given to her by Lady Darkulan only yesterday.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why? To kill her, of course. It seems that Lady Darkulan is a jealous woman and only discovered three days ago that her husband was seeing this other woman.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Wives have killed their husbands\'92 mistresses before,\'94 Cholik said. Even past royal courts of Westmarch had stories about such events.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Kabraxis replied, \'93but it appears that Lord Darkulan\'92s mistress of the last three months is also the daughter of the leader of the Bramwell merchants\'92 guild. If the daughter should die, the merchant will wreak havoc with Bramwell\'92s trade agreements and use his influence in the Westmarch royal courts to have his daughter\'92s murderess brought to justice.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Hodgewell means to have Lady Darkulan brought up on charges?\'94 Cholik couldn\'92t believe it. He knew the merchant Kabraxis was talking about. Ammin Hodgewell was a spiteful, vengeful man who had stood against the Church of the Prophet of the Light since its inception.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint224}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint224}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Hodgewell means to have her hanged on the Block of Justice. He\'92s working now to bring charges against Lady Darkulan.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Lord Darkulan knows this?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why doesn\'92t he enlist the aid of an apothecary?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He has,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93Several of them, in fact, since it was discovered yesterday that his mistress is doomed to a lingering illness. None of the apothecaries or healers can save her. She has only one salvation left to her.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The Way of Dreams,\'94 Cholik breathed. The implications of the impending murder swirled in his mind, banishing all thoughts of his near death.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93You understand.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik glanced at the demon, hardly daring to hope. \'93If Lord Darkulan comes to us for aid and we are able to save his mistress from the poison, save his wife from being hanged, and keep the peace in Bramwell\'97\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We will claim him on the Black Road,\'94 the demon said. \'93Then Lord Darkulan will be ours now and forever. He will be our springboard into Westmarch and the destiny that lies before us.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik shook his head. \'93Lord Darkulan is no young man to give into his passions with a woman of Merchantman Hodgewell\'92s standing.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He had no choice,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93The young woman\'92s desire for him became overwhelming. And Lord Darkulan\'92s desires for her became strong as well.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Understanding flooded Cholik, and he gazed at the demon in wonder. \'93You.\plain \f2\i\fs24 You\plain \f2\fs24 did this.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Of course.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What about the poison that Lady Darkulan used? I can\'92t believe that all of Lord Darkulan\'92s healers and apothecaries couldn\'92t find an antidote.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I gave it to Lady Darkulan,\'94 Kabraxis admitted, \'93even as I consoled her over her husband\'92s infidelity. Once she had the poison, she wasted no time in the administration of it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint225}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint225}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How much longer does Hodgewell\'92s daughter have before the poison kills her?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Till tomorrow night.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And Lord Darkulan knows this?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then today\'97\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I believe he meant to come forward today after the service,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93Your attempted assassination caused his bodyguards to get him clear of the church. Some of the church\'92s guards\'97as well as the lord\'92s protectors\'97were killed in that maneuver, which helped cover the real assassin\'92s escape.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then Lord Darkulan will still come,\'94 Cholik said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He must,\'94 Kabraxis agreed. \'93He has no choice. Unless he wishes to see his mistress dead by nightfall tomorrow and witness his wife\'92s hanging shortly after that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Lord Darkulan might take his wife and try to run.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Kabraxis grinned. \'93And leave his riches and power behind? For the love of a woman he betrayed? A woman who can no longer love him back in the same manner as before? No. Lord Darkulan would see them both dead before he would willingly abdicate his position here. But even that won\'92t save him. If all of this comes to light and the women die\'97\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Especially when the people believe he could have saved them both by turning to the Church of the Prophet of the Light as they have all done with their own problems,\'94 Cholik said, halfway stunned by the devious simplicity of Kabraxis\'92s scheme, \'93Lord Darkulan will fall out of favor with the populace.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You do see,\'94 Kabraxis said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik stared at the demon. \'93Why didn\'92t you tell me any of this?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I did,\'94 Kabraxis explained. \'93As soon as you needed to know.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Part of Cholik\'92s upbringing in the Zakarum Church whispered into the back of his mind.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Demons can influence men, but only if those men are willing to listen.\plain \f2\fs24 At any point, Kabraxis\'92s multitiered scheme might have come apart. The{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint226}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint226}mistress might not have fallen for the lord. The lord might not have betrayed his lady or might have broken the relationship off and confessed his indiscretions. And the lady might have taken a lover out of vengeance rather than poison the woman who took her husband.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  If the plan had not worked, Cholik would never have known, and the demon\'92s pride would have been intact.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I humbled them all,\'94 Kabraxis said, \'93and I have brought these lands under our control. And we will have some of the most powerful people here as our allies. Lord Darkulan will be thankful for the salvation of his mistress, just as Merchantman Hodgewell will be grateful for the salvation of his daughter.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik examined the plan. It was bold and cunning and duplicitous\'97exactly what he would have expected from a demon. \'93We have it all,\'94 he said, looking back at Kabraxis.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 the demon replied. \'93And we will have more.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Someone knocked on the chamber doors.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What?\'94 Cholik said with some annoyance.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Master Sayes,\'94 the priest called from the other side, \'93I only wanted to know that you were all right.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Go to them,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93We will talk again later.\'94 He retreated to the back of the room and passed through the secret door.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik strode to the door and flung it open. The priests, acolytes, and mercenaries stepped back. One of the mercenaries held a small girl before him, one hand clapped over her mouth as she struggled to get free.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Master,\'94 the head priest said, \'93I beg your forgiveness. Only my worry over you prompted me to interrupt you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I am fine,\'94 Cholik said, knowing the priest would continue to excuse himself out of his own fear.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But the arrow went so deep,\'94 the priest said. \'93I saw it for myself.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I was healed by the grace of Dien-Ap-Sten.\'94 Cholik pulled his robe open, revealing the unmarked flesh beneath the bloody clothing. \'93Great is the power of the Prophet of the Light.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint227}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint227}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Great is the power of the Prophet of the Light,\'94 the priests replied at once. \'93May Dien-Ap-Sten\'92s mercies be eternal.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik pulled his robe back around himself. He looked at the struggling girl in the mercenary\'92s hands. \'93What is this child doing here?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93She is the sister to the boys that Dien-Ap-Sten made whole today,\'94 the mercenary said. \'93She also saw the assassin.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93This child did, and yet you and your men did not?\'94 Cholik\'92s voice held the unforgiving edge of bared steel.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93She stood beside him when he loosed his shaft at you, Master Sayes,\'94 the mercenary replied. He looked uncomfortable.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik stepped toward the man. The priests and the other mercenaries moved back, as if expecting Cholik to summon down a lightning bolt to reduce the mercenary leader to ash. The thought, Cholik had to admit, was tempting. He looked away from the quaking mercenary and at the girl. The resemblance between the girl and the conjoined twins was striking.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Tears leaked from the girl\'92s eyes as she shuddered and cried. Her fear had turned her pale.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Release her,\'94 Cholik said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Reluctantly, the mercenary removed his big, callused hand from the girl\'92s mouth. She drew in a deep, quaking breath. Tears continued to trickle down her face as she glanced around, seeking some way to escape.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Are you all right, child?\'94 Cholik asked in a soft voice.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I want my da,\'94 the girl said. \'93I want my ma. I didn\'92t do anything.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Did you see the man who shot me?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes.\'94 Her tear-filled eyes gazed up at Cholik. \'93Please, Master Sayes. I didn\'92t do anything. I would have screamed, but he was too fast. He shot you before I could think. I didn\'92t think he was going to do it. I wouldn\'92t hurt you. You saved my brothers. Mikel and Dannis. You saved them. I wouldn\'92t hurt you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint228}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint228}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik put a comforting hand on the girl\'92s shoulder. He felt her shudder and cringe at his touch. \'93Easy, child. I only need to know about the man who tried to kill me. I won\'92t hurt you, either.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  She looked at him. \'93Promise?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The girl\'92s innocence touched Cholik. Promises were easy to give to the young; they wanted to believe.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I promise,\'94 Cholik said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The girl looked around, as if making sure the hard-faced mercenaries had heard Master Sayes\'92s promise as well.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93They will not touch you,\'94 Cholik said. \'93Describe the man who shot me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  She gazed at him in big-eyed wonderment. \'93I thought he killed you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He can\'92t,\'94 Cholik said. \'93I\'92m one of the chosen of Dien-Ap-Sten. No mortal man may take my life as long as I stay in the prophet\'92s favor.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The girl sipped air again, becoming almost calm. \'93He was burned. Nearly all of his face was burned. His hands and arms were burned.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The description meant nothing to Cholik. \'93Is there anything else you noticed about him?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94 The girl hesitated.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What is it?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I think he was afraid that you would know him if you saw him,\'94 the girl said. \'93He said that he was surprised that he was let into the building.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ve never seen a man burned so badly as you say who still lived.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Maybe he didn\'92t live,\'94 the girl said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What makes you say that?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I don\'92t know. I just don\'92t see how anyone could live after being burned so bad, is all.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Pursued by a dead man?\plain \f2\fs24 Cholik turned the thought over in his mind for a short time.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Come,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said in his mind.\plain \f2\i\fs24 We have things to do. The assassin is gone.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint229}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint229}\plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik reached into the pocket of his robe and took out a few silver coins. The amount was enough to feed a family in Bramwell for months. Once, perhaps, the money might have meant something to him. Now, it was only a bargaining tool. He placed the silver coins in the girl\'92s hand and folded her fingers over them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Take this, girl,\'94 Cholik said, \'93as a token of my appreciation.\'94 He glanced up at the nearest mercenary. \'93See that she gets back to her family.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The mercenary nodded and led the little girl away. She never once looked back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Despite the fact that more than a year had passed since he\'92d found Kabraxis\'92s gateway under the remains of Tauruk\'92s Port and Ransim, Cholik\'92s mind wandered back to the labyrinth and the chamber where he\'92d released the demon back into the human world. One man had escaped that night, a Westmarch sailor who had even evaded the skeletons and zombies Kabraxis had raised to kill everyone there.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik felt that no one in Bramwell would have dared attack him in the church. And if the man were burned as badly as the girl described, someone would have come forward to identify him and hope to earn a reward from Dien-Ap-Sten or himself.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  So it had been an outsider. Someone not even the populace of the city had known about. Yet it had to be someone who had known Cholik from before.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Where had the man who had escaped from Tauruk\'92s Port gone? If this was him, and it made no sense for it to be anyone else, why had he waited so long before he\'92d stepped forward? And why approach Cholik now at all?
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  It was unsettling. Especially when Cholik thought about how near the quarrel had come to piercing his heart. Thoughts churning, Cholik reentered his private chamber to plan and scheme with the demon he had freed. Whatever chance the assassin had had was now gone. Cholik would never be caught unprepared again. He consoled himself with that.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\qc\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f0\fs20 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\qc\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 ***
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint230}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint230}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Back and shoulders on fire from all the lifting he\'92d done during the day, Darrick entered the Blue Lantern. Pipe smoke and the closing night filled the tavern with darkness. Men swapping stories and telling lies filled the tavern with noise. To the west, near where the mouth of the Gulf of Westmarch met the Frozen Sea, the sunset settled into the water, looking like dying red embers scattered from a stirred campfire.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A cold north wind followed Darrick into the tavern. The weather had changed in the last hour, just as the ships\'92 captains and mates had been thinking it would. Come morning, Sahyir had told Darrick, there might even be a layer of ice covering the harbor. It wouldn\'92t be enough to lock the ships in, but that time wasn\'92t far off, either.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Men looked up as Darrick walked through the small building. Some of the men knew him, and some were from the ships out in the harbor. All of their eyes were wary. Seeker\'92s Point wasn\'92t a big village, but the numbers swelled when ships were in the harbor. And if a man wanted trouble in the village, the Blue Lantern was where he came.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  There was no table space in the tavern. Three men Darrick knew slightly offered their tables with their friends. Darrick thanked them but declined, passing on through the tables till he spotted the man Sahyir had talked about earlier that day.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The man was in his middle years, gray showing in his square-cut beard. He was broad-shouldered and a little overweight, a solid man who had seen an active life. His clothing was second-hand, worn but comfortable-looking, and warm enough against the cool winds blowing in from the north. He wore round-lensed spectacles, and Darrick could still count on the fingers of both hands how many times he\'92d seen such devices.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A platter of bread and meat sat to the sage\'92s left. He wrote with his right hand, pausing every now and again to dip his quill into an inkwell beside the book he worked in.A whale-oil lantern near the book provided him more light to work by.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint231}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint231}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick stopped only a short distance from the table, uncertain what he should say.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Abruptly, the sage looked up, peering over his spectacles. \'93Darrick?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Startled, Darrick said nothing.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Your friend Sahyir named you,\'94 the sage said. \'93He told me when he talked to me last night that you might be stopping by.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick said. \'93Though I must confess I don\'92t truly know what I\'92m doing here.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If you\'92ve seen that symbol as Sahyir seems inclined to believe that you have,\'94 the sage said, \'93it\'92s probably marked you.\'94 He gestured to the book before him. \'93The Light knows that the pursuit of knowledge about it has marked me. Much to my own detriment, according to some of my mentors and peers.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92ve seen the demon?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Renewed interest flickered in the sage\'92s deep green eyes. \'93You have?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick paused, feeling that he\'92d admitted more than he should have.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  An irritable look filled the sage\'92s face. \'93Damnation, son. If you\'92re going to talk, then sit. I\'92ve been working hard for days here, and weeks and months before that in other places. Looking up gets hellaciously tiresome for me.\'94 He pointed at a chair across from him with the quill, then closed his book and put it aside.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Still feeling uncertain, Darrick pulled out the chair and sat. Out of habit, he laid his sheathed cutlass across his thighs.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sage laced his fingers together and rested both elbows on the tabletop. \'93Have you eaten tonight?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94 Unloading imported goods from the ship and then loading exported goods had filled the day. Darrick had only eaten what he\'92d carried along in the food bag, which had been empty for hours.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Would you like to eat?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint232}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint232}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sage gestured to one of the serving wenches. The young woman went to get the order immediately.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Sahyir told me you were a sailor,\'94 the sage said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Tell me where you saw the demon,\'94 the sage suggested.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick held himself in check. \'93I never said that I saw such a thing, now, did I?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A frown deepened the wrinkles over the sage\'92s eyes. \'93Are you always this churlish?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Sir,\'94 Darrick stated evenly, \'93I don\'92t even know your name.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Taramis,\'94 the sage replied. \'93Taramis Volken.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And what is it that you do, Taramis Volken?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I gather wisdom,\'94 the man replied. \'93Especially that pertaining to demons.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because I don\'92t like them, and usually the things that I learn can be used against them.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The serving wench returned with a platter of goat\'92s meat and shrimp and fish, backed by fresh bread and portions of melon that had shipped up that day. She offered mulled wine.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The temptation was there only for a moment for Darrick. For the last year he had tried to bury his life and his pain in wine and spirits. It hadn\'92t worked, and only old Sahyir had seen fit to save him from himself. But as the old man had told him, saving himself was a day-to-day job, and only one man could do that.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Tea,\'94 Darrick said. \'93Please.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The wench nodded and returned with a tall tankard of unsweetened tea.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93So,\'94 Taramis said, \'93about your demon\'97\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Not my demon,\'94 Darrick said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A fleeting smile touched the sage\'92s lips. \'93As you will. Where did you see the demon?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick ignored the question. He dipped his finger into the gravy on his plate and drew out the ellipses with the{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint233}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint233}single line threading through them. He even drew the symbol so that the line went under and over the appropriate ellipses.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sage studied the gravy symbol. \'93Do you know what this is?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Or whom it belongs to?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick shook his head.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Where did you see this?\'94 the sage asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Darrick replied. \'93You\'92ll get nothing from me until I\'92m convinced I\'92m getting something from you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sage reached into the worn lizard-hide traveler\'92s pack in the chair beside him. Thoughtfully, he took out a pipe and a bag. After shoving the bowl full of tobacco, he set his pipe ablaze with the lantern. He smoked in silence, a hazy wreath forming around his head. He never blinked as he stared at Darrick.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Fresh-shaved that morning, Darrick hadn\'92t seen a more fiercely demanding gaze since the mirror then. Even the Westmarch ships\'92 officers paled by comparison. But he ate, savoring the hot food. By the working standards he was accustomed to in Seeker\'92s Point, the meal was an extravagance. The cargo handling he\'92d done for the day might have to feed him for two weeks in order to keep him from hunting meager game in the forest with winter soon to be breathing down their necks.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis reached back into his traveler\'92s pack and took out another book. Flipping through the tome, he stopped at a page, laid the book on the table, spun it around, and pushed it across the table toward Darrick. The sage moved the lantern so it shone on the pages more directly.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The demon that you saw,\'94 Taramis said. \'93Did it look anything like this?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick glanced at the page. The illustration was done by hand and in great detail.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The picture was the demon he\'92d seen at Tauruk\'92s Port, the one who had summoned the undead creatures responsible for Mat Hu-Ring\'92s death.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint234}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint234}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Not entirely responsible,\plain \f2\fs24 Darrick told himself, feeling his appetite ebb. He owned the majority of that responsibility. He kept eating mechanically, knowing it would be days or weeks before he had the chance to eat so well again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What do you know about the symbol?\'94 Darrick asked, not answering the sage\'92s question.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92re a hard sell, aren\'92t you, boy?\'94 Taramis asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick broke a piece of bread and slathered honey butter onto it. He started eating while Taramis tried to wait him out.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Finally giving up, Taramis replied, \'93That symbol is the one that was longest associated with a demon called Kabraxis. He is supposed to be the guardian of the Twisted Path of Dreams and Shadows.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The Way of Dreams?\'94 Darrick asked, remembering the stories Sahyir had been telling about Bramwell that morning.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Interesting, isn\'92t it?\'94 the sage asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Sahyir told me he\'92d gone to church in Bramwell,\'94 Darrick said. \'93There\'92s a new church there called the Church of the Prophet of the Light. They also mention the Way of Dreams there.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis nodded. \'93They worship a prophet there named Dien-Ap-Sten.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Not Kabraxis?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It would be pretty stupid for a demon to be going around telling people to call him by his rightful name, now, wouldn\'92t it?\'94 Taramis grinned. \'93I mean, the whole bit of anonymity would be right out the window if that was the case. Most people wouldn\'92t worship a demon by choice, although there are some.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick waved a hand over his platter. \'93I appreciate this fine meal you went and bought me, I really do. But I have to tell you, if this story hasn\'92t picked up some by the time I finish, I\'92m out of here.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Patience isn\'92t one of your virtues, is it?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94 Darrick felt no shame in admitting such.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Kabraxis is an old and powerful demon,\'94 Taramis said.{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint235}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint235}\'93He\'92s been around, in one form or another, since the beginning of recorded history. He\'92s been known by dozens, possibly hundreds, of names.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick pointed to the gravy-rendered symbol on the tabletop. \'93And this is his symbol?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis puffed on his pipe. The coals in the pipe bowl glowed orange. \'93I believe this is the demon\'92s primary symbol. Did you see this in Bramwell?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ve not been to Bramwell in years,\'94 Darrick answered. It had been too close to Westmarch.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then where did you see the demon?\'94 The sage\'92s interest was intense.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I never said I did,\'94 Darrick reminded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Your friend told me\'97\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He told you that I knew about this symbol.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93That\'92s all you\'92ve ever told him?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick sipped his tea and ignored the question. He pointedly returned his attention to his meal. The plate steadily emptied.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Do you know the meaning of the symbol?\'94 Taramis asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It\'92s supposed to represent the layers of man. The facets of a man that a demon may prey on.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I don\'92t understand,\'94 Darrick said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sage seemed surprised. \'93You\'92ve had no priest\'92s training?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And yet you know of Kabraxis\'92s most potent symbol without training?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick said nothing as he used his knife to spear a potato chunk.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis sighed. \'93All right, then. You intrigue me, and that\'92s the only reason I\'92m going to continue, because I will not tolerate being treated in such a cavalier manner.\'94 He tapped the ellipses. \'93These are the layers of man as divined by Kabraxis, Banisher of the Light.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why is he called Banisher of the Light?\'94 Darrick asked.{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint236}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint236}He glanced around them, making sure none of the sailors or longshoremen was taking much interest in their conversation. In some communities, the discussion of demons was enough to get a man strung up or, at the least, tested by a dunking chair or a red-hot poker.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because Kabraxis\'92s main objective in the world of man is to eclipse and replace Zakarum. Kabraxis worked during the Sin War to keep Zakarum from being brought forth by the Archangel Yaerius through his disciple Akarat.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What of the Archangel Inarius?\'94 Darrick asked, remembering the old stories he\'92d been told of the Sin War. \'93It was Inarius who first built a Cathedral of Light in this world.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Inarius grew overconfident and destroyed Mephisto\'92s temple, and Inarius was enslaved and returned with the Seraph to Hell to be tortured for all time. Kabraxis aided in Inarius\'92s downfall by winning them over to the demon\'92s side.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I don\'92t remember that,\'94 Darrick said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The war was primarily between Mephisto and Inarius,\'94 Taramis said. \'93Only a sage or someone who has had priest training would know of Kabraxis\'92s part in the Sin War. The Banisher of Light is a conniving demon. Kabraxis works in the shadows, stretching their boundaries till they cover the Light. Most men who have worshipped him over all those years have never known his true name.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But you believe he is in Bramwell?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93At the Church of the Prophet of the Light.\'94 The sage nodded. \'93Yes. And there he is known as Dien-Ap-Sten.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick tapped the symbol. \'93What of this?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Again,\'94 Taramis said, \'93those ellipses represent the layers of man as Kabraxis perceives them. It is through those layers that he is able to reach into a man\'92s soul, twist it, bend it, and finally possess it. He is not by nature a confrontational demon as are Diablo, Mephisto, and Baal.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick shook his head. \'93You can\'92t go about just dropping{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint237}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint237}the names of all those demons like that. They aren\'92t real. They can\'92t be all real.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The Prime Evils are real.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A chill threaded through Darrick, but even after everything he\'92d seen\'97even after everything he\'92d lost after seeing the demon in Tauruk\'92s Port\'97he struggled to believe that the worlds of the demons, the Burning Hells, were real and not just stories.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Have you seen the Church of the Prophet of the Light?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It is huge,\'94 Taramis said. \'93In less than a year, the Church of the Prophet of the Light has become one of the most prominent structures in Bramwell.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Bramwell isn\'92t a big city,\'94 Darrick said. \'93Mainly fishermen and farmers live there. Westmarch barely keeps a garrison of guards there, and it\'92s mostly a show of support because no invading army would attack Westmarch through Bramwell. The roads are too harsh and uncertain.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Kabraxis takes generations to build his power,\'94 Taramis said. \'93That\'92s why even the unholy trinity of brothers learned to fear him. Where they waged war and fought with human armies with their own demonic ones, Kabraxis won believers to him.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Through the layers of man.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes.\'94 The sage tapped the outermost ellipse. \'93First is the fear mankind has of demons. People who fear Kabraxis will acknowledge his leadership, but they will break away at the first chance.\'94 He tapped the next ellipse. \'93Next comes greed. Through the Church of the Prophet of the Light, Kabraxis and the high priest known as Master Sayes, also called the Wayfinder have granted gifts to their worshippers. Good fortune in business, money, an unexpected inheritance. Then he moves closer to the heart.\'94 He tapped the next ellipse. \'93Covetousness. Do you secretly want your neighbor\'92s wife? His land? Worship Kabraxis, and it will be yours in time.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Only if the man you want those things from doesn\'92t worship Kabraxis as well.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint238}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint238}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Not true.\'94 Taramis paused to relight his pipe. \'93Kabraxis weighs and judges those who serve him. If one man\'97more powerful in the community than another\'97will better serve Kabraxis\'92s purposes, the Banisher of the Light rewards the more powerful man.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What of the worshipper who loses whatever the other man wants?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sage waved the question away. \'93Simple enough. Kabraxis tells everyone that the man who lost his lands or his wife or his family wasn\'92t strong in his faith. That he played Kabraxis\'97or, in this case, Dien-Ap-Sten\'97falsely and deserved what he got.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Sour bile rumbled in Darrick\'92s stomach. Every word the sage spoke had the ring of truth in it.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis moved to the next ellipse. \'93From that point, Kabraxis seeks out those people with greater fears. Sickness in your family? Come to the church to be healed. Your father is becoming senile? Come to the church, and have clarity returned to him.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Kabraxis can do these things?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Taramis said. \'93And more. Demons have many powers. In their own way, they offer salvation to those who serve them. You\'92ve heard of the gifts Diablo, Baal, and Mephisto have given their own champions in the past. Enchanted armor, mystical weapons, great power to raise armies of dead. The Prime Evils rule through fear and destruction, always aiming for subjugation.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Kabraxis has no interest in that?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Of course he does,\'94 Taramis said. \'93He\'92s a demon, after all. Even archangels want those who worship them to fear them just a little bit. Otherwise, why would they choose such fearsome forms and act the way they do?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick considered the question and supposed it was true. Still, all this talk of demons was foreign to him, something he didn\'92t even want to invest in. Yet he felt he had no choice.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Archangels for the Light threaten man with being tortured by demons for the rest of his eternal life, and they{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint239}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint239}promise dire vengeance for any who worship and aid the demons.\'94 Taramis shook his head. \'93Archangels are warriors, just as demons are.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But they have a more generous view of how man is supposed to fit into this world with them.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93That,\'94 the sage said, \'93depends on your belief, doesn\'92t it?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick sat quietly.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93There are some who believe this world should be cleansed of demons and angels, that there should be no Light or Darkness, and men should find their own way in life.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What do you believe?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I believe in the Light,\'94 Taramis replied. \'93That\'92s why I hunt demons and expose them for what they are. I\'92ve killed eight lesser demons in the last twenty years. Not all of them are the likes of the Prime Evils.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick knew that, but he\'92d only seen the one demon, and it had been a truly horrifying creature. \'93What are you going to do to Kabraxis?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Kill him if I can,\'94 the sage stated. \'93If not, I mean to see him exposed for what he is, his priest slain, and his church razed to the ground.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The man\'92s words drew Darrick in, and he took comfort in them. Taramis made doing such an incredible thing sound possible.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92ve lost someone to the demon,\'94 Taramis whispered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick drew back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Don\'92t bother to deny it,\'94 the sage said. \'93I see the truth in your eyes. You wear your pain like a chevron for anyone who has been through the same thing.\'94 He paused, his eyes sliding from Darrick\'92s for a moment. \'93I lost my family to a demon. Twenty-three years ago. I was a priest. Such a thing wasn\'92t supposed to happen to me. But a demon\'92s hand took my wife and my three children from me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The lantern light flickered on the table.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I was young then and full of my studies as a Vizjerei{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint240}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint240}mage. I taught in one of the outlying schools in my homelands. A stranger came to our door. We lived in back of the school, just my family and I. This man told us that he had no place to sleep and had eaten nothing for two days. Fool that I was and full of my new position, I let him in. During the night, he killed my family. Only I lived, though most thought I would not.\'94 He pulled back the sleeves of his shirt, revealing the long, wicked scars across his flesh. \'93I have more scars over the rest of my body.\'94 He tilted his head back, revealing the thick scar that curved around half of his neck and across his throat. \'93The priests who saved me had to piece me back together. All of the healers told me later that I should have died. The Light knows I wanted to.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But you lived,\'94 Darrick whispered, drawn into the horror of the story.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes.\'94 Taramis knocked ash from his pipe and put it away. \'93For a time, I resented my life. Then I came to realize that it was a more focused one. The demon that had killed my family would go on to kill other families. I resolved to get well, mentally and physically. And I did. It took me three years to heal and nine years to track down the demon that took my family from me. I had killed two other demons by that time and revealed four others.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And now you hunt Kabraxis?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes. When the Church of the Prophet of the Light first came into being, I became suspicious. So I began researching it and found enough similarities between the healing and the changes wrought within the worshippers to lead me in the direction of Kabraxis.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then why come here?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because,\'94 the sage said, \'93Kabraxis was once here. For a time, the barbarian tribes worshipped him when they warred against the people of the southern lands. During that time he was known as Iceclaw the Merciless. He succeeded in uniting some of the more powerful barbarian tribes, creating a great horde that landed between the Twin Seas, the Great Ocean, and the Frozen Sea.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint241}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint241}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick considered the implications. The stories about the barbarian horde went so far back that they were considered only tales to frighten children with. The barbarians had been depicted as cannibalistic warriors who filed their teeth and filled their bellies from the bodies of women and children. \'93Until Hauklin came with his great sword, Stormfury, and slew Iceclaw during a battle that took six days.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis grinned. \'93You\'92ve heard the stories.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick replied. \'93But that doesn\'92t answer why you\'92re here.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because Stormfury is still here,\'94 the sage answered. \'93I came for the sword because it is the only thing that can slay Kabraxis.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It didn\'92t slay him the first time,\'94 Darrick pointed out.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The texts I read said that Kabraxis fled before the devastating might of Stormfury. Only in the stories of men was the demon reported dead. But I believe the sword has the power to kill Kabraxis. If you can track him back into the Burning Hells with it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If you knew all of this, why did you bother to talk to me?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sage\'92s eyes searched Darrick. \'93Because I am one man, Darrick Lang, and I\'92m not as young as I used to be.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You know my name?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Of course.\'94 Taramis waved at the books before him. \'93I am a learned man. I heard the stories of the discovery of the demon at Tauruk\'92s Port more than a year ago while I was down in Westmarch. And I heard of the young navy officer who lost his best friend while carrying out a mission given him by the king\'92s nephew.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then why go through all this subterfuge?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93So that I could convince you of my cause,\'94 Taramis said softly, \'93and perhaps your destiny.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What destiny?\'94 Darrick immediately felt trapped.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92re tied to this thing somehow,\'94 the sage said. \'93You lost blood to Kabraxis, so perhaps that\'92s it. Or maybe there is something more that binds you to the demon.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I want nothing more to do with that demon,\'94 Darrick{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint242}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint242}said. But even as he said it, he felt uncertain, and with that uncertainty came a harsh wave of fear.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Really? Then how is it you\'92ve ended up here? Where the weapon that will cut Kabraxis down is?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ve been drunk most of the past year,\'94 Darrick said. \'93I lost my post in the Westmarch Navy. Drunk and destitute most of the time, I only drifted from town to town, finding enough work to keep myself alive and away from Westmarch. I didn\'92t know I was here till I woke up damn near freezing to death. I knew nothing of that sword until you told me just now. I haven\'92t been following a demon\'92s trail.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No?\'94 Taramis glanced at the elliptical symbol drawn in gravy on the tabletop. \'93Then what are you doing here now? Unless you\'92ve only come for a free meal.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Darrick admitted.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You already knew who that symbol belonged to before you spoke to me,\'94 Taramis said. \'93Now that you know the demon is in Bramwell, hiding behind the mystical auguries of the Church of the Prophet of the Light, can you truly walk away from this? From any of this?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Unbidden, the memory of Mat plunging over the cliffside to his doom trickled through Darrick\'92s mind in slow motion again. The pain, once blinded and muffled by drink for the past year, twisted within him again as if it were new and fresh. Anger raged within him, but somehow he managed to keep it under control.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The Light has guided you here, Darrick,\'94 the sage said in his quiet voice. \'93It has guided you here to this place and at this time, and made it possible for us to meet, because you have a stake in this. Because you can make a difference. My question is whether you\'92re ready to take up the battle that awaits you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick hesitated, knowing that either answer he gave\'97and, perhaps, even giving no answer at all\'97would doom him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You believe the sword can kill Kabraxis?\'94 Darrick asked in a hoarse whisper.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint243}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint243}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Taramis answered. \'93But only here in the final layer.\'94 He tapped the elliptical symbol again. \'93Two layers yet remain that we\'92ve not spoken of. The outermost is where Kabraxis takes initiates to forge them into something more than mere men. Here they must face the fears of a demon world, walk the Twisted Path of Dreams and Shadows. The Black Road.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The Black Road?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93As Kabraxis calls it. He\'92s had several names for it during his campaigns here in the world of men, but its true and proper name is the Twisted Path of Dreams and Shadows. Once facing the demonic world, Kabraxis\'92s chosen must give themselves to him, mind and body and soul, for now and forever. Many fail, and they are cast into the Burning Hells to die and die again for all eternity.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How are the men changed?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93They become faster and stronger than normal men,\'94 the sage replied. \'93Harder to kill. And some of them are given an understanding of demonic magic.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You make getting to Kabraxis sound impossible.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Not with Stormfury,\'94 Taramis said. \'93And I\'92m not without magic of my own.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What if I chose not to go?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then I would go alone.\'94 The sage smiled. \'93But you can\'92t deny this, can you, Darrick? This has become too much a part of you. Perhaps a year ago you would have been able to turn your back on me and walk away. But not now. You\'92ve tried to live around what happened to your friend and what happened to you. It\'92s nearly destroyed you.\'94 He paused. \'93Now you must find the strength to live through this.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick looked at the elliptical drawing. \'93What lies in the final layer?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Hesitating, Taramis shook his head. \'93I don\'92t know. The texts that I\'92ve read regarding Kabraxis have no answer. It has been referred to as the layer of the greatest fear, but I have no idea what that is.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It might be good to know what is there.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint244}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint244}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Perhaps we can find out together,\'94 the sage suggested.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick locked eyes with the man, wishing he were strong enough to say no, that he wouldn\'92t go. But he couldn\'92t do that because he was tired of trying to live half a life and avoid the guilt. He should have died with Mat. Perhaps the only way to escape was to die now.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick whispered. \'93I\'92ll go with you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint245}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint245}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  EIGHTEEN
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Buyard Cholik stood on the platform above the snake\'92s head and awaited the arrival of his guest. Anticipation filled Cholik as he surveyed the empty pews around him. That morning, he had been enthused to see the large room overflowing with people. Every day the service was larger than the day before. There was no longer seating for all those in attendance. Even building as quickly as they were able, the construction crews weren\'92t able to keep pace with the growth.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Yet tonight there was only one person in attendance, and Cholik\'92s elation soared even higher. He remained silent as Lord Darkulan paused at the great central entrance.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Around the lord, a score of armored guards held lanterns and bared weapons. The lantern light glinted from scale mail and keen-edged steel. Voices whispered, and in their barely heard words Cholik detected fear and hostility.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan was a young man of thirty. His regal bearing showed the regimen he used to stay in shape as a warrior as well as a leader of men. An open-faced helmet with fierce curved horns framed his lean, hawklike features. A mustache followed the sneering curve up his mouth. He wore a dark green cloak that blended with his black breeches and tunic over a dark green shirt. Although it was hidden, Cholik was certain the lord wore the mystical chainmail armor beneath the tunic.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Impatiently, Lord Darkulan waved to one of his warriors.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The man nodded and stepped into the main area of the cathedral. His metal-shod boots clanked as he crossed the stone floor into the cathedral proper.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint246}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint246}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik raised his voice, knowing from the way the room was constructed that it would be easily heard. \'93Lord Darkulan, this meeting time was set aside for you. No one else may enter this part of the church.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The warriors swung their lanterns in Cholik\'92s direction. Some of the lanterns had bull\'92s-eye construction and lit on Cholik directly.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik squinted against the blinding light but did not raise his hand to shield his eyes.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93These are only my personal bodyguards,\'94 Lord Darkulan responded. \'93They will offer you no harm. In fact, after the episode today, I thought you would appreciate their presence.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Cholik said. \'93You requested this meeting, and I acceded to it. We will keep it like that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And if I insist?\'94 Lord Darkulan asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik spoke words of power and thrust his hands straight out. Flames leapt from his fingertips and ignited the oil-filled channels around the snake\'92s head. Alive once more, the snake\'92s head leapt from the stone wall toward the guard.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Unnerved, the guard threw himself backward. His metal-shod boots scraped sparks from the stone floor as he hurried to rejoin the other guards. The warriors clustered around Lord Darkulan, trying to draw him back to safety. Lanterns swirled like a cloud of fireflies in the main entrance.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Would you have your mistress die?\'94 Cholik asked as he rode the swaying snake\'92s head. \'93Would you have your lady hung by the neck? Would you have your own good name dragged through the mud and dung of this city? Especially when I can change all that?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan cursed his men and fought them off him. Reluctantly, the warriors stepped away from him. Their leaders talked quickly to their lord, trying to get him to listen to their reason.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The lord paused at the mouth of the entrance and stared at Cholik atop the stone snake\'92s head. Below Cholik, fire{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint247}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint247}clung to the snake\'92s jaws, and he knew it must be a horrific sight in the middle of the dark cathedral.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93They said you were killed this morning,\'94 Lord Darkulan said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik spread his arms, enjoying the role he played. \'93Do I look like a dead man, Lord Darkulan?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93More like he\'92s a zombie,\'94 one of the guards muttered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92m no zombie,\'94 Cholik said. \'93Come closer, Lord Darkulan, that you may hear my heartbeat. Perhaps, should you truly not believe, I\'92ll let you bleed me. Zombies and dead things don\'92t bleed as the living do.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why can\'92t my men accompany me?\'94 Lord Darkulan asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because if I am to save the people in your life whom you wish saved\'97if I am to save\plain \f2\i\fs24 you,\plain \f2\fs24 Lord Darkulan\'97you must trust me.\'94 Cholik waited, trying not to act as though he had as much depending on the lord\'92s decision as he did. He wondered if Kabraxis were watching, then realized that wasn\'92t the proper question. The proper question was from where the demon watched.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan took a lantern from one of his men, steeled himself for a moment, then strode into the cathedral. \'93How is it that you know so much about my business and the affairs of state?\'94 he demanded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I am the Wayfinder,\'94 Cholik declared. \'93Chosen of Dien-Ap-Sten himself. How could I not know?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93A few among those who counsel me suggest that somehow you and this church are behind the troubles that plague me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Do you believe that, Lord Darkulan?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The lord hesitated. \'93I don\'92t know.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93This morning you saw me dead, slain by a quarrel from the hand of a treacherous assassin. Yet here I stand. I am whole and alive and ready to help you in your hour of need, my lord. Or perhaps I should turn from you as you have turned from Dien-Ap-Sten and this church since we first began our sojourn among you.\'94 Cholik paused. \'93I could do that, you know. There are some among my own{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint248}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint248}counsel who believe the assassin who tried to kill me today was hired by you and that you are jealous of my own rise to power within your community.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Those are lies,\'94 Lord Darkulan responded. \'93I have never been one to skulk around.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And does Lady Darkulan still feel that is a fair assessment of you?\'94 Cholik asked softly.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan\'92s hand dropped to the hilt of his saber. His voice turned gruff and hard. \'93Don\'92t press your luck, priest.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I stared death in the eye today, Lord Darkulan. Your threats won\'92t carry much weight with me. I know that I walk hand-in-hand with Dien-Ap-Sten.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I could have you driven from this church,\'94 Lord Darkulan said angrily.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93There are more citizens and visitors here who wouldn\'92t allow that to happen than you have army or navy to get it done.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You don\'92t know\'97\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Cholik interrupted, causing the stone snake\'92s head to rear up above the lord. \'93You don\'92t know what you\'92re dealing with.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The snake opened its fanged jaws and spewed fire against the stone floor in front of the guards and drove them back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You need me,\'94 Cholik told Lord Darkulan. \'93And you need the salvation that Dien-Ap-Sten can offer. If your mistress is saved, your wife will be saved. If both women are saved, your power will be saved.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Letting you stay here was a mistake,\'94 Lord Darkulan said. \'93I should have had you banished from the city.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93After the first night of miracles here,\'94 Cholik said, \'93you wouldn\'92t have been able to do that. Dien-Ap-Sten and the Way of Dreams bring power to people. Wealth and privilege. Both are for the taking. Health for the sick and infirm and dying.\'94 He silently commanded the snake\'92s head to the ground where it lay prone.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan stepped backward, but the flame still{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint249}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint249}roiled where it had struck the stone floor. He was separated from his men, but Cholik was also grimly aware that some of the guards had bows, and even knives could be thrown that distance.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You did the only thing you could in coming here tonight,\'94 Cholik said. He walked down the platform circling the stone snake\'92s neck.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The snake lay quiet and still, but the fiery eyes darted and watched. Its tongue, smoldering and steaming, flicked out rapidly, scenting the air. Deep orange embers swirled through the still air inside the dark cathedral, turning to black ash shortly before reaching the ceiling. Waves of heat rolled off the stone snake.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik stopped in front of the snake, knowing the animated creature outlined him, making him seem like a dark shadow in front of a dreadful beast.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Perhaps you think you have sealed your doom by coming here tonight, Lord Darkulan,\'94 Cholik said softly.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The lord said nothing. Fear etched deep shadows into his face despite the light given off by his lantern and the snake.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I assure you,\'94 Cholik said, \'93that the opposite is true: you have sealed your future.\'94 He gestured at the snake, feeling the furnace blast of heat as the creature opened its jaws. \'93Walk with me, Lord Darkulan. Give your worries and fears over to Dien-Ap-Sten that he may make them go away.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan stood his ground.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You were here today,\'94 Cholik said. \'93You witnessed the miracle that Dien-Ap-Sten performed on the Black Road by separating the two boys locked in each other\'92s flesh. Have you ever seen such a thing done before?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 the lord replied in a quaking voice.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Have you even heard of such a thing?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Never.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93With Dien-Ap-Sten at his side,\'94 Cholik promised, \'93a man who ventures down the Way of Dreams may do anything.\'94 He held out his hand. \'93Come with me that I may show you even more miracles.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint250}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint250}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Hesitation showed on Lord Darkulan\'92s face.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93By morning,\'94 Cholik said, \'93it will be too late. The poison will have claimed the life of your mistress. Her father will demand the life of your wife in return.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How am I supposed to save them by going with you?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93On the Way of Dreams,\'94 Cholik said, \'93all things are made possible. Come.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Trying not to show his fear, Lord Darkulan stepped forward and allowed Cholik to take his arm and guide him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Be brave, Lord Darkulan,\'94 Cholik advised. \'93You are going to see wonders seldom seen by human eyes. Step into the snake\'92s mouth, and all your fear will be taken from you if you but believe.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan followed a half-step behind Cholik. They stepped over the stone snake\'92s sharp teeth and followed the black, smoldering ribbon of tongue down into the snake\'92s throat, where it became a black road that wound down into a long hallway.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Where are we?\'94 Lord Darkulan asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93On the Way of Dreams,\'94 Cholik replied. \'93We\'92re going to find your destiny. It takes a strong man to follow the teachings of Dien-Ap-Sten. You will become an even stronger man.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The hallway widened and changed a number of times, but the Black Road remained constant beneath Cholik\'92s feet. He\'92d talked to several parishioners who had ventured along the Black Road to be healed or receive a blessing, and all of them had described the path differently. Some had said they\'92d journeyed down familiar hallways, while others were taken through places they\'92d never seen and hoped they would never see.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A green sun dawned in the hallway before them, and suddenly they were no longer in a hallway. Now the Black Road clung to a cliffside. The path they followed was so high that clouds obscured the view below. Still, the harsh mountain range towered above. Ice glinted on the peaks only a little farther up.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan stopped. \'93I want to go back.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint251}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint251}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You can\'92t,\'94 Cholik replied. \'93Look.\'94 He turned and pointed back along the way they had come.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Flames clung to the Black Road, twisting and curling three times the height of a man.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The only way open to you is forward,\'94 Cholik said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ve made a mistake,\'94 Lord Darkulan announced.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93This was not the first,\'94 Cholik replied.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Spinning abruptly, Lord Darkulan raised his sword, bringing it to within inches of Cholik\'92s unprotected throat. \'93You will let me out of here now, or I\'92ll have your head from your shoulders!\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Secure in the knowledge that Kabraxis watched over him, Cholik grasped the sword. The sharp edges cut into the flesh of his hand. Blood trickled down the blade and dripped to the Black Road, giving birth to fist-sized fires at their feet.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Cholik said, \'93you won\'92t.\'94 Power coursed through him, turning the sword red-hot in a heartbeat.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Screaming in pain, Lord Darkulan released his weapon and stumbled back. He held his burned hand in disbelief.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik ignored the sizzling pain of his own burning hand, ignored the stink of scorched flesh and the smoke that curled up. Much worse things had happened to him during the trips down the Black Road that Kabraxis had led him on. He could still occasionally feel the demon\'92s talons rooting around inside his brain, scraping against his skull.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Swiveling, Cholik flung the lord\'92s sword over the cliff\'92s edge. He held out his burned and bleeding hand for inspection.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92re insane,\'94 Lord Darkulan said in disbelief.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Cholik stated calmly. \'93I believe in Dien-Ap-Sten and the power of the Way of Dreams.\'94 He held his hand up. Even as he watched, the cuts knitted together, and the burns healed and went away. In less than a moment, his hand was completely healed. \'93You can believe, too. Hold out your hand, and accept what I am telling you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Trembling, afraid, and hurting, Lord Darkulan held his hand up.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint252}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint252}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Believe,\'94 Cholik said softly. \'93Believe, and you will be given the power to heal yourself and end your misery.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan concentrated. Sweat popped out on his brow. \'93I can\'92t,\'94 he whispered hoarsely. \'93Please, I beg you. Make the pain go away.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I can\'92t,\'94 Cholik said. \'93That is for you to do. Just come to Dien-Ap-Sten willingly. Only a little faith is needed. Trust that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Slowly, then, Lord Darkulan\'92s hand began to heal. The burns scabbed over, and only a moment or two after that, smooth flesh remained where the horrible burns had been.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ve done it.\'94 Lord Darkulan gazed at his uninjured hand in disbelief. His fingers still trembled.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Cholik said. \'93But the worst is yet to come.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Without warning, the ledge broke away, dropping them into the abyss over the clouds.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan screamed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik controlled his own fear. He was on the Black Road now. The warriors and priests who had become part of his inner circle had all experienced much worse than this. All of those men who had reached this point had to relive a horrific nightmare that was their deepest secret.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The bottom of the long fall through the cottony clouds wasn\'92t the bone-breaking stop against jagged rocks that Cholik had expected. Instead, he landed light as a feather in the midst of a moon-dappled bog under a clear night sky.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan plummeted into the bog, disappearing with a huge splash that threw black mud in all directions.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik grew worried after a time that something had gone wrong. Initiates had died along the way of the Black Road, but generally Kabraxis was selective about who was brought into the inner circle.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He\'92s fine,\'94 the demon said. \'93Give him a moment more. I found this place and this event in a tight secret place that he seldom goes to these days. Pay attention.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik waited, amazed that he could stand on the bog\'92s surface tension.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint253}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint253}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Then Lord Darkulan shoved an arm up through the bog, clapped it onto a semi-submerged tree trunk that had fallen a long time ago. Mud covered his head and face, stripping away the regal look and leaving only the frightened man behind.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan reached toward Cholik. \'93Help me! Hurry!\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What is he afraid of?\'94 Cholik asked Kabraxis. Neither of them made a move toward the struggling lord. \'93The bog is not so deep that he will drown.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He fears the past,\'94 the demon said. \'93And he should.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Fearfully, Lord Darkulan gazed over his shoulder at the swamp. Naked and dead trees stood out from the loose mud. Dead brush with ashy, curling leaving lined the shore. Skeletons of small creatures, some of them recently dead so that patches of fur clung to them, lay partially submerged in the swamp and on the shore. Dead birds clung upside down by their claws from naked tree branches. Frog corpses floated in the bog.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan screamed, then was pulled under the bog by something strong and fierce. Bubbles erupted from the mud.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Is he going to die here?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He will,\'94 Kabraxis answered, \'93if I don\'92t save him. He can\'92t fight this nightmare. It\'92s too strong for him.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The man\'92s arm shot out of the bog again, found the tree trunk, and succeeded in pulling himself out of the muck. When he appeared, a skeleton clung to his back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Years of submersion in the bog had turned the dead woman\'92s skin to leather, and it sank in tightly to her skull. Once, Cholik knew, she might have been pretty, but there was no way to know that now. The soft blue dress that might once have hidden womanly curves now clung to the emaciated form of the horror that rode Lord Darkulan\'92s back. The dead woman bent close to him, teeth showing through her ruined flesh. She licked out a dead, leathery tongue that caught his ear, then drew it back between her broken teeth. When she bit down, crushing the earlobe like a grape, crimson sprayed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint254}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint254}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan screamed in pain and flailed, trying desperately to shove the dead woman from him and haul himself onto the tree trunk.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Help me!\'94 the lord called out.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Who is the woman?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Once,\'94 Kabraxis said, \'93she was his lover. It was during the early years before his marriage. She was a common girl named Azyka, a shopkeeper\'92s daughter. Before the marriage, she told Lord Darkulan she was going to have his child. Knowing he couldn\'92t allow that, Lord Darkulan killed her and left her body in this bog outside Bramwell.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The girl was never found?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik watched the horrified lord fighting to maintain his grip on the moss-encrusted tree trunk. The dead woman\'92s weight steadily bore him under. Cholik was not amazed by Kabraxis\'92s story. As a priest of the Zakarum Church, he was no stranger to the special privileges invoked by royalty. In Westmarch\'92s history, several murders had been forgotten about and the murderers absolved by special dispensation from the church.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Help me!\'94 Lord Darkulan screamed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Kabraxis strode forward. His large feet left only small ripples on the bog water and never once became wet. \'93Lord Darkulan,\'94 the demon called.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The lord glanced up, seeing the demon for the first time. For a moment, Lord Darkulan froze, but the dead woman chewing his ear into ragged, bloody bits caught his attention again. He fought against her, losing his grip on the tree trunk and plunging into the bog up to his chin. The dead woman\'92s hair floated on the bog water.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Lord Darkulan,\'94 the demon said. \'93I am Dien-Ap-Sten. I am your salvation.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92re no salvation,\'94 Lord Darkulan cried. \'93You\'92re a demon.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And you\'92re a drowning man,\'94 Kabraxis stated. \'93Accept me or die.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92ll not be tricked by one of your illusions\'97\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint255}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint255}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The dead woman reached up behind Lord Darkulan and knotted her skeletal fingers in his hair. When she yanked, Lord Darkulan vanished beneath the black muck of the bog.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Kabraxis stood patiently waiting.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  For a moment, Cholik believed it was done and that the lord had died in the bog with the specter of the girl he had murdered so long ago. The chill of the swamp blew through Cholik, and he wrapped his arms around himself. As many times as he had ventured down the Black Road, he had never gotten used to the experience. Each time was unique, each fear different.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan\'92s hand broke the surface, and Kabraxis\'92s hand was there to catch it. Effortlessly, the demon hauled the lord from the muck and the mire with the dead woman still riding him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Live or die,\'94 Kabraxis offered calmly. \'93The choice is yours.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan hesitated only a moment. \'93Live. May the Light forgive me, I want to live.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A cruel smile carved Kabraxis\'92s horrendous face. \'93\plain \f2\i\fs24 I\plain \f2\fs24 forgive you,\'94 the demon mocked. He continued pulling the muddy, bloody lord from the swamp. The dead woman still clung to Lord Darkulan\'92s back, biting his mangled ear and scratching his face with the claws of her free hand.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Kabraxis backhanded the dead woman from Lord Darkulan\'92s back. When he finished hauling the man up, Cholik found that they all once more stood on the solid ground of the Black Road twisting through the high mountains. The swamp was nowhere to be seen.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan gave in to his fear, shaking and shivering before the demon\'92s wrath. \'93Don\'92t kill me,\'94 the lord pleaded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I won\'92t kill you,\'94 Kabraxis said, pushing the man to his knees before him, humbling him. \'93I am going to give you your life.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Shuddering, Lord Darkulan stayed still before the demon.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You are weak.\'94 Kabraxis spoke in deep tones. \'93I will be{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint256}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint256}your strength.\'94 The demon wrapped one of his large hands around Lord Darkulan\'92s head. \'93You are unguided. I will be your design.\'94 The fingers elongated into sharp spikes. \'93By your own hand and childish desires of flesh, you are unmade. I will make you a man and a leader of men.\'94 With a quick snap of his wrist, the demon drove his spiked fingers through Lord Darkulan\'92s skull. Blood leaked down his face, threading through the mud that clung to his features. \'93Mind, body, and soul, you are\plain \f2\i\fs24 mine!\plain \f2\fs24 \'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lightning flashed through the dark sky above the mountains, followed immediately by the rumbling roar of thunder that shattered all other sounds. The Black Road trembled beneath Cholik\'92s feet, and for a dreadful moment he thought the whole mountain range was going to fall.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Then the lightning and the thunder faded, and Kabraxis withdrew his spiked fingers from Lord Darkulan\'92s skull.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Rise,\'94 the demon ordered, \'93and begin the new life that I have given you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan rose, and as he did the mud and fatigue and blood vanished from him. He stood straight and tall, clear-eyed and calm. \'93I hear and obey.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Only one thing yet remains,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93You must bear my mark that I may keep watch over you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Without hesitation, Lord Darkulan stripped away his tunic, chainmail shirt, and blouse beneath to bare his chest. \'93Here,\'94 he offered. \'93Over my heart that I may keep you close to me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Kabraxis placed his palm over Lord Darkulan\'92s chest. When he removed his hand, the tattoo that was the demon\'92s mark marred the lord\'92s flesh.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You are in my service,\'94 the demon said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Till the end of my days,\'94 Lord Darkulan said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Go then, Lord Darkulan, and know that you have the power to heal your mistress and prevent your wife\'92s hanging. Draw a bit of your blood, mix it in wine, and have her drink it to cure her.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Lord Darkulan agreed and offered his undying loyalty to the demon once more, then followed the Black Road{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint257}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint257}back out of the stone snake\'92s mouth. At the other end of the Black Road, Cholik once more saw the interior of the great cathedral.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93So now you have him,\'94 Cholik said, watching as Lord Darkulan rejoined his guards.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We have him,\'94 Kabraxis agreed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Surprised that the demon didn\'92t sound more satisfied, Cholik looked at him. \'93Is something wrong?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93There is a man I have learned of,\'94 the demon said. \'93Taramis Volken. He\'92s a demon hunter, and he has picked up my trail.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It doesn\'92t matter. After tonight, he will no longer be a concern to me. But after the burned man attempted to kill you today, which I did not see coming, I think you should tighten security around the church.\'94 Kabraxis paused. \'93Lord Darkulan should be more than willing to aid you with that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93There\'92s no way to tighten security completely in the church,\'94 Cholik objected. \'93We admit too many people, and many of them we can\'92t identify, to screen everyone.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Do it better,\'94 Kabraxis snapped.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Of course,\'94 Cholik said, bowing his head and watching as the demon vanished from sight. Cholik\'92s thoughts rushed, scrambling over one another in his head. Who was this demon hunter Kabraxis feared? In their year and more together, Cholik had never seen the demon concerned about anything. The matter was puzzling and more than a little unsettling, even after Kabraxis\'92s assurances that the matter was taken care of.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  And how was it that Kabraxis had taken care of the man who hunted him?
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint258}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint258}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  NINETEEN
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Although he\'92d ridden horses a few times while working with overland trade caravans, Darrick had never grown used to their lurching gait. Even a ship\'92s deck riding the crests of a storm-tossed sea felt more certain than the beast beneath him as it picked its way down the forested hillside.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Luckily, the animal followed Taramis Volken\'92s mount along the narrow trail and required no real guidance from him. He only wished he could sleep in the saddle as some of the other men accompanying them seemed able to do.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Last night at the Blue Lantern tavern, Darrick would not have guessed that Taramis headed the small army of men encamped outside Seeker\'92s Point. But after witnessing their professionalism and dedication to their quest, he understood how they could have escaped notice.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  All of the warriors rode in single file along the trail. Two riderless horses testified to the fact that scouts ranged on foot ahead of the group. The men rode with hardly any noise, their gear carefully padded so that nothing clinked or clanked. They were hard-eyed men, like wolves that hunted in a pack. The wintry wind and the leaden, overcast sky of morning further brought that appearance out.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick straightened in the saddle, trying to find a comfortable position. Since leaving the Blue Lantern last evening, he\'92d ridden all night. A few times he\'92d dozed in the saddle, exhaustion finally overcoming his fear of falling off the horse, but that had been reawakened after only a moment or two when he woke and found himself sliding.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint259}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint259}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A birdcall sounded in the quiet of the forest.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick\'92s sharp ears picked the sound out, recognizing that it was false only because he\'92d heard the same cry earlier. The call came from one of the two scouts ahead. During the night, they\'92d used owl calls to communicate, but this morning they emulated a small ruby-throated wren that sailors sometimes took on board sailing ships to raise.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  One of the scouts stepped from the forest and loped alongside Taramis Volken\'92s mount, matching the long-limbed animal with ease. The scout and the sage talked briefly, then the scout disappeared again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis appeared unconcerned, so Darrick tried to relax. His muscles were stiff and sore from hauling cargo the day before and the long ride during the night. More than anything, he wanted off the horse, and he wished he\'92d stayed in Seeker\'92s Point. He had no business among these men. They all seemed to be veteran warriors, and the few words that Darrick had overheard them say alluded to past battles with demons, though none of them was as powerful as Kabraxis.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick pushed his breath out, watching it fog briefly in the chill of morning. He couldn\'92t imagine why Taramis had asked him to come along when there were already so many warriors.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A little farther on, the trail they followed led out into a cleared space. Among a littering of tree stumps sat a small house with a thatched roof. The land to the south of the house had been cleared for gardening. The current crop appeared to be onions and carrots, but there were stands where vine crops had grown during the summer. In back of the garden was a door set into a small hill that Darrick believed would lead to a root cellar. A well occupied the space between the garden and the small barn.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  An old man and a young boy came out of the barn. They looked enough alike that Darrick believed they were family, probably grandfather and grandson.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The old man carried a pitchfork and a milking pail. He{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint260}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint260}handed the pail to the boy and waved him back into the barn. The old man was bald and had a long gray beard. He wore deerskin outer garments, but the neck of a purple blouse showed under the jacket.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93May the Light bless you,\'94 the old man said, holding the pitchfork in both hands. A little fear showed in his eyes, but the confident manner in which he wielded the pitchfork told Darrick that the old man was prepared for trouble.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And may the Light bless you,\'94 Taramis said, reining his horse in at a respectful distance from the old man. \'93My name is Taramis Volken, and if I got your directions right, you\'92d be Ellig Barrows.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 the old man said, keeping his stance open. His bright blue eyes roved over the warriors and Darrick. \'93And if you\'92re who you says you are, I\'92ve heard of you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I am,\'94 Taramis said, swinging down from his horse with easy grace. \'93I\'92ve got papers that prove it right enough.\'94 He reached inside his blouse. \'93They bear the king\'92s mark.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The old man held up a hand. A light sapphire glow enveloped Taramis. For a moment a ruby glow surrounded the sage and kept the sapphire glow from him. Then the ruby light faded and vanished entirely.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Sorry,\'94 Taramis apologized. \'93Wooten told me you\'92d be a cautious man.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92re no demon,\'94 Ellig Barrows said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Taramis agreed. \'93May the Light blind them and bind them and burn them forever.\'94 He spat.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I bid you welcome to my home,\'94 Ellig said. \'93If you and your men have not eaten, I\'92ll have a simple breakfast out soon enough if you\'92ll have it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We wouldn\'92t want to impose,\'94 Taramis said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It\'92s not imposition,\'94 the old man assured him. \'93As you can tell from the trail you followed up, we seldom have company here.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I need you to know something further,\'94 Taramis said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Ellig regarded him. \'93You\'92ve come for the sword. I knew{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint261}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint261}that from the reading I took of you. Come on inside the house, and we\'92ll talk. Then we\'92ll see if you get it or not.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis waved to his men to dismount, and Darrick dismounted with them. The wind whistled through the trees overhead.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik found Kabraxis in one of the rooftop gardens. The demon faced north, his arms folded over his broad chest. The illusion spell he maintained over the garden prevented anyone in the street below from seeing him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Pausing, Cholik peered over the roof\'92s side, spotting the steady stream of worshippers pouring into the building.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You sent for me?\'94 Cholik asked, coming to a halt behind the demon. Kabraxis had, of course, because Cholik wouldn\'92t have heard the demon\'92s voice in his head while he was preparing for the morning service otherwise.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93In dealing with the man I\'92d learned of, I found out something else interesting.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Taramis Volken?\'94 Cholik asked. He remembered the demon hunter\'92s name from the previous night\'92s conversation.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes. But there is another man that I recognize with Taramis Volken\'92s group. I wanted you to look at him as well.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Of course.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Kabraxis turned and crossed the rooftop to one of the small pools in the garden. Passing a hand over the pool, the demon stepped back. \'93Look.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Moving forward, Cholik knelt and gazed into the pool. Ripples passed over the water\'92s surface, then settled out again. For a moment, Cholik only saw the reflected blue of the sky.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Then the image formed, showing a small house tucked away under the embrace of tall fir, maple, and oak trees. Warriors sat outside the small house, all of them rough-looking and hard traveled. Cholik knew at once that there were too many of them to live at the house. They were visitors, then, but he didn\'92t recognize the house.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint262}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint262}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Do you see him?\'94 Kabraxis demanded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I see many men,\'94 Cholik replied.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Here.\'94 Kabraxis gestured impatiently.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The pool rippled and clouded for a moment, then cleared once more and focused on a wan young man with reddish hair pulled back into a queue. Seated at the base of a big oak tree, a cutlass across his knees, the young man appeared to sleep with his back to the tree. A ragged scar marred one of his eyebrows.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Do you recognize him?\'94 Kabraxis asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Cholik replied, recognizing the man now. \'93He was at Tauruk\'92s Port.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And now he is with Taramis Volken,\'94 Kabraxis mused.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93They know each other?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Not that I was aware of. For all I know, Taramis Volken and this man, Darrick Lang, met each other in Seeker\'92s Point last evening.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You have spies watching the demon hunter?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93When I am not watching the man myself, of course. Taramis Volken is a dangerous human, and the quest he\'92s on pertains to us. If he is given what he seeks at this farmer\'92s house, his next move will be to come for us.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What is it he seeks?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Stormfury,\'94 Kabraxis replied.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The mystic sword that turned the barbarian horde hundreds of years ago?\'94 Cholik asked. His nimble mind searched for the reasons Kabraxis would be interested in the sword and why he would think that the demon hunter would turn his sights on them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The same.\'94 A grimace twisted the demon\'92s hideous face.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik thought then that Kabraxis was afraid of the sword and what it might do, but he also knew he dared not mention that. Desperately, he tried to eradicate the errant thought from his mind before the demon sensed it.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The sword can be a problem,\'94 Kabraxis said, \'93but I have minions that are even now closing in on Taramis{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint263}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint263}Volken and his band. They won\'92t escape, and if the sword is there, my minions will retrieve it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik thought and worked to couch his words carefully. \'93How is the sword a problem?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It is a powerful weapon,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93A blacksmith imbued with the power of the Light forged the sword hundreds of years ago to use against the barbarian horde and the dark force they worshipped.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Understanding dawned in Cholik. \'93They worshipped you. You were Iceclaw.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes. And the humans used the sword to drive me from this world then.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Can it be used against you again?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I am more powerful now than I was then,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93Still, I will see to it that the sword is destroyed forever and always after this day.\'94 The demon paused. \'93But the presence of this other man troubles me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I have cast auguries to show the portents of the things we have done concerning Lord Darkulan,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93This man keeps turning up in them.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik considered that. Spies he had placed inside the lord\'92s keep had relayed that Darkulan\'92s mistress was already better and on her way back to a full recovery. Lord Darkulan had visited her immediately after leaving the church last evening.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93When did you see this man again after Tauruk\'92s Port?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Only moments ago,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93When I summoned the lezanti and set them upon the hunt for Taramis Volken and his warriors. I had to scry upon the group to set the lezanti upon the scent.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A shudder passed through Cholik when he considered the lezanti. He\'92d always believed the creatures to be truly the stuff of legends and myth.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  According to the tales he\'92d been told, the lezanti were created by the blending of a human female\'92s corpse, a freshly slain wolf, and a lizard, creating a fast and ferocious{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint264}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint264}chimera that possessed super-animal cunning, a partially upright physique, and an ability to take a lot of damage and grow limb replacements after amputation.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If you\'92ve only just now seen this man,\'94 Cholik said, \'93how do you know he was the one you saw in your auguries?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Do you distrust my abilities, Buyard Cholik?\'94 the demon demanded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Cholik replied quickly, not wanting Kabraxis to vent the cold rage that filled him. \'93I just wondered how you kept him separate from Taramis Volken or another of the warriors with him.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because I can,\'94 the demon replied. \'93Just as I robbed time of your years and returned your youth to you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik stared into the pool, looking into the young man\'92s relaxed face. He wondered how the young man had gotten there, more than a year after the events at Tauruk\'92s Port.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I am concerned because of the magic that was used to open the gateway,\'94 Kabraxis said. \'93When demons come from the Burning Hells, so, too, come the seeds of their potential downfall. It is a balance that is kept between the Light and the Darkness. But by the same hand, no champion of the Light may burst forth without a weakness that can be exploited. It\'92s up to the champion which propensity\'97strength or weakness\'97wins out. And it is up to the demon whether he stands against the power that would banish him from this plane again.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And you think such power has been assigned to this man because he was there the night you came through the gateway back into our world?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No. This man doesn\'92t have such power. And there is a great affinity for darkness in his soul.\'94 The demon smiled. \'93In fact, were we able to get him here and persuade him properly, I think he could be turned to serve me. There is weakness in him as well as strength. I feel it would be no problem to exploit that weakness.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then why the concern?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The juxtaposition of all the variables,\'94 Kabraxis said.{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint265}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint265}\'93Taramis Volken\'92s discovery of Stormfury is bad enough, but for this man to appear here so soon after the burned man attempted to kill you, I have to consider how threatening our situation can get. The balance between Light and Dark has always been maintained, and somewhere out there is a threat I have to recognize.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Staring into the pool of water as the view shifted and pulled back, Cholik watched the sleek forms of the lezanti cluster along the ridgeline around the small house. The lezanti stood hunchbacked and broad-shouldered on two clawed feet and legs that bent backward like a horse\'92s rear legs. Lizard\'92s skin hugged the body and shifted colors as quickly as a chameleon\'92s, allowing them to blend into their surroundings with astonishing ease. Tufts of fur spread over their shoulders, crowned their heads around their small triangular ears, and covered their flanks where a hairless lizard\'92s tail flicked and twisted. Their jaws were filled with large fangs.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The church bells rang, signaling the beginning of the morning service.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik stood, waiting for the order to dismiss and return to the church. \'93This situation is under your control,\'94 he said. \'93The lezanti will leave no one alive.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Perhaps,\'94 Kabraxis said. He gestured toward the pool.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  In the image trapped in the water, the lezanti began stealthily closing in on the warriors and the little house in the forest. Hypnotized, remembering the violence the demon-formed creatures were reputed to be capable of, Cholik watched while the cathedral below them continued to fill.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick sat under the spreading oak tree a short distance from the house and held the deep wooden plate he\'92d been given in his hands. He wished the house had been bigger or that there had been fewer men. The dark chimney smoke pouring into the air let him know there was a fire inside. He wasn\'92t truly cold, but a chance to sit by the fire for a few moments to break the chill that covered him would have been welcome.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint266}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint266}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The generosity Ellig Barrows showed his unexpected guests was amazing. It was one thing for the old man to have been willing to care for such a large group, but it was even more surprising that he was able to. Breakfast consisted of simple fare: eggs, stringy venison chops, potato mush, thick brown gravy, and fat wedges of bread. But it was all warm and welcome.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  As it turned out, both of Taramis\'92s scouts had taken deer in the forest and dressed them out to replace the meat they ate from the old man\'92s larder. There was no replacing the bread, though, and Darrick guessed that the old man\'92s wife would be busy for several days baking to replace what they\'92d consumed that morning.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick sopped up the last of the gravy and eggs with his remaining piece of bread and drank from his waterskin. Setting the plate to one side for the moment, he enjoyed the sensation of being full and off the horse. He pulled a blanket from his pack and wrapped it around his shoulders.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Winter was coming, marching down from the harsh northlands. Soon enough, mornings would be filled with frost and cold that made a man\'92s bones ache. Darrick kept to himself, watching the other warriors break up into small groups and talk among themselves. As they ate, the warriors also relieved the guards posted in the forest, making sure everyone was fed and rested.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Ellig Barrows and Taramis Volken talked on the covered porch in front of the house. Each man seemed intent on taking the measure of the other. Taramis wore orange-colored robes with silver designs worked into them. During his travels, Darrick had heard descriptions of the Vizjerei robes, but he had never seen them before. The enchanted robes offered protection from spells and demonic creatures.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick knew that Taramis sought to persuade the old man to give him Stormfury, the sword from the old legend. Although he\'92d seen a number of things in his life as a sailor for Westmarch even before he\'92d seen the demon at Tauruk\'92s Port, Darrick had never seen anything as legendary as the{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint267}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint267}sword. His mind played with the idea of it, what it might look like and what powers it might hold. But again and again, his thoughts insisted on coming back to why Taramis would believe he belonged with them on this quest.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Darrick,\'94 Taramis called a few minutes later.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Rousing from near slumber, regretting the need to move when he\'92d finally gotten comfortable against the tree, Darrick glanced at the sage.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Come with us,\'94 Taramis requested, standing and following the old man across the yard.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Reluctantly, Darrick got to his feet and carried the plate to the porch, where it was taken by the old man\'92s grandson. Darrick followed Taramis and Ellig Barrows into the root cellar built into the hillside.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The old man took a lantern from the root cellar\'92s wall inside, lit it with a coal he\'92d carried from the house, and followed the short flight of earthen stairs down into the small root cellar.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick hesitated in the doorway. The cloying smell of dank earth, potatoes, onions, and spices filled his nostrils. He didn\'92t like the darkness of the cellar or the closed-in feeling he got from the racks of foods canned in jars or the wine bottles. For a house in the middle of nowhere along the Frozen Sea coast, Ellig Barrows and his family had a large larder.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Come on,\'94 Taramis said, following the old man to the back of the cellar.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick crossed the uneven floor dug from the earth and covered with small rock. The cellar\'92s ceiling was so low his head scraped a couple of times, and he kept hunkered down.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A huge stone surface blocked the other end of the cellar. The lantern Ellig Barrows carried clanked against the stone as he stood next to it.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I was given care of the sword,\'94 the old man said, turning to face Taramis, \'93along with the power to do so by my grandfather, as he was given the power to care for it by his grandfather. I teach this responsibility and power to my own{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint268}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint268}grandson now. For hundreds of years, Stormfury has been in the possession of my family, awaiting the time when the demon would rise again and it would be needed.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The sword has been needed before now,\'94 Taramis said gravely. \'93But Kabraxis is a cunning demon and doesn\'92t ever use the same name twice. If it were not for Darrick\'92s encounter with the demon in Tauruk\'92s Port more than a year ago, we would not know which one we faced now.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Iceclaw was a fierce and evil beast,\'94 the old man said. \'93The old stories tell of all the murder and carnage he wrought while he was in our world.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93There were two other times Kabraxis was in the world,\'94 Taramis said. \'93Both times before, Diablo and his brothers sought him out and returned him to the Burning Hells. Only the sword now offers a chance against the demon.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You know why the sword has never been taken from my family before,\'94 Ellig Barrows said. The lantern light deepened the hollows of his eye sockets, making him look like a man days dead.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick shivered at the thought.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The sword has never allowed itself to be taken,\'94 Taramis said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Two kings have died trying to take this sword,\'94 the old man said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick hadn\'92t known that. He glanced at Taramis, studying the sage\'92s appearance in the lantern\'92s pale yellow glow.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93They died,\'94 the sage said, \'93because they didn\'92t understand the sword\'92s true nature.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93So you say,\'94 Ellig Barrows replied. \'93There are mysteries about the sword that I don\'92t know. That my grandfather before me didn\'92t know, and his grandfather before him. Yet you come to my house and tell me you know more than all of them.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Show me the sword,\'94 Taramis said, \'93and you can see for yourself.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We have been responsible for the sword for so long. It has not been an easy burden to bear.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint269}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint269}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It shouldn\'92t have been,\'94 Taramis agreed. He faced the old man. \'93Please.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Sighing, the old man turned to the wall. \'93You take your own lives in your hands,\'94 he warned. His fingers inscribed arcane symbols in the air. As soon as each one was completed, it glowed briefly, then sank into the wall.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick glanced at Taramis, wanting to ask why he instead of one of the other warriors had been brought on this part of their search. Even as he started to open his mouth, the root cellar wall shimmered and turned opaque.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Ellig Barrows raised the lantern, and the light shone into the room on the other side of the opaque stone wall. Eldritch energy sparkled inside the wall, illuminated by the lantern light.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Beyond the wall, wreathed in the shadows of the hidden room, a dead man lay in a niche cut into the hillside. His snow-white beard trailed down to his chest, and he wore animal hides over crude chainmail. A visored helm hid part of the shrunken features that bound the dead man\'92s head. His arms crossed over his chest, and his withered hands\'97the yellow ivory of his knuckles showing through\'97gripped the hilt of a long sword.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint270}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint270}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  TWENTY
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 In the hidden room in Ellig Barrows\'92s root cellar, Darrick studied the sword Taramis Volken had come all this way to get and found the weapon was in no way like anything he\'92d imagined since the sage had told him of it. The sword appeared plain and unadorned, hammered from steel with a craftsman\'92s skill but lacking the touch of an artist. The blade was an infantryman\'92s weapon, not something that would invoke fear in demons.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \'93You\'92re disappointed?\'94 Ellig Barrows asked, looking at Darrick.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick hesitated, not wanting to offend. \'93I had just expected something more.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93A jeweled weapon, perhaps?\'94 the old man asked. \'93Something every bandit you met would want and try to steal? A weapon so unique and striking-looking that everyone would mark its passage and know it for what it was?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I hadn\'92t thought of it like that,\'94 Darrick admitted. But he also wondered if someone had stolen the real sword a long time ago and left the barbaric piece in its stead. He immediately felt guilty for that, because it would have meant the old man\'92s life had been spent doing useless guard duty.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Ellig Barrows stepped through the opaque wall. \'93The smith who forged this weapon did think of those things. Perhaps Stormfury isn\'92t an elegant weapon, but you\'92ll never find a truer one. Of course, you\'92ll only know that if you\'92re able to take it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis followed the old man through the wall.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  After a moment, Darrick stepped through the mystical wall as well. A cold sensation gripped him as he passed{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint271}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint271}through, and it felt as if he were walking through the thickest forest growth, having to fight his way through.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The sword is protected from interlopers,\'94 Ellig Barrows said. \'93No man may touch it or take it if Kabraxis is not within this world.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And if any try?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The sword can\'92t be taken,\'94 the old man said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What of the kings who died?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93One slew members of my family,\'94 Ellig Barrows said. \'93He and all his warriors died less than a day later. The Light is not evil as the demons are, but it is vengeful against those who transgress against it. Another tried to drag Hauklin\'92s body from its resting place. He rose that time and slew them all.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Standing in the crypt carved from the root cellar, Darrick felt afraid. Although the caverns under Tauruk\'92s Port were larger and the huge doorway had seemed more threatening, the dead man lying with the sword clasped in his hands seemed just as deadly. Darrick would have gladly left the crypt and been satisfied never to see anything more of a magical nature.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He glanced at Taramis. \'93Why did you want me here?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because you are tied to this,\'94 the sage said. \'93You have been since you witnessed Kabraxis\'92s arrival on this plane.\'94 He looked at the dead man. \'93I think that you are the one who can take Hauklin\'92s sword to use against the demon.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why not you?\'94 Darrick demanded. For a moment he wondered if the sage was only using him, willing to risk his life in the effort to recover the sword.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis turned and reached for the sword. His hand halted, quivering, in the air several inches from the weapon. The effort he made to reach the weapon corded muscle along his arm. Pain showed on his features. Finally, in disappointed disgust, he drew his arm back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I can\'92t take it,\'94 the sage said. \'93I am not the one.\'94 He turned to Darrick. \'93But I believe that you are.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because the Light and the Darkness balance each other,\'94{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint272}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint272}Taramis said. \'93Any time power is passed into this world from the Light or the Darkness, a balance must be made. Demons come into this world, and a means of defeating them is also created. If the Light tries to upset the balance by introducing an object of power that can be used against the Darkness, the powers of Darkness intercede to make the balance whole again. Ultimately, the true threat to the balance, whether the Light or the Darkness has the greater power in our world, is left up to us. The people. Just as when the Prime Evils appeared in this world during the time that came to be known as the Dark Exile, the Angel Tyreal gathered the magi, warriors, and scholars in the East and formed the Brotherhood of the Horadrim. Those people would never have come together with such power if the demons had not been loosed in our world. If Tyreal had tried to do this before the Prime Evils had arrived here, Darkness would have found a means to strike a balance.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93That doesn\'92t explain why you think I can pick up that sword,\'94 Darrick said. He made no move to try.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I heard the stories about you when I arrived in Westmarch,\'94 Taramis said. \'93And I began looking for you. But by the time I\'92d arrived, you\'92d vanished. I caught up with your ship, but no one knew where you were. I couldn\'92t tell many that I was searching for you, because that might have alerted Kabraxis\'92s minions, and your life could have become forfeit.\'94 He paused, locking his gaze with Darrick\'92s. \'93As for the sword, perhaps I\'92m wrong. If I am, it will prevent you from taking it. You have nothing to lose.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick glanced at Ellig Barrows.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Over the years before the sword was hidden away,\'94 the old man said, \'93many tried to take it just as Taramis has. If there was no true evil in their hearts, they were only prevented from removing the sword.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick looked at the corpse and the plain sword it held. \'93Has Hauklin\'92s sword ever been taken?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Never,\'94 Ellig Barrows said. \'93Not once from his hand. Not even I can remove it. I have only been made their protector. As my grandson shall be after me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint273}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint273}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Try,\'94 Taramis urged. \'93If you can\'92t take up the sword, then I\'92ve come on a fool\'92s quest and uncovered secrets best left hidden.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes,\'94 Ellig Barrows said. \'93No one has ever come for the sword in my lifetime. I had begun to think the world had forgotten about it. Or that the demon Kabraxis had been permanently banished from this world.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis put his hand on Darrick\'92s shoulder. \'93But the demon is back,\'94 the sage said. \'93We know that, don\'92t we? The demon is back, and the sword should come free.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But am I the one?\'94 Darrick asked in a hoarse voice.
