\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick whispered, \'93Mat.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  There was no answer, only the whistling sound of the normal breeze moving through the rigging.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The whale-oil freighter bucked again, sliding four or five feet backward and almost coming free of the rocks.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We\'92re losing the ship,\'94 Taramis said. \'93Move! Now!\'94 He stepped over the railing and threw himself at the riverbank, leading the way.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Go!\plain \f2\fs24 Mat whispered in Darrick\'92s mind, sounding farther away than ever.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Trapped, wanting to know more about how Mat was able to talk to him, thinking perhaps his friend was actually alive somewhere, Darrick climbed the railing and{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint303}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint303}stepped over as the freighter shifted once more, turning slightly as the river current caught it. Another good shove like that by the current, and Darrick knew the ship would twist free. Stepping off the ship, he threw himself forward.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick landed in the mud, sinking his boots up past the ankles, losing his footing and sliding out of control, ending up facedown in the cold muck. The river current washed over him, drenching him and chilling him to the bone. In contrast, the wound in his side burned as if he\'92d been jabbed with a red-hot poker.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The other warriors leapt after him, landing in the mud for the most part, but the last few landed in the river and were nearly washed away in the current before the others helped them. For a moment as they gathered themselves,\plain \f2\i\fs24 Blue Zephyr\plain \f2\fs24 acted as a defensive wall. Quarrels thunked into the ship\'92s side from the guard ship that closed on them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  In the space of the next drawn breath, the burning ship twisted once more and was gone, following the river current. The ship full of guards managed to avoid the bigger ship, but the wash left by its passing and their efforts to get out of the way caught them and nearly capsized them. Then the freighter was by them, plunging downriver toward the ships lying at anchor, promising all manner of destruction before morning saw Bramwell again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Damnation,\'94 Palat swore. \'93We\'92re like to burn this unfortunate town down around its ears while we\'92re trying to save it tonight.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If it happens,\'94 Taramis said, \'93the people here would be better served if it were humans doing the rebuilding instead of demons.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Slipping and sliding, Darrick followed the sage into the sewer tunnel. He only noted then that his sword had dimmed, leaving Taramis\'92s torch and the lanterns and torches carried by the other warriors.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sewer was halfway submerged from the problems Taramis had found out about during his foray through Bramwell\'92s taverns. The collision with the freighter had{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint304}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint304}broken through the wall as Taramis had planned, but the extent of the damage was greater than what Darrick would have believed possible. Water poured through cracks in the mortared brick wall wide enough to fit the fingers of a man\'92s hand, sluicing in to join the waist-high deluge that rapidly deepened. Moss and slime grew on the sewer walls, and muck clung to the stone floor beneath the rancid-smelling water.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis halted in the middle of the wide sewer, glancing to the left and the right.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Which way?\'94 Palat asked, raking an arm over his face to clear the water and mud. Smears streaked his features.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93To the left,\'94 Taramis said, and turned in that direction.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  To the right,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat said in Darrick\'92s ear.\plain \f2\i\fs24 If ye go to the left, ye will be caught.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis waded through the rising water.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Tell them!
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Hesitant, not truly trusting that Mat was speaking to him, knowing that he could have gone insane and never noticed it until now, Darrick said, \'93You\'92re going the wrong way.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis halted in water that was now chest deep. He peered at Darrick. \'93How do you know?\'94 the sage asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick didn\'92t answer.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Tell him,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Tell him about me.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Shouts outside the sewer system echoed inside the tunnel, carried flat and hard across the water. Torchlight neared the break, and Darrick knew it wouldn\'92t be long before the guards attacked them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because Mat is telling me which way to go,\'94 Darrick said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Mat who?\'94 Taramis demanded suspiciously. \'93Your friend who was killed at Tauruk\'92s Port?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick replied, knowing he wouldn\'92t have believed his story if he\'92d been the one it was being told to. He could scarcely believe it now.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How?\'94 Taramis asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Darrick admitted. \'93But it was him who{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint305}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint305}got me to activate the sword\'92s power and show us the way into this sewer.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The warriors gathered around Taramis, all of them wet and bedraggled, all of their faces filled with doubt and dark suspicion.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What do you think?\'94 Palat asked Taramis, taking a half-step in front of the sage to separate him further from Darrick.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Aware of the big warrior\'92s cautionary measure, Darrick remained silent and understood. He would have thought he was mad as well if he hadn\'92t been the one hearing Mat\'92s voice.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis held his torch higher. The flames licked at the stones overhead, charring the moss and lichens that grew there. \'93Every time a demon is loosed into the world of men,\'94 he quoted, \'93the balance must be kept. A way will be made, and only human choice can rid the world of the demon again.\'94 He smiled, but there was no mirth in the expression. \'93Are you certain of this, Darrick?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Rhambal pointed his lantern at the wall. \'93We\'92ve got no choice about moving. Those damned guards are going to be on top of us in no time. And most of them are honest men, men just getting paid for enforcing the peace. I don\'92t want to hang around and fight them if I can help it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis nodded. \'93To the right, then.\'94 He led the way, pushing his torch before him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sewer channel gradually headed up. Darrick felt the incline more because the inrushing water flooded around him and made him more buoyant, which made walking up the hill harder than it should have been. Gradually, though, the water level dropped, and Taramis\'92s torchlight reflected in hundreds of eyes before them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Rats,\'94 Rhambal said, then swore.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The rats occupied the sides of the sewer, shifting and slithering against one another, islands and clots of rat flesh. Their hairless tails flipped and wriggled as they moved constantly.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint306}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint306}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The rising water lapped over the sides of the sewer tunnel, lifting small groups of tightly clustered rats free of their temporary retreat. Riding the crest of the water as it ebbed and flowed, the rats fixated on the warriors in the tunnel.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  And in the next moment, they attacked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Buyard Cholik rode the stone snake\'92s head back to the wall as guards circulated through the crowd. The confluence of whispered voices created a din in the cathedral that made it impossible to talk.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Someone attacked the church.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The thought pounded through Cholik\'92s mind. He didn\'92t know who could dare such a thing. During the last month, the relationship with Lord Darkulan had become even better. Ties and agreements were beginning to be made to erect a church in Westmarch. The Zakarum Church was fighting politically to disallow the Church of the Prophet of the Light entrance to the capitol city, but Cholik knew it was only a matter of time before even that resistance went away. Through Lord Darkulan and his own observers, many of whom Cholik had entertained in the church during the last month with Lord Darkulan\'92s help, the king had learned how much wealth the hopeful pilgrims brought to Bramwell.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  But even beyond the basic wealth that the church could bring to Westmarch, there was no doubt about the miracles. Or about the man who made them happen. With more people coming to the church, Cholik had begun doing more services. He now conducted six from dawn until after dusk. A normal man, Cholik knew, a simply human man, would have dropped in his tracks from the demands, but he had reveled in them, meeting them and surpassing them. Kabraxis had given Cholik his strength, shoring him up and keeping him going.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  More miracles had been worked, all of them received by those fortunate enough to be chosen to journey along the Way of Dreams. During the past months, the size and{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint307}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint307}number of the miracles had increased along with the number of services. Health had been restored. Crooked limbs had been straightened. Wealth had been given. Love had been granted. Husbands and sons who had gone missing in battles had emerged from the gaping, flaming jaws of the stone snake, called from wherever they had been to the path of the Black Road. Those survivors had no memories of where they had been until the moment they stepped from the snake\'92s mouth into the cathedral.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  And three times, youth had been restored to aging parishioners.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  That had all of the coastal cities along the Gulf of Westmarch talking as the story was carried by ship from port to port. Caravans picked up the stories in the port cities and carried them to the east, to Lut Gholein and possibly across the Twin Seas to Kurast and beyond.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Giving the youth back to the three men was the most difficult, Cholik knew, and required great sacrifice. Kabraxis made the sacrifice, but the demon didn\'92t pay the price himself. Instead, Kabraxis took children from the city during the nights and sacrificed them on the Black Road, robbing them of their years so he could reward the parishioners he\'92d chosen with extended years. All three of those parishioners were men who could help the Church of the Prophet of the Light grow and earn the favor of the king. One of them, in fact, had been one of the king\'92s own observers, a man\'97Lord Darkulan insisted\'97who was like a father to the king.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  It was a time of miracles. Everyone in Bramwell spoke of the Church of the Prophet of the Light that way. Health, wealth, love, and a return to youth\'97there was nothing more a man could hope for in life.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  But someone had dared attack the church.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Deep anger resonated inside Cholik as he gazed out over the filled cathedral. One of the lesser priests Cholik had groomed stepped forward into the lighted area below.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Brothers and sisters,\'94 the priest said, \'93beloved of Dien-Ap-Sten, join me now in prayer to our magnificent{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint308}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint308}prophet. Wayfinder Sayes goes to speak on your behalf to our prophet and ask that only a few more miracles be granted before we take leave of this service.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  His words, amplified by the specially constructed stage, rolled over the church audience and quieted the whispering that had resulted from the news about the attack on the church.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Threaten to take away their chances at a miracle for themselves,\plain \f2\fs24 Cholik mused\plain \f2\i\fs24 , and you get the attention of every person in the room.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The priest guided the assembly in prayers to Dien-Ap-Sten, singing of the prophet\'92s greatness, goodness, and generousness.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Once the snake\'92s head was again locked into place on the wall and had become immobile, the flames died away, and that section of the cathedral darkened. Many worshippers screamed out Dien-Ap-Sten\'92s name then, begging that the prophet return and grant more miracles.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik stepped from the platform on the snake\'92s back onto the third-floor balcony. A guard hidden in the shadows pulled the heavy drapes back and opened the door for him. Two crossbowmen stood behind the drapes at all times, relieved every hour during the times of service.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Stepping through the door into the hallway beyond, Cholik found a dozen members of his personal guard waiting for him. No one used this hallway except him, and it led to the secret passageways that had been honeycombed throughout the church. They held lanterns to light the darkened hallway.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What is going on?\'94 Cholik demanded, stopping among them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The church has been attacked, Wayfinder,\'94 Captain Rhellik reported. He was a hard-faced man, used to commanding mercenaries and waging small, hard-won wars or tracking bandits.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I knew that,\'94 Cholik spat. \'93Who has dared attack my church?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Rhellik shook his head. \'93I\'92ve not yet learned, Wayfinder.{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint309}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint309}From what I\'92ve been told, a ship smashed into the courtyard south of the church that overhung the river.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93An accident?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No, Wayfinder. The attack on the parapet was deliberate.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Why attack the courtyard there? What could they possibly hope to gain?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I don\'92t know, Wayfinder.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik believed the mercenary captain. When Rhellik had been brought to the church almost a year ago, he\'92d been dying a paraplegic, paralyzed from the neck down by a horse stepping on him during a battle with bandits while traveling from Lut Gholein. His men had bound him to a litter and brought him almost two hundred miles for healing.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  At first, Cholik had seen no value in the mercenary captain, but Kabraxis had insisted that they watch him. For weeks, Rhellik had stayed at every service, fed by his men and bathed in the river, and he had sung praises to Dien-Ap-Sten as best as he was able with his failing voice. Then, one day, the snake\'92s head had lifted him from the crowd and gulped him down. A few minutes after that, the mercenary captain had walked back from the Way of Dreams, hale and hearty, and he had pledged his service forever to the prophet Dien-Ap-Sten and his Wayfinder.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It doesn\'92t make any sense,\'94 Cholik said, starting down the hallway.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No, Wayfinder,\'94 Rhellik agreed. He raised the lantern he carried in one hand to light their way. He carried his vicious curved sword in the other hand.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93None of these people has been identified?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How large is the force that attacked the church?\'94 Cholik demanded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No more than a couple dozen warriors,\'94 Rhellik said. \'93The city guards tried to turn them.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The boat had to sail upriver to crash into that parapet.\'94 Cholik turned and followed the passageway to his right,{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint310}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint310}going up the short flight of steps. He knew every hallway in the church. His robes swished as he hurried. \'93It couldn\'92t have been going fast. Why didn\'92t the city guards stop it?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The ship was driven by magic, Wayfinder. They had no chance to stop it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And we don\'92t know who these people are?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I regret to say, Wayfinder, that we don\'92t. As soon as that changes, I\'92ll let you know.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Only a little farther on, Cholik reached the hidden door that opened into one of the main hallways on the fourth floor. He released the lock and stepped out into the hallway.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  No one was in the hallway. No visitors were allowed up from the first and second floors where seating was made available in the cathedral. And none of the staff who lived there was in those rooms because they were all attending the service. The south fourth-floor wing was reserved for acolytes who had been with the church for six months or longer. It was surprising how quickly those small rooms had filled.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik turned to the left and walked toward the balcony that overlooked the parapet courtyard at the river\'92s edge below.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Wayfinder,\'94 Rhellik said uncomfortably.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What?\'94 Cholik snapped.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Perhaps it would be better if you allowed us to protect you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Protect me?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93By taking you to one of the lower rooms where we can better defend you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You want to hide me away?\'94 Cholik asked in exasperation. \'93At a time when my church is attacked, you expect me to hide away like some coward?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92m sorry, Wayfinder, but it would be the safest course of action.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The mercenary\'92s words weighed heavily on Cholik\'92s thoughts. He had sought out Kabraxis with his mind, but the demon was nowhere to be found. The situation irritated and{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint311}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint311}frightened him. As big as the church was, there was nowhere for him to go if he\'92d been targeted by assassins.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Cholik said. \'93I am guarded by Dien-Ap-Sten\'92s love for me. That will be my buckler and my shield.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes, Wayfinder. I apologize for doubting.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Doubters do not stay in the grace of the Prophet of the Light for long, captain. I would have you remember that.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Of course, Wayfinder.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik strode up the final flight of steps to the balcony. The night wind whipped over him. There was no sign of the mystical winds of which Rhellik had spoken. But Cholik\'92s eyes settled on the burning ship loose on the river current.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Flames roiled across the entire length of the ship, twisting and shifting and racing toward the heavens. Swirls of orange and red embers leapt up from the topmost parts of the masts and rigging, dying in their suicidal race to reach the night sky. In the next moment, the ship rammed into one of the vessels anchored in the river harbor, catching the other ship broadside.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A shower of embers and flying debris from the sails blew over the line of ships beyond the two that remained locked together. Torches and lanterns marked the sailors running to deal with the fire and save the ships. As tightly packed as they were, the fire would spread rapidly if it remained unchecked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik glanced upriver, spotting the guards at the base of the river where the hanging courtyard had been torn away. He watched in confused speculation as the guards leapt from their craft and waded through the water. Only when their lanterns and torches neared the opening in the sewer did he spot it.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93They\'92re inside the sewers,\'94 Cholik said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Rhellik nodded. \'93I have already sent a runner to take some of my men there to intercept them. We have maps of the sewer systems.\'94 His mouth tightened into a grim line. \'93We shall protect you, Wayfinder. You need have no fear.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I have no fear,\'94 Cholik said, turning to address the{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint312}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint312}mercenary captain. \'93I am chosen of Dien-Ap-Sten. I am the Wayfinder of the Way of Dreams where all miracles take place. The men who have broken into my church are dead men, whether they know it or not. If they don\'92t die at the hands of the guards or at my own hands, then they will die at the hands of Dien-Ap-Sten. Although generous to his believers, Dien-Ap-Sten is merciless against those who would strike against him.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The guards funneled into the breached sewer tunnel. Their lantern light and torchlight made the opening glow cherry red like a wound gone bad with poisonous infection.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Pass the word along to your men, captain,\'94 Cholik said. \'93I want them to watch for the burned man who attacked me last month.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Yes, Wayfinder. I only pray that no worshipper comes here this night with such an affliction in hopes of being healed. Such a person would find only death waiting.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Cholik stared across the black river. Clusters of lights stood on either bank. More lights raced along the two bridges that connected the north and south sections of the city.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  When the attackers were caught, and Cholik had every reason to believe that they would be, they would be put to death. He\'92d have their heads mounted on pikes at the main entrance through the church walls, and he would say that Dien-Ap-Sten had commanded that it be so, to show the enemies of the Church of the Prophet of the Light that the prophet could be fierce and unforgiving as well. It would temper the faith of those who believed, and it would be a grand story that would bring more people in to see the church and the religion.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Buyard Cholik.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Surprised by the demon\'92s voice in his head, Cholik started. \'93Yes, Dien-Ap-Sten.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The mercenary captain signaled his men, waving them back away from Cholik, taking two steps himself. He touched the back of his sword hand to the tattoo that had{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint313}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint313}been placed over his heart when he had sworn loyalty to the church. A rote prayer to the prophet tumbled from his lips, praying for a safe and enlightening journey that the wisdom and power of Dien-Ap-Sten be spread even farther.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Return to the services,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 I will not have those disrupted. I will not be shown as weak or wanting.\plain \f2\fs24 The demon sounded far away.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Who has attacked the church?\'94 Cholik asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Taramis Volken and his band of demon hunters,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A worm of fear crawled through Cholik\'92s heart. Although he had not talked to Kabraxis of the demon hunter, Cholik had read about the man. Taramis Volken had been a powerful force against demons for years. Once he had read and heard some of the stories about the man, Cholik remembered reading about him from the archives in the Zakarum Church. Taramis Volken was viewed as an inflexible man, one who would not quit. The demon hunter had proven that over the last few weeks. Ever since recovering Stormfury, Hauklin\'92s sword, the group had vanished.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  They\'92ve only been hidden,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Now they are once more in my grasp.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  But before he could stop himself, Cholik wondered if they were somehow in Taramis Volken\'92s grasp instead. All his training in the Zakarum Church had taught him that demons didn\'92t enter the human world without affecting the balance between Light and Darkness. Taramis Volken had proven himself to be the champion of Light on several occasions.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Taramis Volken will die in those sewers,\plain \f2\fs24 Kabraxis growled inside Cholik\'92s mind.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Doubt me, and you will pay, Buyard Cholik, even if you are my chosen one.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I don\'92t doubt you, Dien-Ap-Sten,\'94 Cholik said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Then go. I will deal with Taramis Volken.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93As you wish, my prophet.\'94 Cholik touched his head in benediction, then turned with a swirl of his robe.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint314}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint314}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Wayfinder,\'94 Rhellik said, looking up, \'93returning to the cathedral might not be the safest thing you can do.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It is the safest place to be,\'94 Cholik said, \'93when you go there with Dien-Ap-Sten\'92s blessing.\'94\plain \f2\i\fs24 And not going there could be the most dangerous.\plain \f2\fs24 But he amended that even as he thought it.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The most dangerous place to be was in the sewers beneath the Church of the Prophet of the Light.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint315}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint315}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  TWENTY-THREE
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\pict\jpegblip\picw29\pich23 }
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Hairless tails flicking, sharp teeth snapping, the rat packs poured toward Darrick, Taramis Volken, and the demon hunters. The pale yellow light of the warriors\'92 lanterns and torches played over the wriggling rat bodies as they raced along the ledges and the uneven walls and swam through the murky water of the sewer mixing with the river encroaching through the break in the tunnel behind them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 For a moment, ice-cold terror thudded through Darrick\'92s veins as he thought about being covered over in a mass of furry bodies and dragged under the water. The other warriors cursed and called out to the Light as they spread out and took up defensive positions.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Rhambal stood tall and massive at the head of the group. With a backward swipe of his shield, the warrior knocked a dozen of the leaping rats from the air. The thuds of their bodies slamming against the shield echoed in the sewer tunnel.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Stand,\'94 Taramis ordered his warriors. \'93Hold them from me for only a moment more.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Rats leapt from the walls, landing on the armored helms and shoulders of the warriors. Their claws scratched against the plate and chainmail, demanding blood.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick swiped at one of the foul creatures and halved it from nose to tail with Hauklin\'92s sharp blade. The rat\'92s blood sprayed across him, blinding him in one eye for a moment. By the time he\'92d wiped the blood from his face and cleared his vision, three more rats landed on him, staggering him with their sudden weight. The rats started up toward his face at once, the flickering torchlight dancing{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint316}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint316}across their fangs. Cursing, Darrick knocked the rats from him. They plopped into the water and disappeared for a moment before they bobbed back to the surface.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Despite their best efforts, the warriors gave ground before the onslaught of rats. Blades and hammers flashed through the air, coming dangerously close to hitting their comrades. Blood mixed in with the dark sewer water and the white froth of the river rushing into the tunnel.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The undertow created by the pull of the river and the push of the sewer almost dislodged Darrick\'92s tenuous stance atop the muck-lined stone floor. Darrick whipped the sword around, amazed at how easily and fluidly the weapon moved. Dead rats and pieces of dead rats flew around him, but still many managed to reach him. Their fangs cut his arms and legs where they were left uncovered by the chainmail shirt he wore.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Working quickly, Taramis inscribed magical symbols in the air. Green fire followed his fingertips, and the finished symbols glowed brightly. With another gesture, the sage sent the symbols spinning forward.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The symbols exploded in the air only a few feet away, and white light stabbed out. The light shafts speared through the rats and dropped them in their tracks, shredding the flesh from their bones till only skeletons remained.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  For a moment, Darrick believed the danger had passed. The bites stung, but none of them was bad enough to slow him. Infection, however, was a concern, but only if they lived through the attack on the church.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Taramis,\'94 Palat said, supporting one of the warriors and keeping a hand pressed over his neck. \'93One of the rats tore Clavyn\'92s throat and cut the jugular vein. If we don\'92t get the bleeding stopped, he\'92s going to die.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Wading through the rising water to examine the warrior, Taramis shook his head. \'93There\'92s nothing I can do,\'94 he whispered hoarsely. They\'92d not been able to find healing potions along the way and lacked gold to buy it, besides.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Palat\'92s face turned wintry hard as the blood continued seeping between his fingers. \'93I\'92m not going to let him die,{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint317}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint317}damn it,\'94 the grizzled old warrior said. \'93I didn\'92t come all this way just to watch my friends die.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Shaking his head, Taramis said, \'93There\'92s nothing you can do.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Horror touched Darrick, sliding past the defenses he tried to erect. If Clavyn died a quick death, they\'92d have to leave his body there\'97for the rats. And if the warrior died slowly, he\'92d have to die alone, because they couldn\'92t afford to stay with him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Since arriving in the tunnel, Darrick had stepped back into that safe place he\'92d first created to endure his father\'92s beatings and harsh words. He refused to let Clavyn\'92s death touch him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  No,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat whispered.\plain \f2\i\fs24 He doesn\'92t have to die, Darrick. Use the sword. Use Hauklin\'92s sword.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93How?\'94 Darrick asked. Inside the tunnel, his voice cut through the splashing echoes of the water swirling into the walls on either side of him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  The hilt,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat replied.\plain \f2\i\fs24 The hilt must be pressed to Clavyn\'92s flesh.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Desperate, not wanting to see the man die in such an ignoble fashion, Darrick moved forward. As he did, the sword\'92s blade glowed fierce blue again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Palat stepped forward, standing between Darrick and the wounded warrior. \'93No,\'94 Palat said. \'93I\'92ll not have you ending his life.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92m not going to kill him,\'94 Darrick said. \'93I\'92m going to try to save him.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Still, the big warrior refused to move.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  In that moment, Darrick knew that he\'92d never been one of them and would never be one of them. They had traveled together and eaten together and fought together, but he was apart from them. Only his ability to take Hauklin\'92s sword had bound them to him. Anger stirred in him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Darrick,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Don\'92t give in to this. You\'92re not alone.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  But Darrick knew that wasn\'92t true. He\'92d been alone all his life. At the end, even Mat had left him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  No,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat argued.\plain \f2\i\fs24 The way ye\'92re feelin\'92 isn\'92t real, Darrick. It\'92s{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint318}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint318}the demon. It\'92s Kabraxis. He\'92s down here with us. He\'92s aware of us. Even now, there are warriors coming to intercept yer group. But Kabraxis\'92s thoughts are within ye\'92s. I\'92m tryin\'92 to keep him from ye, but he\'92s sortin\'92 out yer weaknesses. Don\'92t let the demon turn ye from these men. They need ye.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A fierce headache dawned between Darrick\'92s temples, then throbbed with an insane beat that almost dropped him to his knees in the cold water. Black spots swam in his vision.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Use the sword, Darrick,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat insisted.\plain \f2\i\fs24 It can save all of ye.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What can I do?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Believe,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat answered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Struggling, Darrick tried to find the key to make the magic work. It would be better if there were a magic word or something else. All he could remember was how the sword had acted and felt at Ellig Barrows\'92s house, and how the sword had behaved when it lit the riverbank to reveal the tunnel they\'92d clambered through only moments before. It wasn\'92t belief, Darrick knew, but it was something he knew to be true.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sword shivered and glowed blue again. Calm warmth filled the tunnel and soaked into Darrick\'92s flesh and bones as a humming sound filled the air. In stunned amazement, he watched as the blood stopped slipping between Palat\'92s fingers.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Hesitantly, Palat removed his hand from Clavyn\'92s neck, revealing the jagged wound that had severed the warrior\'92s jugular. As they watched, the flesh knitted, turning back into seamless flesh with only a small scar left behind.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The humming and the warmth continued, and Darrick watched as even the wounds he\'92d endured healed, including the rip along his ribcage made by the arrow earlier. In less than a minute, the warriors were all healed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Blessed by the Light,\'94 Rhambal said, a childlike grin on his broad face. \'93We\'92ve been blessed by the Light.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Or saved to be killed later,\'94 Palat growled, \'93if you\'92re going to stand there flapping your lips.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick reached for Mat, wanting to hear his voice.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint319}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint319}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Stay strong,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 The worst is yet to come. This is only the calm before the storm.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Damn,\'94 Palat swore, pointing back the way they\'92d come. \'93The guards are nearly upon us.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Head buzzing, still filled with the headache, Darrick gazed back along the tunnel.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Flickering light filled the darkness behind them, proof that the guard ship had arrived. Splashing echoed around Darrick and signaled the guards\'92 approach.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Forward,\'94 Taramis ordered, lifting his lantern and moving farther up the sewer.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The group started forward, fighting the water and the sewer\'92s slick stone bottom. The darkness ahead of them retreated before the torches and the lanterns. Darting through the shadows and the water, a few rats shrilled and squeaked at their approach but made no move to attack.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Something thudded into Darrick\'92s side, drawing his attention. He looked down, barely able to spot the short piece of ivory bone that slid through the water. At first, he thought the bone was some sore of creature with a hard carapace, then he saw that it was a leg bone from one of the rats Taramis had slain with his spell.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Hey,\'94 Rhambal called out, reaching down and snatching a small rat\'92s skull from the water. \'93These are the bones of the rats.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Before the big warrior could say any more, the skull leapt from his hand and snapped at his face, causing him to draw back. He swept his armored fist at it, but the skull was gone, dropping back into the water.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Hold,\'94 Taramis said, taking a lantern from one of the nearby warriors and raising it. The light chased the darkness, splintering the shadows and reflecting from the tossed and uneven planes of the water.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Revealed by the lantern light, hundreds of bones slid through the water, flashing greenish white under the light.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It\'92s the demon\'92s doing,\'94 Palat snarled. \'93The demon knows we\'92re down here.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  In the next instant, a frightening figure surged from{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint320}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint320}beneath the water. The line of warriors closest to it stepped back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Formed of the rats\'92 bones, the creature stood eight feet tall, built square and broad-chested as an ape. It stood on bowed legs that were whitely visible through the murky water. Instead of two arms, the bone creature possessed four, all longer than the legs. When it closed its hands, horns formed of ribs and rats\'92 teeth stuck out of the creature\'92s fists, rendering them into morningstars for all intents and purposes. The horns looked sharp-edged, constructed for slashing as well as stabbing. Small bones, some of them jagged pieces of bone, formed the demon\'92s face the creature wore.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93That\'92s a bone golem,\'94 Taramis said. \'93Your weapons won\'92t do it much harm.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The bone golem\'92s mouth, created by splintered bones so tightly interwoven they gave the semblance of mobility, grinned, then opened as the creature spoke in a harsh howl that sounded like a midnight wind tearing through a graveyard. \'93Come to your deaths, fools.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis gestured with his free hand, inscribing a mystic symbol. Immediately, the symbol became a pumpkin-sized fireball that streaked for the incredible bone creature.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Striking the bone golem in the chest, the impact of the fireball knocked the creature back on its heels for a moment. Flames wreathed the demon-made thing, crawling through the gaps in the bones till it seemed to be burning on the inside as well. Steam welled out of the bone golem but didn\'92t appear to do any further damage.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Opening its mouth again, the bone golem howled once more, and this time flames spat into the air as well. The ululating wail echoed the length of the sewer, so loud it was deafening. Several of the warriors put their hands to their ears, their mouths open as they screamed in pain.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick never heard the warriors\'92 screams over the spine-chilling roar. But he heard Mat\'92s voice.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  It\'92s up to ye, Darrick,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat said calmly.\plain \f2\i\fs24 The bone golem will kill them if it gets the chance. Only Hauklin\'92s enchanted blade can damage the creature.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint321}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint321}\plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92m no hero,\'94 Darrick whispered as he looked at the creature.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Perhaps not,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat said,\plain \f2\i\fs24 but there\'92s no place to run.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Glancing back over his shoulder, Darrick saw the line of church guards filling the sewer behind them. Retreat only offered the inevitable battle with the guards and the promise of even more waiting for them out in the harbor.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The warriors drew back beside Darrick, obviously preferring their chances against human foes instead of the bone golem. Darrick stared at the creature, pushing himself through and past his fear. There was no way out except through the bone golem.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  He stepped forward, falling into a defensive position as the creature closed on him. One of the spiked fists slashed at him. Ducking beneath the blow, Darrick set himself and cut upward. Catching the bone golem\'92s arm with the edge of his blade, Darrick tried to cut through the elbow joint. The blow missed by a couple of inches and skidded along the creature\'92s arm.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Sensing his opponent\'92s movement more than he saw it, Darrick dodged backward, narrowly avoiding the balled left fist that streaked for his head. The bone blades jutting from the fist slashed through the chest of his traveling leathers, then splashed into the waist-high water swirling around them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Before the bone golem could draw its arm back, Darrick swung the enchanted blade again. This time the sword sheared through the arm, splintering it into a thousand bone shards and scattering them through the water. The bone golem threw a right fist at Darrick\'92s face that would have carved the face from his skull if it had landed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Desperately, Darrick threw himself backward. The razor edges of the fist slashed across his chest again, cutting through his traveling leathers but scoring on the flesh beneath this time as well. Fear rattled through Darrick, almost causing him to give up hope, but Hauklin\'92s sword felt steady and true in his hands. He parried the bone golem\'92s next blow, turning the huge fist from its target,{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint322}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint322}stepping back as the creature followed the bony hammer into the water and bent double. Spinning, Darrick landed a blow against the bone golem\'92s ribcage beneath the stub of its bottom left arm. Broken bone shards flew in all directions, but the creature remained whole.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Still moving, somehow keeping his footing in the water and in the muck, Darrick retreated, slashing and parrying with Hauklin\'92s sword. Crimson stained the front of his traveling leathers as he bled. While pulling back, he tripped and fell.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The bone golem swiped at Darrick at once, aiming a fist at his face.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Then Rhambal was there, blocking the blow with his shield. The razor-sharp spikes that festooned the bone golem\'92s fist tore through the warrior\'92s shield less than a foot from Darrick\'92s face. Getting his feet under him again, Darrick saw the bone golem\'92s spike pierce Rhambal\'92s shield and into the arm that held it. Blood spurted as the bone golem drew its fist free.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  In obvious agony, Rhambal stepped back, then faltered and fell to his knees, clutching his wounded arm to his chest and leaving his head exposed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Guilt hammered Darrick, more painful than the cuts across his chest.\plain \f2\i\fs24 It\'92s my fault,\plain \f2\fs24 he told himself.\plain \f2\i\fs24 If I hadn\'92t been able to free Hauklin\'92s sword, they would have never come here.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  No,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 They would have come, Darrick. Even without ye an\'92 that sword. It\'92s the demon working inside ye. It\'92s puttin\'92 them thoughts there. Fillin\'92 ye with bad thoughts an\'92 makin\'92 ye weak. Ye can make a difference in this, an\'92 that\'92s what I come back for. Now move!
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The bone golem wasted no time in setting itself and attacking the new prey it found before it. Gripping the enchanted sword in both hands, Darrick stepped forward and swung. When the blade met the bone golem\'92s arm, the weapon shattered the limb.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Roaring with rage, the bone golem turned its attention back to Darrick, flailing after him with its two remaining arms. Darrick fended one of the blows off, then avoided{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint323}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint323}the other, throwing himself into the air and flipping over the arm.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis and Palat dashed forward, caught Rhambal under the arms, and dragged him back from the bone golem\'92s reach.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Landing on his feet, Darrick blocked another sweeping roundhouse blow, feeling the impact vibrate through his wrists and arms. He almost lost his grip on the sword but clung to it tightly. Running at the wall on the left, knowing if he stopped the bone golem would swarm over him, Darrick threw himself into the air and struck the wall with his water-filled boots. Water splashed out of his boots on impact.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  You\'92re a blight on me, boy,\plain \f2\fs24 his father\'92s voice thundered inside his head.\plain \f2\i\fs24 An embarrassment to me. By the Light, I hate the sight of your ugly face. It ain\'92t no face that ever belonged to me. And that red hair of yours, you\'92ll never find it in my family. Nor in your ma\'92s, I\'92ll warrant.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The words tumbled through Darrick\'92s mind, splitting his concentration as he cushioned the impact against the wall by bending his knees and falling forward.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Don\'92t listen to him,\plain \f2\fs24 Mat said.\plain \f2\i\fs24 It\'92s only the damned demon talkin\'92 to ye. He\'92s lookin\'92 for yer weak spots, he is. An\'92 yer personal business, why, it\'92s no business of his.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  But Darrick knew that the words didn\'92t just come from the demon. They came from that small stable in back of his father\'92s butcher shop, and they came from years of abuse and cold hatred that he hadn\'92t understood as a child. Even as a young man, Darrick had been powerless to defend himself against his father\'92s harsh words. Maybe his father had learned not to be so quick with his hands when Darrick had started fighting back, but Darrick had never learned to protect himself from his father\'92s verbal assaults and his mother\'92s neglect.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick fell forward on the wall, his forward momentum allowing him to make contact for just an instant before gravity pulled him toward the water-filled tunnel. From the corner of his eye, he saw the bone golem throwing{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint324}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint324}another punch. By the time it reached the wall where he\'92d landed, he had pushed off with one hand\'97the other gripping Hauklin\'92s sword\'97and flipped back toward the tunnel behind his attacker.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The bone golem\'92s fist crunched into the wall, splitting stone and breaking loose mortar that held it together.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick forced his father\'92s words from his mind, stilled his shaking hand, and squared himself as he took a full breath of the fetid air around him. Taking a two-handed grip on the magical blade, watching the bone golem start turning to face him, Darrick saw Taramis and his warriors on the other side of the creature. Beyond them, the church guards awaited an opportunity. Crossbowman fired their weapons, but the quarrels caught on the shields of the men at the rear of the warrior group.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Do it!\plain \f2\fs24 Mat roared in Darrick\'92s head.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sword blazed blue again, a true and cold blue like that found in the sea before the deep turned black. Swinging, not holding anything back, Darrick felt the enchanted weapon shatter through the bone golem\'92s ribcage and grate to a stop embedded in the creature\'92s spine.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The bone golem howled with pain, but its macabre voice carried laughter as well, rolling gales of it. \'93Now you\'92re going to die, insect.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Darrick said, feeling the power tingling through the sword. \'93Go back to hell, demon.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Eldritch blue flames leapt down the length of the sword and curled around the bone golem\'92s spine as it reached for Darrick. The fire grew, enveloping the bone golem and burning away whatever magic bound the skeletal remains of the dead rats together. Flaming bones toppled into the sewer water, hissing when they struck.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  For a moment, everyone\'97including Darrick\'97stood frozen in disbelief.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\i\fs24  Run!\plain \f2\fs24 Mat yelled.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Turning, Darrick ran, raising his knees high to clear the water level. The sword continued to glow, chasing back the{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint325}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint325}shadows that filled the tunnel. Taramis and the demon hunters came after Darrick.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Less than fifty yards farther on, the tunnel ended at a T juncture. Without hesitation, the sword pulled Darrick to the right. He ran on, filmed by the condensation filling the tunnel as well as perspiration pouring from every pore. His breath burned the back of his throat, and he was convinced the stench of the place was soaking into him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Only a short distance farther on, the tunnel ended without warning. Sometime in distant years past, the sewer had collapsed. The sword\'92s bright blade illuminated the pile of rubble that blocked the passageway. Cloaked in the shadows and the collapse of broken rock, rats prowled the rubbish heap. Hundreds of them scampered and crept along the broken rock.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Above the rubble, a rounded dome of fallen earth peeked through. No longer shored up by the stones, the earth had collapsed inward over the years but had not completely fallen. There was no way to guess how many feet of earth and rock separated the tunnel from the surface.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Dead end,\'94 Palat growled. \'93That damned sword has played us false this time, Taramis. Those guards will be down on us in another moment, and there\'92s no place for us to run.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis turned to Darrick. \'93What is the meaning of this?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Darrick admitted.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint326}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint326}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  TWENTY-FOUR
