\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Cold, distant morning sun split the eastern sky, threading the white clouds with violent reds and purples like a fertilized egg that had been cracked too close to term and held blood in the yolk. Despite the cold blowing down out of the mountains, the sun\'92s rays chased the night\'92s shadows away from Bramwell and out into the sea.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 Darrick Lang stood atop the garden-covered roof of the Church of the Prophet of the Light as he had all through the long night. He wore his heavy cloak, but the wind cut through it and left him near frozen; still, he wouldn\'92t walk away. His father\'92s voice had rung in his head for hours and had only started to dim a short time ago. Darrick didn\'92t hear Mat\'92s voice at all and didn\'92t know if Mat had continued on through the ghost roads or if he had died yet again during the final confrontation. It was hard not knowing.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Some of Buyard Cholik\'92s mercenaries had threatened to put up a fight, but since their employer had been killed, not many of them had the heart for it. Palat had spat blood and told them they were all mad because they\'92d lost easy jobs, and if they wanted to lose more than that, all they had to do was step up. None of the mercenaries had. During the confusion, Raithen had disappeared.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis had kept his group together, fearing retaliation on the part of the stunned crowd. At first, it had looked as if the audience would turn on the demon slayers despite the fact that Darrick had held Kabraxis\'92s head and showed them the lie they had been told. They had been there to witness and receive miracles and had seen all that torn away instead. Some of them had sat in the pews for hours,{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint354}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint354}in faint hope that the Prophet of the Light and the Wayfinder would return for those who truly believed.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Footsteps scraped the rooftop.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick turned, Hauklin\'92s mystic sword still bared in his fist. Although he had worked with Taramis and the other demon hunters and had slain both Buyard Cholik and Kabraxis, Darrick knew they still didn\'92t trust him. His path was not theirs; he wouldn\'92t ride off into the new dawn or find a ship out in the harbor to make war against another demon.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Another demon. A bitter laugh rose to Darrick\'92s lips, but he let it die. He wasn\'92t over the last demon yet. Nor was he over the demons his father had instilled within him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis Volken walked through the gardens. The sage still carried the signs of battle\'97blood, some of it his and some belonging to others, and soot\'97on his orange robes. Shadows clung to his face despite the dawn, and he looked older somehow in the clean light.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I wondered if you would still be up here,\'94 the sage said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No, you didn\'92t,\'94 Darrick said. \'93You\'92ve had Rhambal watching the passageway from the rooftop.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis hesitated only a moment. \'93You\'92re right, of course.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick said nothing.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Walking over to the roof\'92s edge, the sage looked down. The breeze ruffled his orange robes. \'93Many of the worshippers aren\'92t leaving.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Reluctantly, Darrick joined the older man at the roof\'92s edge and peered down as well. The streets in front of the church were choked with people despite the city guard\'92s best efforts to move them along. Smoke billowed from a half-dozen burning buildings.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93They haven\'92t stopped believing,\'94 Taramis said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Because Cholik and Kabraxis gave them what they wanted,\'94 Darrick said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Some of them,\'94 Taramis corrected. \'93And the price was high. But it was enough to keep the others here, hoping that{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint355}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint355}they would be picked out next for fortune\'92s favor.\'94 He looked up at Darrick. \'93What the demon did was a terrible thing.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick remained silent. The north wind wasn\'92t any colder than the sage\'92s words.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The city guard is fighting with roving bands of worshippers in the city,\'94 Taramis said. \'93Many of them are protesting the night\'92s events. They say that Cholik and the Prophet Dien-Ap-Sten were slain by Lord Darkulan out of jealousy and that there never was a demon.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The demon is gone,\'94 Darrick said. \'93Not believing Kabraxis wasn\'92t a demon isn\'92t going to bring him back.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No, but they want revenge against the city for the guilt and confusion and anger they feel. If Bramwell is lucky, only a few buildings and a few lives will be lost before the guard gets the situation under control.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick reflected on his own dark anger. The emotion was residue from what his father had done to him. He knew that now, but he also knew that residue was indelible and would be with him forever.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93They say,\'94 Taramis said, \'93that when a man faces a demon, that man comes to know himself in ways he was never shown before. You faced Kabraxis, Darrick, more closely than any man I\'92ve ever known before.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92ve fought and killed demons,\'94 Darrick countered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis leaned against the roof ledge and crossed his hands over his chest. \'93I\'92ve never followed them into the Burning Hells to do it as you did.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Would you have?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93If I\'92d had to, yes.\'94 No trace of hesitation sounded in the sage\'92s voice. \'93But I have to ask myself why you did.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I didn\'92t choose that path,\'94 Darrick pointed out. \'93The snake swallowed me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The snake swallowed you because Kabraxis thought he could beat you on the Black Road. And he thought he could beat Stormfury. My question to you is, why did the demon think that?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  For a long while, Darrick held the silence between them,{\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint356}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint356}but he realized that the sage wasn\'92t going to go anywhere. \'93Because of the guilt I carry,\'94 he finally said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Over your friend Mat?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And more,\'94 Darrick admitted. Then, before he could stop himself, he told the sage the story of his father and of the beatings he\'92d received in the butcher\'92s shop in Hillsfar. \'93It took me a long time to figure out that my mother had been unfaithful to my father and that I didn\'92t know who my true father was. I still don\'92t.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Have you ever wanted to know?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Sometimes,\'94 Darrick admitted. \'93But the Light only knows what trouble that would bring if I did find out. I\'92ve had trouble enough.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Kabraxis thought he could weaken you by confronting you with your father\'92s anger.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93He would have done it,\'94 Darrick said, \'93were it not for Mat. Always during those times after the beatings, Mat stood by me. And he stood by me again on the Black Road.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93By helping you through Kabraxis\'92s subterfuge.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye.\'94 Darrick gazed at the sage. \'93But the winning wasn\'92t all mine, you see.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis looked at him.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I defeated Kabraxis in the Burning Hells,\'94 Darrick said, \'93but I brought a part of it back with me.\'94 With a quick move, he thrust Stormfury into one of the nearby garden beds. Such treatment to a weapon was unthinkable because the moisture would make it rust. But he knew the mystical sword would suffer no damage. He left the sword quivering there and held out his hand. \'93The damned demon tainted me somehow.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick\'92s hand shimmered, then began to change, losing its humanness and twisting into a demonic appendage.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93By the Light,\'94 Taramis whispered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I destroyed Buyard Cholik and Kabraxis\'92s way into our world,\'94 Darrick said, \'93but I became that way.\'94 Long talons jutted from his fingers now covered in hairy, green and black skin.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint357}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint357}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93When did this happen?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93While I was on the Black Road,\'94 Darrick said. \'93I\'92ll tell you another thing, too. Kabraxis isn\'92t dead. I don\'92t know if he\'92ll ever have another body that will survive in our world, but he\'92s still alive in the Burning Hells. Every now and again, I can hear him whispering to me, mocking me. He\'92s waiting, you see, for me to give up and die or to lose control of myself by getting drunk or not caring if I live or die.\'94 He reached for Hauklin\'92s sword, closed his hand around it, and watched as the hand became human again.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Hauklin\'92s sword grounds you,\'94 Taramis said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick said. \'93And it keeps me human.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Kabraxis cursed you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick sheathed the sword at his side. \'93Kabraxis\'92s gateway from the Burning Hells no longer lies under the ruins of the city on the Dyre River. His gateway is now me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And if you should be killed by another?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick shook his head. \'93I don\'92t know. If my body were completely destroyed, maybe Kabraxis wouldn\'92t be able to make his way into this world again.\'94 He smiled, but it was cold and devoid of humor, holding only bitterness. \'93By revealing this to you, I feel as though I\'92ve put my life at risk.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis didn\'92t say anything for a time. \'93There are some who would be tempted to put you to death rather than risk the demon\'92s return.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And you?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Doing such a thing would make me no better than the monsters I hunt,\'94 the sage replied. \'93No, you have nothing to fear from me. But should Kabraxis gain the upper hand within you, I\'92ll hunt you down and kill you.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Fair enough,\'94 Darrick agreed. He knew he could expect no less.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You will need to keep Hauklin\'92s sword with you,\'94 Taramis said. \'93I\'92ll explain the matter to Ellig Barrows, but chances are that he and his family will be glad to be shut of it.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick nodded.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint358}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint358}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93What will you do?\'94 Taramis asked. \'93Where will you go?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I don\'92t know.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You could ride with us.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We both know my place isn\'92t with you,\'94 Darrick replied. \'93Although it would probably prove easier for you to keep your eye on me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  A wry grin fitted Taramis\'92s face. \'93True.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93There is something more I received from the demon\'92s death,\'94 Darrick said. He strode close to the sage. \'93You\'92re wounded. Show it to me.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Hesitantly, Taramis pulled his robe away and revealed the deep wound in his side. Someone had clumsily bandaged it, but the blood still seeped through.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick clapped a hand over the sage\'92s side, causing him to wince. Power flowed through Darrick, and for the time it took to work, he heard Kabraxis\'92s whispers more loudly in the back of his mind. He took his hand away. \'93Check the wound.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  In disbelief, Taramis pulled the bandage away and inspected his side. \'93It\'92s healed.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Aye,\'94 Darrick said. \'93As are the wounds that I suffered last night. But such healing comes with a price. While I do it, Kabraxis has greater access to me. Only Hauklin\'92s sword keeps me sane and human.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You\'92ve healed me more quickly and better than any healer or potion I\'92ve ever used,\'94 Taramis said. \'93You could be a great asset.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But to whom?\'94 Darrick asked. \'93And at what cost? Perhaps Kabraxis has given me this power so that I will continue to use it and grow closer and closer to him.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Then what will you do?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Darrick answered. \'93I know I need to get away from here. I need the sea again for a time, Taramis. Something to clear my head. I need to find good, honest work again, a sailor\'92s life, so I won\'92t have so much time to think.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Believe in the Light,\'94 Taramis said. \'93The Light always shows you the way even in the darkest times.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\qc\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f0\fs20 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\qc\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f2\fs24 ***
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint359}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint359}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Hours later, with the sun now in the west out over the ocean and a ship\'92s passage secured, Darrick stood on the Bramwell docks. Taramis and the other demon hunters joined him, agreeing to take at least this much of the voyage together.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The docks were congested, people milling around like cattle being herded onto cargo ships. The waves pressed the ships up against the dock pilings, causing sonorous booms to echo over the dockyards.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Without warning, a woman\'92s shrill scream punctuated the noise.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Halfway up the gangplank leading onto the ship he\'92d booked passage on, Darrick turned and looked back.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Men hauled a young girl from the water, her body torn and shattered in her long dress.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  An older woman, probably her mother, knelt beside the little girl as the sailors stretched her out on the docks. \'93Please,\'94 the woman begged. \'93Can someone help my little girl? Is there a healer here?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93A healer wouldn\'92t do that one any good,\'94 a gruff sailor beside Darrick said. \'93That little girl had the ill luck to fall between the ship an\'92 the pilin\'92s as she was boardin\'92. Smashed her up inside. Ain\'92t nobody gonna be able to do anything about that. She\'92s dead, just waitin\'92 for it to come callin\'92.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick looked at the frail girl, her body busted up from the impact, drenched and in horrible pain.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Darrick,\'94 Taramis said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  For a frozen moment, Darrick remained on the boardwalk. What if the little girl\'92s accident was no accident? What if it was a temptation arranged by Kabraxis to use the healing power again? What if someone in the crowd, a traveling Vizjerei or another wizard, recognized that Darrick\'92s power wasn\'92t given by the Light but from a demon spawn from the Burning Hells?
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Then Darrick was moving, vaulting from the gangplank and back to the shore. He shoved people from his path, feeling the old anger and intemperance surging within him. A moment more, and he was at the little girl\'92s side.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint360}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint360}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Her mother looked up at him, her face stained with frightened and helpless tears. \'93Can you help her? Please, can you help her?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The little girl was no more than six or seven, hardly older than one of Mat\'92s sisters the last time Darrick had seen her.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Ain\'92t no good,\'94 a man nearby whispered. \'93Seen people all squashed up like this before. That little girl\'92s as good as dead, she is.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Without a word, Darrick placed his hands on the girl\'92s body, feeling the broken bones shifting within her.\plain \f2\i\fs24 Please,\plain \f2\fs24 he thought, ignoring Kabraxis\'92s harsh whispers fouling the back of his mind. He wouldn\'92t let the demon\'92s words come forward, wouldn\'92t allow himself to understand them.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Power flowed through Darrick\'92s hands, pouring into the little girl. A long moment passed, then her body arched suddenly, and she stopped breathing. During that still moment, Darrick felt certain that Kabraxis had somehow betrayed him, had somehow made him cause the girl\'92s death instead of preventing it.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Then the girl opened her eyes, the clearest blue eyes Darrick thought he\'92d ever seen. She called for her mother and reached for her. The woman took up her child and hugged her to her breast fiercely.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93A healer,\'94 someone whispered.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93That\'92s not just a healer,\'94 someone else said. \'93He brought her back from the dead, he did. That little girl weren\'92t nothin\'92 more than a corpse, an\'92 he done brung her back like it was nothin\'92.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick pushed himself to his feet, suddenly ringed in by people who were curious and suspicious of him. He put his hand on his sword, barely resisting the impulse to draw the weapon and clear the path from him. In the back of his mind, he heard the demon laugh.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Taramis was suddenly at Darrick\'92s side, as were Rhambal and Palat. \'93Come on,\'94 the sage urged.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93It\'92s the Prophet of the Light,\'94 someone else said. \'93He\'92s returned.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint361}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint361}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 another said. \'93Those are the people who killed the Wayfinder and destroyed the Way of Dreams. Hang them!\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93We\'92ve got to go,\'94 Taramis said.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Was this what Kabraxis wanted? Darrick wondered. Would his death at the hands of a lynch mob allow the demon to step back into the world of men? Darrick didn\'92t know.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The mother rose to his defense, holding her child to her. \'93Don\'92t you men dare touch him. He brought my little Jenna back to me. If he is the one who killed the Wayfinder, then he had to have done it for good cause, says I. This man is a miracle worker, a chosen one of the Light.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93The Wayfinder was leading you to demons,\'94 Taramis said. \'93If he had not killed the servant of the false Prophet of the Light, all of you would have been doomed to the Burning Hells.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick felt sickened. He was no hero, and he was no saint. He forced himself to release his tight hold on Stormfury.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Grudgingly, the lynch mob mentality gave way, surrendering to the people who were looking for something to make sense out of all they had been through with the Church of the Prophet of the Light.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  In amazement, Darrick watched as people came forward with wounded friends and family, beseeching him to heal them. He turned to Taramis. \'93What do I do?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  The sage gazed at him. \'93The choice is yours. You can board that ship and tend to your own needs as best you can, or you can stay here in this moment and tend the needs of others.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Darrick looked out over the huge crowd. \'93But there are so many.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Already two dozen litters with men and women lying near death were spread across the docks. People called out to him, begging him to aid their fallen family and comrades.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93But the power I have,\'94 Darrick said, \'93it isn\'92t from the Light.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart RichViewCheckpoint362}{\*\bkmkend RichViewCheckpoint362}
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93No,\'94 Taramis agreed. \'93Listen to me, though. How do you know that in this moment the Light hasn\'92t had a design in placing you exactly in the position you find yourself in now?\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93I\'92m tainted with the demon.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93You also possess a demon\'92s great power, and you can do a lot of good with it if you choose.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93And what if in using that power I also lose myself?\'94 Darrick asked.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  \'93Life is about balance,\'94 Taramis said. \'93Balance between the Light and the Dark. I would not be able to champion the will of the Light so strongly, so willingly, had I not been exposed to the Darkness that waits to devour us in the Burning Hells. Just as steel must be tempered, Darrick, so must a man. You\'92ve come a long way. Your present is balanced between your past and the dreams you might have. You stand between the Light and the Dark as Kabraxis\'92s gateway, but it is your choice to remain open or closed. Your choice to hide the power or to use it. You can fear it or embrace it. Either way, it has already changed your life forever.\'94
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0  Quietly, thoughts racing inside his head, the demon whispering somewhere at the back, Darrick looked at the crowd that waited so expectantly. Then, taking a deep breath, he went forward to meet his future, his head high, no one\'92s unloved bastard child anymore but a man of compassion and conviction. He went to the wounded and the dying, and he healed them, listening to the demon scream at the back of his mind.
\par \pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f0\fs20\cf1 
